raphy.aspx?mpsno=62 |title=Botcha Satyanarayana at Lok Sabha |access-date=5 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023040/http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/members/former_Biography.aspx?mpsno=62 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Bulusu Sambamurti]], was an Indian lawyer, politician and freedom-fighter\n* [[Chaganti Somayajulu]], Telugu writers.\n* [[Dwaram Bhavanarayana Rao]], musicologist and Principal of [[Maharajah's Government College of Music and Dance]].\n* Dr. D. N. Rao\n* Justice [[E. Venkatesam]], former Judge of [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/evj.html |title=Biodata of Justice E. Venkatesam at Andhra Pradesh High Court. |access-date=13 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202254/http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/evj.html |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Justice [[G. Ramanujulu Naidu]], former Judge of [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/grnj.html |title=Profile of G. Ramanujulu Naidu at Andhra Pradesh High Court. |access-date=13 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317060433/http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/grnj.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Ganti Jogi Somayaji]], Telugu scholar and faculty in [[Andhra University]].\n* Ganti Prasada Rao, electrical engineering and systems science scholar, researcher and academician.\n* [[Gidugu Venkata Ramamurthy]], the father of Colloquial Telugu language movement.\n* [[Gurazada Apparao]], poet.\n* [[Indukuri Ramakrishnam Raju]], better known as [[Rajashri]], dialogue and lyrics writer in Telugu cinema.<ref>Rajashri, 20th Century Telugu Luminaries, Part II, Potti Sriramulu Telugu University, Hyderabad, 2005, pp: 481-2.</ref>\n* [[J. V. Somayajulu]], theater and film actor.\n* Justice [[K. Punnayya]], former Judge of [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]] and [[Member of Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/kpj.html |title=Profile of K. Punnayya at Andhra Pradesh High Court. |access-date=13 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192503/http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/kpj.html |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Dr. K. S. R. Krishna Rao\n* General [[K. V. Krishna Rao]], former [[Chief of the Army Staff (India)|Chief of the Army Staff]] of the [[Indian Army]].\n* [[Kala Venkata Rao]], freedom fighter and politician.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dspace.vidyanidhi.org.in:8080/dspace/bitstream/2009/4764/6/AND-1996-041-5.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721183049/http://dspace.vidyanidhi.org.in:8080/dspace/bitstream/2009/4764/6/AND-1996-041-5.pdf |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Kandala Subrahmanyam]], lawyer and [[Member of Parliament]] from Vizianagaram constituency.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/biodata_1_12/1049.htm |title=Biodata of Shri Kandala Subrahmanyam at Lok Sabha website. |access-date=2 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180818/http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/biodata_1_12/1049.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Kotcherlakota Rangadhama Rao]], Indian Physicist.\n* [[M. V. Narayana Rao]], Chief of [[Crime Investigation Department (India)|Crime Investigation Department]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cidap.gov.in/htmlfiles/chiefs.html |title=List of CID Chiefs. |access-date=4 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021061811/http://www.cidap.gov.in/htmlfiles/chiefs.html |archive-date=21 October 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[N. Dilip Kumar]], Chief of Anti-Corruption Branch.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/105619/Cover%20Story/n-dilip-kumar.html]</ref>\n* [[Nyapathi Kameswari]] better known as Radio Akkayya.\n* P. L. N. Raju\n* [[P. V. Ramanaiah Raja]], founder of [[Sri Raja-Lakshmi Foundation]].\n* Major General P. V. Ramanaiah\n* [[Pappu Venugopala Rao]], musicologist.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pappuvenugopalarao.com/ |title=Official website of Pappu Venugopala Rao |access-date=3 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007145518/http://pappuvenugopalarao.com/ |archive-date=7 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Justice [[Penmetsa Satyanarayana Raju]] former [[Chief Justice]] of [[Andhra Pradesh High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/psrj.html |title=Profile of P. Satyanarayana Raju at Andhra Pradesh High Court. |access-date=18 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227061607/http://hc.ap.nic.in/aphc/psrj.html |archive-date=27 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Pulapaka Seethapathi Rao]], CEO of [[State Bank of Hyderabad]] during 1965\u201370\n* Prof. (Dr.) Pyla Narayana Rao, Faculty at School of Corporate Law, Indian Institute of Corporate Affairs (IICA), New Delhi.\n* Justice [[T. V. R. Tatachari]], [[Chief Justice]] of [[Delhi High Court]].<ref>[http://delhihighcourt.nic.in/ Biodata of T. V. R. Tatachari at Delhi High Court website.]</ref>\n* V. R. Panthulu\n* [[Vasantha Rao Venkata Rao]], Physics teacher\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n17. Profile of Dr. Pyla Narayana Rao at http://www.iica.in/\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mracollegevzm.com/ Official website]\n\n{{coord missing|Andhra Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Colleges in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Vizianagaram district]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1879]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Uttarandhra]]\n[[Category:Colleges affiliated to Andhra University]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maharajah%27s_College"}
{"title_page": "2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cup bids", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''bidding process for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups''' was the process by which the [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA) selected locations for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s. The process began officially in March 2009; eleven bids from thirteen countries were received, including one which was withdrawn and one that was rejected before FIFA's executive committee voted in November 2010. Two of the remaining nine bids applied only to the 2022 World Cup, while the rest were initially applications for both. Over the course of the bidding, all non-European bids for the 2018 event were withdrawn, resulting in the exclusion of all European bids from consideration for the 2022 edition.  By the time of the decision, bids for the 2018 World Cup included [[England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|England]], [[Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Russia]], a joint bid from [[Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Belgium and Netherlands]], and a joint bid from [[Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Portugal and Spain]]. Bids for the 2022 World Cup came from [[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Australia]], [[Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Japan]], [[Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Qatar]], [[South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|South Korea]], and the [[United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|United States]]. [[Indonesian 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Indonesia's bid]] was disqualified due to lack of governmental support, and Mexico withdrew its bid for financial reasons.\n\nOn 2 December 2010, Russia and Qatar were selected as the locations for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups respectively. The selection process involved several controversies. Two members of the [[FIFA Executive Committee]] had their voting rights suspended following allegations that they would accept money in exchange for votes. More allegations of vote buying arose after Qatar's win was announced. Eleven of the 22 committee members who voted on the 2018 and 2022 tournaments have been fined, suspended, banned for life or [[2015 FIFA corruption case|prosecuted]] for corruption.\n\n== Background ==\nIn October 2007, FIFA ended its continental rotation policy. Instead countries that are members of the same confederation as either of the last two tournament hosts are ineligible, leaving [[Confederation of African Football|Africa]] ineligible for 2018 and [[CONMEBOL|South America]] ineligible for both 2018 and 2022.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7067187.stm |work=BBC News |date= 29 October 2007 |accessdate=29 October 2007|title= Fifa abandons World Cup rotation | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071030043406/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7067187.stm| archivedate= 30 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> Other factors in the selection process include the number of suitable stadiums, and their location across candidate nations. Voting is done using a multiple round [[exhaustive ballot]] system whereby the candidate receiving the fewest votes in each round is eliminated until a single candidate is chosen by the majority.\n\n=== Rotation policy ===\n[[File:World Map FIFA2.svg|thumb|FIFA's confederations]]\n\nFollowing the selection of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] hosts, FIFA had decided on a policy for determining the hosts of future editions. The six world confederations\u2014roughly corresponding to continents\u2014would rotate in their turn of providing bids, for a specific edition, from within their member national associations. This system was used only for the selection of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] (South Africa) and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] (Brazil) hosts, open only to [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] and [[CONMEBOL]] members, respectively.\n\nIn September 2007, the rotation system came under review, and a new system was proposed which renders ineligible for bidding only the last two World Cup host confederations.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7013110.stm |title= New rotation proposal |work=BBC Sport |date= 25 September 2007 |accessdate=22 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071011155608/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7013110.stm| archivedate= 11 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> This proposal was adopted on 29 October 2007, in [[Zurich]], Switzerland by FIFA's Executive Committee. Under this policy, a 2018 bid could have come from [[CONCACAF]], [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]], [[UEFA]], or [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]], as Africa and South America are ineligible.<ref name=iht>{{cite news |url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/australia-can-host-world-cup/2005/09/17/1126750168444.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title= Australia can host World Cup |first= Matthew |last= Hall |date= 18 September 2005|accessdate=22 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071022203403/http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/australia-can-host-world-cup/2005/09/17/1126750168444.html| archivedate= 22 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> Likewise, no CONMEBOL member could have made a 2022 bid, and candidates from the same confederation as the successful 2018 applicant would be disregarded in the 2022 selection procedure.\n\nThe United States, the last non-European candidate in the 2018 bidding cycle, withdrew its bid for that year; hence the 2018 tournament will have to be held in UEFA. This in turn meant that CONMBEBOL and UEFA were ineligible for 2022.\n\n== Voting procedure ==\nFor both the 2018 and 2022 editions of the World Cup, the [[FIFA Executive Committee]] voted to decide which candidate should host the tournament. The multiple round exhaustive ballot system was used to determine the tournament host. All eligible members of the FIFA Executive Committee had one vote. The candidate country that received the fewest votes in each round was eliminated until a single candidate was chosen by the majority. In the event of a tied vote, FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] would have had the deciding vote. There are twenty-four members on the Committee, but two of those were suspended due to accusations of [[Electoral fraud|selling votes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SPORT/football/12/02/football.world.cup.2018.2022/index.html?hpt=T1|title=Russia, Qatar win race to host World Cups as FIFA spreads its vision|date=2 December 2010|publisher=CNN|accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Schedule ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Notes{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n|-\n|15 January 2009\n|Applications formally invited\n|-\n|2 February 2009\n|Closing date for registering intention to bid\n|-\n|16 March 2009\n|Deadline to submit completed bid registration forms\n|-\n|14 May 2010\n|Deadline for submission of full details of bid\n|-\n|19 July 2010\n|Four-day individual applicant inspections begin\n|-\n|17 September 2010\n|Inspections end<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/newsid=1210979.html |publisher=FIFA.com |title=FIFA receives bidding documents for 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729211034/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/newsid%3D1210979.html |archivedate=29 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|2 December 2010\n|FIFA appointed hosts for 2018 and 2022 World Cups\n|}\n\n== 2018 bids ==\nEleven bids were submitted in March 2009 covering thirteen nations, with two joint bids: Belgium-Netherlands and Portugal-Spain. Mexico also submitted a bid, but withdrew theirs on 28 September 2009, while Indonesia had their bid rejected for lack of government support on 19 March 2010.<ref name=reject/> Five of the remaining nine bids, South Korea, Qatar, Japan, Australia and United States were only for the 2022 World Cup, while all the others bid for both the 2018 and 2022 World Cups.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2009-12-03-2489687100_x.htm |title= Bid teams focus on 2018, 2022 WCup hosting prize |first= Graham |last= Dunbar |work=USA Today |date= 3 December 2009 |accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> However, since all of the bids for the 2018 World Cup were from European nations, and FIFA's rules dictate that countries belonging to confederations that hosted either of the two preceding tournaments are not eligible to host,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/administration/releases/newsid=625122.html#rotation+ends+2018 |title=Rotation ends in 2018 |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |work=FIFA.com |accessdate=10 October 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101002817/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/administration/releases/newsid%3D625122.html |archivedate=1 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> all UEFA bids were forced to be for 2018 only. Four bids came from the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC), four from Europe's [[UEFA]], and one from [[CONCACAF]]. It had also been reported on the FIFA website that Egypt was entering a bid, but the president of the [[Egyptian Football Association]] denied that any more than an inquiry in principle had been made.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/7867719.stm|work=BBC News |date= 3 February 2009  |accessdate=3 February 2009  |title= Egypt deny bid for 2022 World Cup | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090206114840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/7867719.stm| archivedate=6 February 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%; border:1px solid black; text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"5\" style=\"background:darkblue; color:white; border:1px solid black\"|[[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]<br>bids<br>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Belgium}}{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Belgium & Netherlands]]\n|rowspan=\"10\" colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-bottom:0px; border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black\" valign=\"middle\"|<center>[[File:Map of 2018 FIFA World Cup bids.svg|600px|middle]]</center>\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|England}} [[England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|England]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Russia}} '''[[Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Russia]]'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Portugal}}{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Portugal & Spain]]\n|-\n!rowspan=5 style=\"background:#5599ff; color:white; border:1px solid black\"|[[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]<br>bids<br>\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Australia]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Japan]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Qatar}} '''[[Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Qatar]]'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|South Korea]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; ; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|United States]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2 style=\"background:#a244ff; color:white; border-top:2px solid white; border:1px solid black\"|&nbsp;Cancelled&nbsp;<br>bids\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Indonesia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Indonesia]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; ; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[#Mexico|Mexico]]\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|darkblue|2018 bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#5599ff|2022 bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#a244ff|Cancelled bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#ff6600|Ineligible in 2018}}</center>\n|style=\"border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#d40000|Ineligible in both}}</center>\n|}\n</div>\n\n=== Belgium and the Netherlands ===\n{{Main|Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\n[[Alain Courtois]], a Belgian Member of Parliament, announced in October 2006 that a formal bid would be made on behalf of the three [[Benelux]] countries: Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg.<ref name=\"Benelux\">{{cite news\n|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=385813&cc=5901\n|title=Benelux trio to apply to host 2018 World Cup|date=16 October 2006 |work=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=18 October 2006}}</ref>\nIn June 2007 the three countries launched their campaign not as a joint bid in the manner of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|Korea-Japan World Cup in 2002]], but emphasising it as a common political organisation.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=441938\n|title= Benelux countries launch 2018 World Cup bid |work= ESPN |date= 27 June 2007 |accessdate=29 October 2007}}</ref> Luxembourg would not host any matches or automatically qualify for the finals in a successful Benelux bid, but would host a FIFA congress.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7095242.stm\n|work=BBC News |location=London\n|title= Benelux countries want World Cup |date= 14 November 2007 |accessdate=14 November 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071116110513/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7095242.stm| archivedate= 16 November 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nBelgium and the Netherlands registered their intention to bid jointly in March 2009.<ref name=twelve>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7863406.stm|title=Twelve nations bid for World Cup|work=BBC News| place=London | date=3 February 2009 }}</ref> A delegation led by the presidents of the [[Royal Belgian Football Association|Belgian]] and [[Royal Dutch Football Association|Dutch]] national football associations met [[FIFA]] president Sepp Blatter on 14 November 2007, officially announcing their interest in submitting a joint bid.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://fifa.com/worldfootball/releases/newsid=637931.html\n |title       = Associations of Belgium and the Netherlands officially announce interest in submitting joint bid\n |date        = 14 November 2007\n |accessdate  = 14 November 2007\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071115095252/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/releases/newsid%3D637931.html\n |archivedate = 15 November 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> On 19 March 2008 the delegation also met with [[UEFA]] President [[Michel Platini]] to convince him that it was a serious offer under one management. Afterwards they claimed to have impressed Platini, who supports the idea of getting the World Cup to Europe.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza.be/voetbal/1.273169 |title= Ons dossier maakte indruk bij Platini |date= 19 March 2008\n|work=sporza.be\n|language= Dutch |accessdate=23 March 2008}}</ref> Former French football international [[Christian Karembeu]] was presented as official counselor for the joint bid on 23 June 2009.\n\nA factor that was against the Benelux bid was the lack of an 80,000 capacity stadium to host the final.<ref name=\"race20090317\">{{cite news\n | title = The race to host World Cup 2018 and 2022\n | first = Marc\n | last = Vesty\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7856716.stm#netherlandsbelgium\n |work=BBC Sport\n | location = London\n | date = 17 March 2009\n }}</ref>\nHowever, the city council of Rotterdam gave permission in March 2009 for development of a [[De Kuip#De Nieuwe Kuip|new stadium]] with a capacity of around 80,000 seats to be completed in time for the possible World Cup in 2018.\nIn November 2009, the venues were presented. In Belgium, matches would have been played in 7 venues: [[Antwerp]], [[Bruges]], Brussels, [[Charleroi]], [[Genk]], [[Ghent]] and [[Li\u00e8ge]]. In the Netherlands, only five cities would host matches: [[Amsterdam]], [[Eindhoven]], [[Enschede]], [[Heerenveen]] and [[Rotterdam]], but both Amsterdam and Rotterdam would provide two stadiums. Eindhoven would function as the 'capital city' of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news\n |work=Sporza.be \n |location=Eindhoven \n |agency=Belga \n |url=http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/wk/091109_speelsteden_WK \n |language=Dutch \n |title=Belgi\u00eb krijgt zeven speelsteden op het WK 2018 \n |date=9 November 2009 \n |accessdate=9 November 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111111437/http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/wk/091109_speelsteden_WK \n |archivedate=11 November 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerfield24.com/world-cup-2018 |title=World Cup 2018|date=September 2010}}</ref> [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] was also jointly hosted by Belgium and the Netherlands.\n\n=== England ===\n{{Main|England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nOn 31 October 2007, [[The Football Association]] officially announced its bid to host the event.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/article2779563.ece\n|title=FA confirms 2018 World Cup Bid\n|work=The Times |location=London \n|date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2010\n |first=Rosemary\n |last=Bennett}}</ref> On 24 April 2008 England finalised a 63-page bid to host the 2018 World Cup, focusing on the development of football worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/sow/news;_ylt=AjRl4htjIVNdu.daSX4XAgQmw7YF?slug=ap-england-2018worldcup&prov=ap&type=lgns\n|title= England plans its 2018 World Cup bid |work= [[Yahoo!]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2008}}</ref> On 27 January 2009, England officially submitted their bid to FIFA.<ref name=jointfail>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7832150.stm\n|title=England submit 2018 World Cup bid\n|date=27 January 2009 |work=BBC Sport|location=London|accessdate=28 January 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090119000948/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7832150.stm| archivedate= 19 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n[[Richard Caborn]] led England's bid to stage the event after stepping down as Sports Minister.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6249864.stm |title= Caborn to spearhead World Cup bid |work=BBC Sport |location=London |date= 28 June 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref> On 24 October 2008 the [[The Football Association|Football Association]] named the Executive Board to prepare the bid, with [[David Triesman, Baron Triesman|David Triesman]] as the bid chairman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/NewsFromTheFA/Postings/WorldCup2018_execboard.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20081015042409/http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/NewsFromTheFA/Postings/WorldCup2018_execboard.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 October 2008 |title= Board confirmed for 2018 |publisher= [[The Football Association]] |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=24 October 2008}}</ref> Triesman resigned on 16 May 2010 after comments were published where he suggested that Spain would drop their bid if Russia helped bribe referees in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], and was then replaced by [[Geoff Thompson (football)|Geoff Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/05/16/1928333/geoff-thompson-replaces-lord-triesman-as-england-2018-bid |title= Geoff Thompson Replaces Lord Triesman As England 2018 Bid Chief |work= Goal.com |date= 16 May 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2010 |first= Edward |last= Pearce| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100522021404/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/05/16/1928333/geoff-thompson-replaces-lord-triesman-as-england-2018-bid| archivedate= 22 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] backed the [[England 2018]] bid. In November 2005, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Gordon Brown]] and [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Sport Minister]] [[Tessa Jowell]] first announced that they were to investigate the possibility of bidding.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2005/press_96_05.cfm| title=Government launches work on 2018 bid| publisher=[[HM Treasury]] (press release) |date=18 November 2005|accessdate=29 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071005103020/http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2005/press_96_05.cfm| archivedate= 5 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThat month, [[Adrian Bevington]], [[the Football Association]]'s Director of Communications, announced the support of the Government and the Treasury in the bid, but put off definite proposals.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/11/England_WorldCup2018.htm |archive-url= https://archive.is/20080720013206/http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/11/England_WorldCup2018.htm |url-status= dead |archive-date= 20 July 2008 |publisher= Football Association |title= World Cup bid latest |date= 15 November 2005 |accessdate=27 October 2007}}</ref>\nBrown reiterated his support for a bid in March 2006, before England's 2006 World Cup campaign,<ref name=\"fa66\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/Wembley/NewsandFeatures/2006/wembley_commemorate_66|title=Heroes of '66 reunited|publisher= Football Association |accessdate=17 October 2010|date=21 March 2006|first=Mark |last=Whittle}}</ref> and again in May 2006.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www2.goldmansachs.com/insight/research/reports/docs/WCB2006.pdf| title= The World Cup and Economics 2006| publisher= [[Goldman Sachs]] research report| date= 3 May 2006| accessdate= 29 October 2007| format= PDF| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071029140706/http://www2.goldmansachs.com/insight/research/reports/docs/WCB2006.pdf| archivedate= 29 October 2007| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe UK government launched its official report on 12 February 2007, in which it was made clear that its support was for an England-only bid and that all games would be played at [[List of English football stadiums by capacity|English grounds]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/chancellor-s-world-cup-fever-fails-to-grip-the-scots-1-681878\n|last=Kirkup | first= James\n|title= Chancellor's World Cup fever fails to grip the Scots\n|work=The Scotsman \n|place=Edinburgh, UK |date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref> The venues selected on 16 December 2009 to form the bid were: London (three stadiums), [[Manchester]] (two stadiums), [[Birmingham]], Bristol, [[Leeds]], Liverpool, [[Milton Keynes]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Nottingham]], [[Plymouth]], [[Sheffield]] and [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8414235.stm|title=Milton Keynes part of England's 2018 World Cup bid|work=BBC Sport |date=6 December 2009 |accessdate=16 December 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091217032444/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8414235.stm| archivedate= 17 December 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[FIFA]] officials also expressed interest in an English bid. David Will, a vice-president of FIFA, noted England's World Cup proposal as early as May 2004.<ref name=\"will\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/click/rss/0.91/public/-/sport1/hi/football/3740851.stm\n| title=FIFA gives England hope |work=BBC News |place=London\n|date=23 May 2004|accessdate=29 October 2007}}</ref>\n[[Franz Beckenbauer]], leader of Germany's successful bid for the 2006 World Cup and a member of FIFA's Executive Committee, twice publicly backed an English bid to host the World Cup, in January and July 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6307237.stm\n|title= Beckenbauer will back England bid\n|work=BBC Sport |location=London |date= 28 January 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6921154.stm\n|title= England gets Beckenbauer backing |work=BBC Sport |date= 29 July 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\nFIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] said he would welcome a 2018 bid from \"the homeland of football.\"<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4208814.stm\n| title= Blatter Welcomes England Cup Bid |work=BBC Sport | date= 2 September 2005| accessdate=30 October 2007}}</ref>\nBlatter met David Cameron on two occasions to discuss the bid while paying visits to England. The British Prime Minister showed much support for the bid and was hopeful that the \"home of football\" would host the tournament.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/06/digger-david-cameron-sepp-blatter\n|title= Prime minister to back 2018 World Cup bid in talks with Sepp Blatter\n|date= 23 October 2007\n|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=28 October 2007\n|first=Matt\n|last=Scott}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview the leader of Russia's bid, Alexei Sorokin, criticised England's bid citing London's high crime rate, alcohol consumption among young people and English fans \"inciting ethnic hatred.\" England filed a complaint, though the complaint was withdrawn following Russia's apology.\n\n=== Portugal and Spain ===\n{{Main|Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nThe President of the [[Portuguese Football Federation]] (FPF), Gilberto Madail, first proposed a joint bid with Spain in November 2007.<ref name=\"telegraph20071127\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=A1YourView&xml=/sport/2007/11/27/sfnwcp127.xml \n |last=Bond \n |first=David \n |work=The Daily Telegraph \n |place=London, UK \n |date=27 November 2007 \n |title=Portugal and Spain to Launch Rival 2018 Bid \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226173847/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=A1YourView&xml=%2Fsport%2F2007%2F11%2F27%2Fsfnwcp127.xml \n |archivedate=26 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=485193&cc=3888\n|title= Iberian threat to England's 2018 World Cup bid\n|work= ESPN |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071201142734/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=485193&cc=3888| archivedate= 1 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> The bid intent was confirmed by [[FIFA]] president, [[Sepp Blatter]], on 18 February 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://www.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1090960.html\n|title=Espa\u00f1a y Portugal se unen para pedir el Mundial de 2018\n|last= Brotons |first=Pablo\n|work= [[Diario Marca|Marca]] |location=Madrid\n|date= 18 February 2008 |accessdate=18 February 2008 |language= Spanish}}</ref>\nHowever, the president of the [[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] (RFEF), Angel Villar, announced in July 2008 that it was Spain's intention to submit an individual World Cup bid, and that positive contacts had already taken place with the government, through the secretary of sports, [[Jaime Lissavetzky]]. No specifications were made then regarding a joint bid with Portugal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Villar/confirma/contactos/Lissavetzky/organizar/Mundial/2018/elpepudep/20080716elpepudep_10/Tes\n|title=Villar confirma contactos con Lissavetzky para organizar el Mundial 2018\n|work= [[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Madrid\n |date= 16 July 2008 |accessdate=16 July 2008 |language= Spanish}}</ref> On 23 November 2008, after his re-election for the RFEF presidency, Villar pledged that one of the fundamental objectives of his term was to bring a World Cup to Spain. While he did not mention whether Spain would present a joint bid with Portugal, he did not rule it out when asked about it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/88/spain/2008/12/23/1026578/spain-portugal-confirm-2018-world-cup-bid|title=Spain-Portugal Confirm 2018 World Cup Bid|date=23 December 2010|work=Goal|accessdate=23 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 December 2008, Angel Villar restated \"We need to present a strong, consistent and winning bid for the 2018 World Cup.\" He further confessed \"Personally, I think it should be with Portugal.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/12/23/sports/SOC-WCup-Spain-Portugal-2018-Bid.php\n|title= Spain eyes joint 2018 World Cup bid with Portugal\n|work= International Herald Tribune\n|location=Paris\n |date= 23 December 2008 |accessdate=23 December 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090204023957/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/12/23/sports/SOC-WCup-Spain-Portugal-2018-Bid.php| archivedate= 4 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Subsequently, in the aftermath of a RFEF meeting board, Spain and Portugal announced their intention to bid together.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1194477.html\n|title= La RFEF concreta su candidatura conjunta al Mundial 2018 |work= [[Diario Marca|Marca]]\n|location=Madrid\n|date= 23 December 2008  |accessdate=23 December 2008  |language= Spanish<!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Spanish sports newspaper ''[[Diario Marca|Marca]]'' advanced some details about the potential bid: Spain would lead a twelve-stadium project with eight of the venues, and the opening and final games would be held in [[Lisbon]] and [[Madrid]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1353757&idCanal=56| location= Lisbon| title= Candidatura ib\u00e9rica ao Mundial 2018 prev\u00ea abertura em Lisboa e final em Madrid| work= [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]| date= 20 December 2008| accessdate= 23 December 2008| language= Portuguese| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205184203/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1353757&idCanal=56| archivedate= 5 February 2009| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Spain has previously hosted the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]], while Portugal organised the [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]].\n\n=== Russia ===\n{{Main|Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nRussia announced its intent to bid in early 2009, and submitted its request to FIFA in time.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7838233.stm |title= Russia enters race to host 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date= 20 January 2009 |accessdate=15 October 2009}}</ref> Russia's President [[Vladimir Putin]] took a keen interest in the bid and ordered Vitaly Mutko, the Minister of Sports, to \"prepare a bid for Russia to hold the 2018 World Cup\". According to a report earlier submitted by Vitaly Mutko, who also served that time as President of the [[Russian Football Union]] (RFU), the country was ready to spend some $10.1 billion on the tournament.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Putin orders sports minister to prepare bid for 2018 World Cup\n | url = http://en.rian.ru/sports/20090505/121448011.html\n | work = RIA Novosti\n | location = [[Moscow]]\n | date =5 May 2009\n }}</ref> The bid committee also included RFU CEO Alexey Sorokin and Alexander Djordjadze as the Director of Bid Planning and Operations.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/bid-committee.aspx |title= Bid committee |work= Russia 2018\u20132022 Bid |date = October 2009|accessdate=15 October 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012020705/http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/bid-committee.aspx| archivedate= 12 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFourteen cities were included in the proposal, which divided them into five different clusters: one in the north, centered on [[Saint Petersburg]], a central cluster, centered on Moscow, a southern cluster, centered on [[Sochi]], and the Volga River cluster. Only one city beyond the Ural Mountains was cited, [[Yekaterinburg]]. The other cities were: [[Kaliningrad]] in the north cluster, [[Rostov-on-Don]] and [[Krasnodar]] in the south cluster and [[Yaroslavl]], [[Nizhny Novgorod]], [[Kazan]], [[Saransk]], [[Samara, Russia|Samara]] and [[Volgograd]] in the Volga River cluster.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/host-cities.aspx |title= Host cities |work= Russia 2018\u20132022 Bid |date = October 2009|accessdate=15 October 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091023181459/http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/host-cities.aspx| archivedate= 23 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> At the time of bidding, Russia did not have a stadium with 80,000 capacity, but the bid called for the expansion of [[Luzhniki Stadium]] in Moscow, already a [[UEFA Elite stadium]], from a capacity of slightly over 78,000 to over 89,000. Russia hoped to have five stadiums fit to host World Cup matches ready by 2013 \u2013 two in Moscow and one stadium each in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Kazan]] and [[Sochi]], which at the time was due to host the [[2014 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.rin.ru/eng/news///12466/7// |title= Russia ready to spend $10 bln on World Cup 2018 preparations |date = April 2009|accessdate=30 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n== 2022 bids ==\n\n=== Australia ===\n{{Main|Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nIn September 2007, the [[Football Federation Australia]] confirmed that Australia would bid for the 2018 World Cup finals.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/socceroos-stars-coming-home-for-two-matches/2006/09/21/1158431837576.html\n|agency=AAP\n|title= Socceroos' stars coming home for two matches |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 September 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071209231144/http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/socceroos-stars-coming-home-for-two-matches/2006/09/21/1158431837576.html| archivedate= 9 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nPreviously, in late May 2006, the [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] sports minister, [[Justin Madden]], said that he wanted his [[States of Australia|state]] to drive a bid to stage the 2018 World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://keobongda247.com/world-cup-2018.html |work=Keobongda247 Sports VietNam |title= news aggregator world cup 2018\n }}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> [[Frank Lowy]], the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] chairman, stated that they aimed to use [[List of sports venues in Australia|16 stadiums]] for the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23259207-5006068,00.html \n |last=Smithies \n |first=Tom \n |title=Lowy's vision for soccer \n |date=23 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205172915/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0%2C22049%2C23259207-5006068%2C00.html \n |archivedate=5 February 2009 \n |accessdate=13 May 2013 \n |work=The Daily Telegraph \n |place=Sydney \n}}</ref>\nFormer Australian Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] announced the Federal Government's support for the bid,<ref>{{cite news\n|last=Gilmore |first=Heath |author2=Proszenko, Adrian\n|url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/pm-makes-the-perfect-pitch-for-world-cup/2008/02/23/1203467452577.html |title= PM makes the perfect pitch for World Cup |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date= 28 February 2008 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref>\nand in December 2008, Federal minister for sport [[Kate Ellis]] announced that the federal government would give the FFA $45.6 million to fund its World Cup bid preparation.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = $45m for 2018 World Cup bid\n |url          = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24778844-12377,00.html\n |agency       = AAP\n |location     = Sydney\n |date         = 10 December 2008\n |access-date  = 12 December 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090206034706/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24778844-12377,00.html\n |archive-date = 6 February 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\nRudd met with Sepp Blatter to discuss the Commonwealth Government's support of the bid in Zurich in July 2009.<ref>[http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=8 Australian Bid Page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720083535/http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=8 |date=20 July 2009 }}.</ref>\n\nAt the 2008 FIFA Congress, held in Sydney, FIFA president Sepp Blatter suggested that Australia concentrate on hosting the 2022 tournament,<ref name=\"2022Bid\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/news/newsid=783630.html#joint+decision+2018+2022+fifa+world+cups \n |title=Joint decision on 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups \n |work=[[FIFA]] \n |date=30 May 2008 \n |accessdate=30 May 2008 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531132531/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/news/newsid%3D783630.html \n |archivedate=31 May 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> but Lowy responded by recommitting Australia to its 2018 bid.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/21/2281753.htm?section=sport\n|agency=AFP\n|title= FFA to press on with 2018 Cup bid: Lowy |date= 21 June 2008 |accessdate=21 June 2008 |work= [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080623012033/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/21/2281753.htm?section=sport| archivedate= 23 June 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> However, Australia ultimately withdrew from the bidding for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in favour of the 2022 FIFA World Cup on 10 June 2010, following comments from the chief of the [[Asian Football Confederation]] that the 2018 tournament should be held in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/australia/7818364/World-Cup-2010-Australia-pull-out-of-World-Cup-2018-bidding.html |title= World Cup 2010: Australia pull out of World Cup 2018 bidding |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date= 10 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010525/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/australia/7818364/World-Cup-2010-Australia-pull-out-of-World-Cup-2018-bidding.html| archivedate= 13 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/09/world-cup-2018-2022-europe |title= World Cup 2018 should be in Europe, says Asian Football Confederation |work=The Guardian |location=London |date= 10 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAustralia's largest stadiums are currently used by other major Australian sports whose domestic seasons overlap with the World Cup. The [[Australian Football League]] and [[National Rugby League]] claimed that loss of access to these major venues for eight weeks would severely disrupt their seasons and impact the viability of their clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770679.htm?site=sport&section=football |title=AFL concerns over world cup run deep. |accessdate=21 December 2009 |work=ABC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430034758/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770679.htm?site=sport&section=football |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/soccers-plan-to-displace-nrl/story-e6frexnr-1225808419104 |title=Soccer's plan to displace NRL |accessdate=21 December 2009 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Sydney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501021425/http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/soccers-plan-to-displace-nrl/story-e6frexnr-1225808419104 |archive-date=1 May 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The AFL in particular had previously advised it would not relinquish [[Docklands Stadium|Etihad Stadium]] in Melbourne for the entire period required.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/cup-bid-needs-to-share-the-vision-20091212-kpim.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Cup bid needs to share the vision | date=13 December 2009}}</ref> On 9 May 2010 the AFL, NRL, and FFA announced a Memorandum of Understanding guaranteeing that the AFL and NRL seasons would continue, should the bid be successful. Compensation for the rival football codes would be awarded as a result of any disruptions caused by hosting the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/rival-codes-finally-shake-hands-on-deal-to-play-through-world-cup-20100509-uluq.html |title= Rival codes finally shake hands on deal to play through World Cup |first= Brad |last= Walter |date= 10 May 2010 |accessdate=19 May 2010 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100512122253/http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/rival-codes-finally-shake-hands-on-deal-to-play-through-world-cup-20100509-uluq.html| archivedate= 12 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> AFL CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] came out in support of the bid, despite initially not supporting the bid.<ref>http://www.theage.com.au/comment/not-every-afl-point-was-a-goal-20140303-3409o.html</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad-application/world-cup-soccer-2020-decision/story-fn6bn88w-1225961153205 |title= World Cup soccer 2022 debate |first= Andrew |last= Demetriou |date= 26 November 2010 |accessdate=28 November 2010 |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia}}</ref> [[Franz Beckenbauer]] indicated that the issue of factional disputes between the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]], [[National Rugby League|NRL]] and, [[Australian Football League|AFL]] were not considered by the [[FIFA Executive Committee]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad-application/argy-bargy-no-threat-to-world-cup-bid/story-fn6bn647-1225961988679 |title= Argy-bargy no threat to World Cup bid |first= David |last= Davutovic |date= 28 November 2010 |accessdate=28 November 2010 |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia}}</ref> Although initially Australia seemed to be a popular contender to host the tournament, the final Australian World Cup bid received only one vote astonishing Franz Beckenbauer<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-12-04/beckenbauer-astonished-by-australia-snub/2362520</ref> and experts alike.\n\n=== Japan ===\n{{Main|Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nJapan bid to become the first Asian country to host the World Cup twice; however, the fact that they were co-hosts so recently in [[World Cup 2002|2002]] was expected to work against them in their bid.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = The race to host World Cup 2018 and 2022\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7856716.stm#japan\n |work=BBC Sport\n | location = London\n | date = 17 March 2009\n }}</ref> Although Japan did not have an 80,000-seat capacity stadium, its plan was based on a proposed 100,000-seat stadium that would have gone on to be a centrepiece of [[2016 Olympics]], for which [[Tokyo bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Tokyo]] was bidding.\n\nJapan also pledged that if it had been granted the rights to host the 2022 World Cup games, it would develop technology enabling it to provide a live international telecast of the event in [[3D television|3D]], which would allow 400 stadiums in 208 countries to provide 360 million people with real-time 3D coverage of the games projected on giant screens, captured in 360 degrees by 200 HD cameras. Furthermore, Japan will broadcast the games in holographic format if the technology to do so is available by that time. Beyond allowing the world's spectators to view the games on flat screens projecting 3D imaging, holographic projection would project the games onto stadium fields, creating a greater illusion of actually being in the presence of the players. Microphones embedded below the playing surface would record all sounds, such as ball kicks, in order to add to the sense of realism.\n\nThe Olympic bid was unsuccessful, coming third in the bidding process that concluded in October 2009. The Vice-President of the [[Japan Football Association]], Junji Ogura, had previously admitted that if Tokyo were to fail in its bid, its chances of hosting either the 2018 or 2022 World Cup would not be very good.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Japan World Cup bid rests on 2016 Olympic vote\n | first = Alastair\n | last = Himmer\n | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/olympicsNews/idUSSP35460420090123\n | work = Reuters\n | date = 22 January 2009\n | accessdate =5 December 2010\n }}</ref> On 4 May 2010, Japan announced that it was withdrawing its bid for the 2018 tournament to focus on 2022, amidst rising speculation that the 2018 edition will be held in Europe.<ref name=\"Japan 2018 withdrawal\">{{cite news | title = Japan drops bid to host 2018 World Cup to aim for 2022 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8659185.stm |work=BBC Sport | location = London | date = 3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Qatar ===\n{{Main|Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nQatar made a bid for only the 2022 World Cup. Qatar was attempting to become the first Arab country to host the World Cup. Failed bids from other Arab countries include [[Morocco]] (1994, 1998, 2006 and 2010), [[Egypt]] and a Libya-Tunisia joint bid withdrew in the [[2010 World Cup]] bidding process.<ref name=\"race20090317\"/>\nSheikh Mohammed bin Hamad bin Khalifa Al-Thani, son of the former [[Emir of Qatar]], was the chairman of the bid committee.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Qatar 2022 announces Bid Committee leadership \n |url=http://www.dubaichronicle.com/life/sport-life/qatar-2022-announces-bid-committee-leadership-7121 \n |work=Dubai Chronicle \n |date=25 March 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602051207/http://www.dubaichronicle.com/life/sport-life/qatar-2022-announces-bid-committee-leadership-7121 \n |archivedate=2 June 2009 \n}}</ref>\nQatar planned to promote the bid as an Arab unity bid and hoped to draw on support from the entire [[Arab world]] and were positioning this as an opportunity to bridge the gap between the Arab and Western worlds.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Qatar launch \"unity\" bid to stage 2022 World Cup finals\n | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=647154&sec=worldcup2010&&cc=5739\n | work = ESPN\n | date = 17 May 2009\n | accessdate =5 December 2010\n }}</ref> The bid launched an advertising campaign across the nation in November 2009.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rCt5n5iWTXU\n | title = Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid TV Commercial\n | date = 15 November 2009\n | work = YouTube\n }}</ref>\n\nSome concerns with Qatar's bid deal with the extreme temperatures.<ref name=cool>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/10093703.stm |title= Qatar pitches cool World Cup bid |first= Neil |last= Heathcote |work= [[BBC World News]] |date= 4 May 2010 |accessdate=7 May 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100507215907/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/10093703.stm| archivedate= 7 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The World Cup is always held in the European off-season in June and July and during this period the average daytime high in most of Qatar is in excess of 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (104&nbsp;\u00b0F), with the average daily low temperatures not dropping below 30&nbsp;\u00b0C (86&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/QAXX0003?from=36hr_bottomnav_business |title=Monthly Averages for Doha, Qatar |work=The Weather Channel |accessdate=26 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229115428/http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/QAXX0003?from=36hr_bottomnav_business |archive-date=29 December 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Sheikh Mohammed bin Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani, the 2022 Qatar bid chairman, responded saying \"the event has to be organised in June or July. We will have to take the help of technology to counter the harsh weather. We have already set in motion the process. A stadium with controlled temperature is the answer to the problem. We have other plans up our sleeves as well.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Qatar will be great host for WC 2022 \n |first=Raajiv \n |last=Tripathi \n |author2=Nag, Arindam \n |url=http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090325/content.asp?section=exclusive1_1 \n |work=Qatar Tribune \n |location=Doha \n |date=25 March 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329073540/http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090325/content.asp?section=exclusive1_1 \n |archivedate=29 March 2009 \n}}</ref> The first five proposed stadiums are planned to employ cooling technology capable of reducing temperatures within the stadium by up to 20 degrees Celsius. Additionally, the upper tiers of the stadiums will be dis-assembled after the World Cup and donated to countries with less developed sports infrastructure.<ref name=cool/>\n\nPresident of FIFA [[Sepp Blatter]] endorsed the idea of having a World Cup in the Middle East, saying in April 2010, \"The Arabic world deserves a World Cup. They have 22 countries and have not had any opportunity to organise the tournament.\" Blatter also praised Qatar's progress, \"When I was first in Qatar<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineqatar.com/visiting/qatar-world-cup-2022/qatar-world-cup-2022-an-overview|title=Qatar Worldcup 2022 Stadiums|publisher=OnlineQatar|author=Davies Krish|date=9 April 2019}}</ref> there were 400,000 people here and now there are 1.6 million. In terms of infrastructure, when you are able to organise the [[2006 Asian Games|Asian Games (in 2006)]] with more than 30 events for men and women, then that is not in question.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/sport/2010/04/2010424184010305993.html|title=Blatter reaches out to Arabia|work=Al Jazeera|date=25 April 2010|accessdate=1 May 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100429041252/http://english.aljazeera.net/sport/2010/04/2010424184010305993.html| archivedate= 29 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Qatar's bid to host the 2022 World Cup received a huge boost on 28 July 2010 when [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC) President [[Mohammed Bin Hammam]] threw his weight behind his country's campaign. Speaking in Singapore, Bin Hammam said: \"I have one vote and, frankly speaking, I will vote for Qatar but if Qatar is not in the running I will vote for another Asian country.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsfeatures.com/soccernews/story/47199/more-bad-news-for-australia-as-bin-hammam-talks-up-qatars-2022-bid.html |title=Bin Hammam talks up Qatar's 2022 bid |publisher=Sports Features Communications |date=28 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209222311/http://www.sportsfeatures.com/soccernews/story/47199/more-bad-news-for-australia-as-bin-hammam-talks-up-qatars-2022-bid.html |archivedate=9 December 2010 }}</ref> Qatar has already hosted the AFC Asian Cup in 1988, FIFA U-20 World Cup 1995 and the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]].\n\n=== South Korea ===\n{{Main|South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nSouth Korea bid only for the 2022 World Cup. They were bidding to become the first Asian country to host the World Cup twice; however, the fact that they were co-hosts so recently in 2002 was expected to work against them in their bid. [[Han Seung-joo]], a former [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade (South Korea)|South Korean Minister of Foreign Affairs]], was appointed as the Chairman of the Bidding Committee in August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kfa.or.kr/eng_kfa/news/news/view.asp?g_conid=2009827162321&g_gubun=1 |title=Han Sung-Joo Appointed as the Chairman of the Bidding Committee |work=[[Korea Football Association]] |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427083109/http://www.kfa.or.kr/eng_kfa/news/news/view.asp?g_conid=2009827162321&g_gubun=1 |archivedate=27 April 2011 }}</ref> He met with FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] in Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kr.news.yahoo.com/sports/npb/view?aid=20090926073606806i1 |script-title=ko:(\uc778\ud130\ubdf0) \ud55c\uc2b9\uc8fc \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5 \"\uad6d\uc81c \ucd95\uad6c\uacc4, 2022 \uc6d4\ub4dc\ucef5 \uc720\uce58 \uc758\uc0ac \ud658\uc601 |date= 26 September 2009 |accessdate=28 November 2009 |work= Yahoo! News Korea |language= Korean}}</ref> In January 2010, President [[Lee Myung-bak]] visited the headquarters of FIFA in [[Zurich]], Switzerland to meet Sepp Blatter in support of the South Korean bid.\n\nAlthough South Korea did not have an 80,000 capacity stadium, it planned to upgrade an existing venue to meet that capacity. There are three grounds which can seat over 60,000 people\u2014[[Seoul Olympic Stadium]], [[Seoul World Cup Stadium]] and [[Daegu Stadium]].  Another 70,000 seat [[Incheon Asiad Main Stadium|stadium]] is scheduled to be built in [[Incheon]] as the main stadium for the [[2014 Asian Games]]. Other venues meet hosting requirements as they were built for the 2002 World Cup.<ref name=\"race20090317\"/> The 12 cities selected to hold the finals were South Korea to win the bid were selected in March 2010 and were [[Busan]], [[Cheonan]], [[Daegu]], [[Daejeon]], [[Goyang]], [[Gwangju]], [[Incheon]] (2 venues), [[Jeonju]], [[Seogwipo]], [[Seoul]] (2venues), [[Suwon]] and [[Ulsan]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.worldfootballinsider.com/Story.aspx?id=33064 |title=Korea 2022 Reveals Host Cities |publisher=World Football Insider |date=4 March 2010 |accessdate=8 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100306150340/http://www.worldfootballinsider.com/Story.aspx?id=33064| archivedate= 6 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Main|United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\n[[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] first said in February 2007 that it would bid for the 2018 World Cup.<ref name=goff>{{cite news\n|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/19/AR2007021900914.html\n|title= U.S. to Seek World Cup\n| work= The Washington Post\n| first=Steven | last=Goff\n| date=20 February 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref> On 28 January 2009, U.S. Soccer then announced that it would submit bids for both the 2018 and 2022 Cups.<ref name=\"USA 2018-2022\">{{cite news\n|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=614052&sec=world&cc=5901\n|title=U.S. to bid for 2018 and 2022 World Cups\n|agency= Associated Press |work=[[ESPNsoccernet]] |location=Chicago |date=29 January 2009 | accessdate=29 January 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090131230810/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=614052&sec=world&cc=5901| archivedate= 31 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> David Downs, president of [[Univision]] Sports, was executive director of the bid. Other committee members included president of [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] [[Sunil Gulati]], U.S. Soccer chief executive officer Dan Flynn, [[Major League Soccer]] Commissioner [[Don Garber]], and Phil Murphy, the former national finance chairman for the [[Democratic National Committee]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/soccerinsider/2009/02/usa_in_18_or_22.html\n|title= USA in '18 (or '22) |first= Steve |last= Goff |work= The Washington Post\n|date= 2 February 2009 |accessdate=4 September 2009}}</ref> The vice president of FIFA, [[Austin \"Jack\" Warner|Jack Warner]], who is also the president of CONCACAF, originally said he would try to bring the World Cup back to the CONCACAF region.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/6939170.stm\n| title=Caborn hits back at Warner attack\n|work=BBC Sport | date=10 August 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\nHowever, Warner also stated that he preferred the USSF change their plans to make a bid for the 2022 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/8204792/Warner-wants-U.S.-to-bid-for-2022-World-Cup| title= Warner wants U.S. to bid for 2022 World Cup| work= [[Fox Sports (USA)]]| accessdate= 4 June 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080606193657/http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/8204792/Warner-wants-U.S.-to-bid-for-2022-World-Cup| archivedate= 6 June 2008| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, the bid committee identified 70 stadiums in 50 communities as possible venues for the tournament, with 58 confirming their interest.<ref name=\"70 stadiums\">{{cite news\n| title=2018 OR 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid Committee Contacts 70 US Venues\n| date=8 April 2009\n| url =http://soccer.teamusa.org/news/2009/04/08/2018-or-2022-fifa-world-cup-bid-committee-contacts-70-us-venues/11583\n| work = USA Soccer | accessdate =20 January 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/fifa-world-cup-2018-guide-to-the-12-host-stadiums\n|title=FIFA World Cup 2018: Guide to the 12 host stadiums\n|date=20 January 2018  |accessdate=20 January 2018 |publisher=Sportskeeda}}</ref> The list of stadiums was trimmed two months later to 45 in 37 cities,<ref name=\"45 stadiums\">{{Cite press release\n |title=USA Bid Committee Issues Requests For Proposals to 37 Potential FIFA World Cup Host Cities For 2018 or 2022 \n |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/articles/viewArticle.jsp_14876672.html \n |publisher=United States Soccer Federation \n |date=16 June 2009 \n |accessdate=18 June 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619071040/http://www.ussoccer.com/articles/viewArticle.jsp_14876672.html \n |archivedate=19 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> and then in August 2009 to 32 stadiums in 27 cities.<ref name=\"32 stadiums\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Federation-Services/2009/08/27-Cities-Chosen-For-World-Cup-Bid.aspx |title=USA Bid Committee Announces List of 27 Cities Still in Contention For Inclusion in U.S. Bid to Host FIFA World Cup in 2018 or 2022 |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=20 August 2009 |publisher=United States Soccer Federation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926202259/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Federation-Services/2009/08/27-Cities-Chosen-For-World-Cup-Bid.aspx |archivedate=26 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In January 2010, 18 cities and 21 stadiums were selected for the final bid. The cities were [[Atlanta]], [[Baltimore]], [[Boston]] ([[Foxborough, Massachusetts|Foxboro]]), [[Dallas]], [[Denver]], [[Houston]], [[Indianapolis]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Miami]], [[Nashville]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[San Diego]], [[Seattle]], [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] The cities with multiple qualifying stadiums were [[Los Angeles]], [[Seattle]], [[Dallas]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. With several large [[American football]] stadiums, the 21 venues were to have an average capacity of 77,000; none seated fewer than 65,000. Seven of the stadiums seat at least 80,000.<ref name=\"18 cities chosen\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.gousabid.com/news/entry/bid-committee-announces-official-bid-cities/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123191730/http://www.gousabid.com/news/entry/bid-committee-announces-official-bid-cities |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 January 2010 |title=Bid Committee announces official bid cities |date=12 January 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |publisher=The USA Bid Committee }}</ref> Two proposed stadiums would be used by [[Major League Soccer]] during the summer.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nIn October 2010, the United States withdrew from the 2018 bid process, to focus solely on the 2022 competition.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9097559.stm |title=US withdraw bid to host 2018 World Cup |date=15 October 2010 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n== Cancelled bids ==\nTwo countries had to cancel bids for the 2018 or 2022 FIFA World Cups before individual evaluations began. Mexico cancelled its bid for both cups, while Indonesia was only bidding for the 2022 World Cup.\n\n=== Indonesia ===\n{{Main|Indonesia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nIn January 2009 the [[Football Association of Indonesia]] (PSSI) confirmed their intention to bid for the 2022 FIFA World Cup, with government support.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/16/world-cup/2009/01/30/1084577/exclusive-indonesia-hosting-world-cup-is-not-impossible/\n|title=Exclusive: Indonesia \u2013 Hosting World Cup Is Not Impossible\n|work=Goal.com|date= 30 January 2009|accessdate=5 February 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090212095001/http://www.goal.com/en/news/16/world-cup/2009/01/30/1084577/exclusive-indonesia-hosting-world-cup-is-not-impossible/| archivedate= 12 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.detiksport.com/sepakbola/read/2009/01/29/095205/1076009/76/pemerintah-mendukung-penuh\n|title=Full Support from government for WC bid\n|work=detik.com\n|date= 29 January 2009|accessdate=5 February 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090203073548/http://detiksport.com/sepakbola/read/2009/01/29/095205/1076009/76/pemerintah-mendukung-penuh| archivedate= 3 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2009, PSSI launched the \"Green World Cup Indonesia 2022\" campaign.<ref name=\"hotland\">{{cite news\n |last=Hotland \n |first=Tony \n |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/02/10/indonesia-upbeat-host-green039-world-cup.html/ \n |title=Indonesia upbeat to host 'green' World Cup \n |work=The Jakarta Post \n |date=11 February 2009 \n |accessdate=11 February 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424191616/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/02/10/indonesia-upbeat-host-green039-world-cup.html/ \n |archivedate=24 April 2013 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\nThis campaign included a $1 billion plan to upgrade supporting infrastructure beside stadiums to meet FIFA's requirements. The funds to construct stadiums were to come from regional governments.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://bola.vivanews.com/news/read/28455-anggaran_infrastruktur_rp_10_triliun\n |title        = 10,000 million rupiahs for stadia constructions\n |work         = vivanews.com\n |date         = 9 February 2009\n |accessdate   = 6 September 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090918231601/http://bola.vivanews.com/news/read/28455-anggaran_infrastruktur_rp_10_triliun\n |archive-date = 18 September 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Indonesia had previously made World Cup history when it became the first Asian nation to play in a World Cup, at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938 tournament]] in France under its colonial name of the Dutch East Indies.<ref>{{cite news\n |agency      = Associated Press\n |url         = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/01/28/indonesia-joins-race-host-2018-2022-world-cup.html\n |title       = Indonesia joins race to host 2018, 2022 World Cup\n |work        = The Jakarta Post\n |date        = 28 January 2009\n |accessdate  = 5 September 2009\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090818140133/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/01/28/indonesia-joins-race-host-2018-2022-world-cup.html\n |archivedate = 18 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Indonesia also had tournament hosting experience as the co-host of [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]].\n\nIn the campaign presentation, PSSI president Nurdin Halid said he believed Indonesia stood a chance to win FIFA's approval to host the 2022 World Cup, despite the relatively poor infrastructure, coupled with the low quality of the national squad compared to other candidates. He said Indonesia had proposed a \"Green World Cup 2022\", hoping to capitalise on the current green and global warming movement worldwide: \"Our deforestation rate has contributed much to world pollution. By hosting the World Cup, we wish to build infrastructure and facilities that are environmentally friendly so we can give more to the planet.\"<ref name=\"hotland\"/>\n\nThe bid was launched at a moment when there were strong pressures from Indonesian football fans for Halid to step down from his position as chairman of PSSI. There was no official support from the government of Indonesia until 9 February 2010, the deadline for the country's government to file a letter of support for the bid.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indonesia's bid for 2022 World Cup in question |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/soccer/wires/02/08/2020.ap.soc.wcup.indonesia.bid.1st.ld.writethru.0227/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |date=9 February 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Secretary General of PSSI Nugraha Besoes did not deny that Indonesia could be disqualified from the bidding process because the Indonesian government did not support the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n |language= Indonesian\n | title = Indonesia Dicoret, Selamat Tinggal Piala Dunia\n | url = http://bola.kompas.com/read/xml/2010/03/10/08294818/Indonesia.Dicoret..Selamat.Tinggal.Piala.Dunia\n | work = Kompas.com\n | date = 10 March 2010|accessdate=11 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100325180708/http://bola.kompas.com/read/xml/2010/03/10/08294818/Indonesia.Dicoret..Selamat.Tinggal.Piala.Dunia| archivedate= 25 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On 19 March 2010, FIFA rejected Indonesia's bid to host the 2022 World Cup because the government stated that their concern is for the people of the country and so could not support the bid as FIFA requested.<ref name=reject>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8577452.stm |title= Indonesia's bid to host the 2022 World Cup bid ends |date= 19 March 2010 |accessdate=19 March 2010 |work=BBC Sport| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100320054013/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8577452.stm| archivedate= 20 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> As a consequence, PSSI threw their support behind Australia's bid for the 2022 tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=70 |title=Indonesia backs Australia's 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid |date=12 June 2010 |publisher=[[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid]] |accessdate=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614232611/http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=70 |archivedate=14 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\nFormer [[Mexican Football Federation]] President, Alberto de la Torre, announced their intention to bid for the cup in 2005, but was ineligible because of the rotation policy at that time.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n== Selection ==\n\n===Eligible voters===\n{{see also|2015 FIFA corruption case}}\n\n;FIFA President\n* [[Sepp Blatter]] (banned in 2015 for eight years by [[FIFA Ethics Committee]], amid a sweeping corruption investigation led by the U.S. in the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n\n;Senior Vice President\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Julio Grondona]] (died on 30 July 2014; indicted on 6 April 2020 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n;Vice Presidents\n* {{flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Issa Hayatou]]\n* {{flagicon|South Korea|1997}} [[Chung Mong-joon]]\n* {{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]] (indicted for corruption in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Angel Maria Villar]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Michel Platini]] (banned in 2015 for life from all football activities for ethics violations)\n* {{flagicon|England}} [[Geoff Thompson (football)|Geoff Thompson]]\n\n;Members\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}} \n* {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Michel D'Hooghe]]\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Ricardo Teixeira]] (indicted on 3 December 2015 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n* {{flagicon|Qatar}} [[Mohamed Bin Hammam]] (banned in 2011 for life from all football activities for ethics violations)\n* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Senes Erzik]]\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Chuck Blazer]] (plead guilty to corruption charges in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Thailand}} [[Worawi Makudi]] (banned in 2015 for five years for forgery and falsification)\n* {{flagicon|Paraguay|1990}} [[Nicolas Leoz]] (indicted for corruption in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Junji Ogura]]\n* {{flagicon|Cyprus}} [[Marios Lefkaritis]]\n* {{flagicon|Ivory Coast}} [[Jacques Anouma]]\n* {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Franz Beckenbauer]]\n* {{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[Rafael Salguero]] (indicted on 3 December 2015 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n* {{flagicon|Egypt}} [[Hany Abo Rida]]\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Vitaly Mutko]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n;Prevented from voting\n*{{flagicon|TAH}} [[Reynald Temarii]]<ref name=qa/>\n*{{flagicon|NGR}} [[Amos Adamu]]<ref name=qa>{{cite web|last1=Fylan|first1=Kevin|title=Q+A - Voting for the 2018 and 2022 World Cup hosts|url=http://uk.mobile.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKTRE6B01OI20101201|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=1 June 2014|date=1 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting rounds ===\n[[File:Russia 2018 World Cup.jpeg|right|thumb|Russian officials celebrate after being awarded the 2018 World Cup.]]\n{{further|FIFA World Cup hosts}}\n\nOn 2 December 2010, FIFA president [[Sepp Blatter]] announced the winning bids at FIFA's headquarters in Zurich. Russia was chosen to host the 2018 World Cup, and Qatar was chosen to host the 2022 World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/russia2018/news/newsid=1344698/index.html|title=Russia and Qatar awarded 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups|date=2 December 2010|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref> This made Russia the first [[Eastern Europe]]an country to host the World Cup, while Qatar would be the first Middle Eastern country to host the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/02/england-russia-win-2018-world-cup|title=England beaten as Russia win 2018 World Cup bid|date=2 December 2010|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=2 December 2010|first=Owen|last=Gibson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/02/qatar-win-2022-world-cup-bid|title=Qatar win 2022 World Cup bid|date=2 December 2010|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=2 December 2010|first=Jamie|last=Jackson}}</ref>\nBlatter noted that the committee had decided to \"go to new lands\" and reflected a desire to \"develop football\" by bringing it to more countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/03/sports/soccer/03worldcup.html?_r=1&hp|title=Russia and Qatar Win World Cup Bids|last=Longman|first=Jer\u00e9|work=New York Times|accessdate=2 December 2010|date=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn each round a majority of twelve votes was needed. If no bid received 12 votes in a round, the bid with the fewest votes in that round was eliminated, and accordingly each remaining bid should receive no fewer votes in subsequent rounds than in preceding rounds. The actual votes cast were as follows:<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/media/newsid=1344971.html |title=Russia and Qatar to host 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups, respectively |publisher=FIFA |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203003635/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/media/newsid%3D1344971.html |archivedate=3 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;\"\n|+ '''2018 World Cup host vote results'''\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Country\n! colspan=\"2\" | Vote\n|-\n! 1\n! 2\n|-bgcolor=#90EE90\n| align=left |  '''{{Flagu|Russia}}'''\n|9\n|'''13'''\n|- \n| align=left | {{Flagu|Spain}}/{{Flagu|Portugal}}\n| 7\n| 7\n|-\n| align=left  | {{Flagu|Netherlands}}/{{Flagu|Belgium}}\n| 4\n| 2\n|-\n| align=left  | {{ENG}}\n| 2\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n! align=left |Total Votes\n! 22\n! 22\n|}\n\n{{Col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;\"\n|+ '''2022 World Cup host vote results'''\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Country\n! colspan=\"4\" | Vote\n|-\n! 1\n! 2\n! 3\n! 4\n|- bgcolor=#90EE90\n| align=left | '''{{Flagu|Qatar}}'''\n|11\n|10\n|11\n|'''14'''\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|United States}}\n| 3\n| 5\n| 6\n| 8\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|South Korea}}\n| 4\n| 5\n| 5\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|Japan}}\n| 3\n| 2\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|Australia}}\n| 1\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n! align=left |Total Votes\n! 22\n! 22\n! 22\n! 22\n|}\n{{Col-end}}As can be observed from multiple bids that received fewer votes in voting round 2 compared to voting round 1 (Netherlands/Belgium, Qatar and Japan), at least 2 voting members in each of the 2018 and 2022 votes changed their votes between voting rounds despite their initial bid not being eliminated in voting round 1 (see '[[2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cup bids#Allegations of vote-buying|Allegations of vote-buying]]', below).\n\n===Allegations of vote-buying===\n{{see also|Garcia Report|2015 FIFA corruption case}}\n\nShortly after the voting in December 2010, [[ESPN]] published allegations linking Qatar's successful bid to Football Dreams, a youth development program that channeled money from the Qatari government to football programs in 15 countries in sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America and Southeast Asia\u2014six of which had representatives on the FIFA executive committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/5933045/how-qatar-became-player-world-soccer |title=Behind Qatar's football success |first=Brent |last=Latham |publisher=ESPN |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref> In February 2011, Blatter admitted that the Spanish and Qatari bid teams did try to trade votes, \"but it didn't work\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9387891.stm |work=BBC Sport |title=Sepp Blatter hints at 2022 summer World Cup in Qatar |quote=I'll be honest, there was a bundle of votes between Spain and Qatar. But it was a nonsense. It was there but it didn't work, not for one and not for the other side.|date= 7 February 2011 |accessdate=9 February 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110208203040/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9387891.stm| archivedate= 8 February 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, the former England 2018 bid chief [[David Triesman, Baron Triesman|Lord Treisman]] told a [[Select committees of the Parliament of the United Kingdom|House of Commons select committee]] that four FIFA committee members approached him asking for various things in exchange for votes. Among the accused were FIFA Vice President [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], who asked for \u00a32.5 million to be used for projects, and [[Nicol\u00e1s Leoz]], who allegedly asked to be knighted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/917869/lord-triesman-accuses-four-fifa-officials-of-impropriety |work=[[ESPN Soccernet]] |title=Triesman accuses four FIFA members |date=10 May 2011 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> ''The Sunday Times'' further reported that month that [[Issa Hayatou]] and [[Jacques Anouma]] were given $1.5 million in exchange for their votes in favor of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/918397/fifa-demands-evidence-of-corruption-|work=ESPN Soccernet|title=FIFA demands evidence of corruption|date=11 May 2011|accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> On 30 May 2011, [[FIFA President]] [[Sepp Blatter]] rejected the evidence in a press conference, while [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], who had been suspended that day for a separate ethics violations pending an investigation, leaked an email from FIFA General Secretary [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Valcke]] which suggested that Qatar had \"bought\" the rights to host the 2022 FIFA World Cup. Valcke subsequently issued a statement denying he had suggested it was bribery, saying instead that the country had \"used its financial muscle to lobby for support\". Qatar officials denied any impropriety.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/30/us-soccer-fifa-qatar-idUSTRE74T4J420110530 |title= Qataris brush off allegations of buying World Cup rights |agency=[[Reuters]] |first= Regan E. |last= Doherty |date= 30 May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> [[Theo Zwanziger]], President of the [[German Football Association]], also called on FIFA to re-examine the awarding of the Cup to Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13613314.stm |title= German Federation asks Fifa for inquiry into Qatar 2022 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date= 1 June 2011 |accessdate=1 June 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110601111502/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13613314.stm| archivedate= 1 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, FIFA appointed former U.S. Attorney [[Michael J. Garcia]] to investigate allegations of vote-buying in the selection process. He submitted [[Garcia Report|the report]] in September 2014, which FIFA at the time declined to release in full. Instead, FIFA released a summary that Garcia described as \"materially incomplete,\" leading Garcia to resign in protest. FIFA ultimately published the report in 2017, after German tabloid ''[[Bild]]'' announced they would publish a leaked copy. The report detailed dozens of allegations but didn't provide hard evidence for vote-buying.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/sports/fifa-garcia-report.html |title= In Long-Secret FIFA Report, More Details but No Smoking Gun |newspaper= The New York Times |first= Andrew |last= Keh |date= 27 June 2017 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> In May 2015, as members gathered in [[Z\u00fcrich]] for the [[65th FIFA Congress]], U.S. federal prosecutors disclosed cases of corruption leading to the arrest of seven. More than 40 individuals were indicted, including 2018 and 2022 voters [[Luis Bedoya]], [[Chuck Blazer]], [[Nicol\u00e1s Leoz]], [[Rafael Salguero]], [[Ricardo Teixeira]], and [[Jack Warner]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/03/sports/soccer/fifa-officials-indicted-for-corruption.html |title= The Soccer Officials Indicted on Corruption Charges |newspaper= The New York Times |date= 3 December 2015 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> The [[2015 FIFA corruption case|resulting cases]] led FIFA to suspend many members, including [[Issa Hayatou]], and the end of Sepp Blatter's presidency of the organization.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/03/sports/soccer/sepp-blatter-to-resign-as-fifa-president.html |title= Sepp Blatter Decides to Resign as FIFA President in About-Face |newspaper= The New York Times |first1= Sam |last1= Borden |first2= Michael S. |last2= Schmidt |first3= Matt |last3= Apuzzo |date= 2 June 2015 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[United States Department of Justice]] unsealed further indictments against voters Nicol\u00e1s Leoz, Ricardo Teixeira, [[Julio Grondona]] of Argentina, and Jack Warner. The indictments spelled out how both the Russian and Qatari bids used [[shell corporation]]s and sham consulting contracts to pay voters between $1\u20135&nbsp;million for their support.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.si.com/soccer/2020/04/06/world-cup-bribery-votes-2018-russia-2022-qatar-jack-warner |title= Indictment Reveals Details of Alleged Bribes for 2018, 2022 FIFA World Cup Votes |agency= Associated Press |website= Sports Illustrated |date= 6 April 2020 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> Other voters who had previously pleaded guilty to accepting bribes, including [[Rafael Salguero]] of Guatemala, aided in the indictments, which when included with previous cases, mean that more than half of the voters in the 2018 and 2022 selection have been accused of wrongdoing related to their votes.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/sports/soccer/qatar-and-russia-bribery-world-cup-fifa.html |title= U.S. Prosecutors Say Qatar and Russia Bribed FIFA Officials to Win World Cup Bids |newspaper= The New York Times |first1= Tariq |last1= Panja |first2= Kevin |last2= Draper |date= 6 April 2020 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> Voter [[Franz Beckenbauer]] has also been accused by Swiss prosecutors of embezzlement and money laundering related to voting in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup#Bribery and corruption allegations|2006 FIFA World Cup host selection]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dw.com/en/franz-beckenbauer-probe-to-be-split-from-world-cup-investigation/a-49654583 |title= Franz Beckenbauer probe to be split from World Cup investigation |newspaper= Deutsche Welle |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> while [[\u00c1ngel Mar\u00eda Villar]] was arrested in July 2017 for embezzlement, after previously being fined for failure to cooperate with investigations into vote-buying in the 2018 and 2022 host selection.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/27/angel-maria-villar-resigns-uefa-fifa-spain |title= \u00c1ngel Mar\u00eda Villar resigns from Uefa and Fifa positions after arrest in Spain |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 27 July 2017 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nIn reaction to the announcement there were celebrations on the streets of Doha.<ref>[[Al Jazeera English]]. 2 December 2010. 18:00 GMT.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9252710.stm|title=A World Cup miracle |date=2 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 December 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101203045716/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9252710.stm| archivedate= 3 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Qatar Stock Exchange]] responded strongly with increased participation in trading following the announcement.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-12/qatar-shares-head-for-2-year-high-on-growth-prospects-linked-to-world-cup.html | work=Bloomberg | first1=Zahra | last1=Hankir | first2=Ahmed | last2=Namatalla | title=Egypt Shares Gain on View Central Bank May Cut Interest Rates, Led by CIBE | date=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] told his Qatari counterpart that hosting the tournament \"is a big athletic event which can promote football in the Persian Gulf area and Middle East region.\" He also said Iran was ready to help Qatar in hosting the event, while saying he hoped its neighbours \"could achieve a reasonable share to attend the games.\" al-Thani \"underlined [a] necessity of cooperation between regional countries to use and take advantage of the sport opportunity.\" He also added that Qatar's initiative would motivate its neighbours to \"promote and develop their football.\"<ref>http://cms.mfa.gov.ir/cms/cms/Tehran/en/Ifrem/1898912{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nRoger Burden, who had been acting chairman of England's Football Association, withdrew his application for the permanent post days after the vote, saying he could not trust FIFA members due to their actions.<ref>[[BBC NEWS]]: [[Web News]], 4 December 2010.</ref> England's bid executive Andy Anson said \"I think it has to [change] because otherwise why would Australia, the United States, Holland, Belgium, England ever bother bidding again?\"<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/12/04/3084628.htm?section=justin 'Why bother': Australia warned against future Cup bids] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205023754/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/12/04/3084628.htm?section=justin |date=5 December 2010 }}, Rachael Brown, ABC News, 4 December 2010</ref>\n\nThere was also a backlash from the media in the losing countries; the majority of British newspapers alleged that the World Cup had been \"sold\" to Russia, and the Spanish ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'', Dutch ''[[Algemeen Dagblad]]'', and the Japanese ''[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun|Nikkei]]'' made comments about the financial power of Russia and Qatar's commodity and energy reserves.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9253692.stm |work=BBC News | title=English media angry at Fifa 'fix' | date=3 December 2010}}</ref> American newspapers the ''[[Seattle Times]]'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' alleged collusion and corruption.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*  [https://web.archive.org/web/20100615200629/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/index.html FIFA 2018/2022 site]\n\n{{Bids for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{FIFA World Cup bids}}\n{{2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{2022 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Portal bar|Association football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2018 And 2022 Fifa World Cup Bids}}\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup bids| ]]\n[[Category:2022 FIFA World Cup bids| ]]\n[[Category:2010\u201311 in Qatari football]]\n[[Category:2010 in Russian football|World Cup bids]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup bids]]\n[[Category:Football in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Russia at the FIFA World Cup]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''bidding process for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups''' was the process by which the [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA) selected locations for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s. The process began officially in March 2009; eleven bids from thirteen countries were received, including one which was withdrawn and one that was rejected before FIFA's executive committee voted in November 2010. Two of the remaining nine bids applied only to the 2022 World Cup, while the rest were initially applications for both. Over the course of the bidding, all non-European bids for the 2018 event were withdrawn, resulting in the exclusion of all European bids from consideration for the 2022 edition.  By the time of the decision, bids for the 2018 World Cup included [[England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|England]], [[Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Russia]], a joint bid from [[Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Belgium and Netherlands]], and a joint bid from [[Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Portugal and Spain]]. Bids for the 2022 World Cup came from [[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Australia]], [[Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Japan]], [[Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Qatar]], [[South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|South Korea]], and the [[United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|United States]]. [[Indonesian 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Indonesia's bid]] was disqualified due to lack of governmental support, and Mexico withdrew its bid for financial reasons.\n\nOn 2 December 2010, Russia and Qatar were selected as the locations for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups respectively. The selection process involved several controversies. Two members of the [[FIFA Executive Committee]] had their voting rights suspended following allegations that they would accept money in exchange for votes. More allegations of vote buying arose after Qatar's win was announced. Eleven of the 22 committee members who voted on the 2018 and 2022 tournaments have been fined, suspended, banned for life or [[2015 FIFA corruption case|prosecuted]] for corruption.\n\n== Background ==\nIn October 2007, FIFA ended its continental rotation policy. Instead countries that are members of the same confederation as either of the last two tournament hosts are ineligible, leaving [[Confederation of African Football|Africa]] ineligible for 2018 and [[CONMEBOL|South America]] ineligible for both 2018 and 2022.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7067187.stm |work=BBC News |date= 29 October 2007 |accessdate=29 October 2007|title= Fifa abandons World Cup rotation | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071030043406/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7067187.stm| archivedate= 30 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> Other factors in the selection process include the number of suitable stadiums, and their location across candidate nations. Voting is done using a multiple round [[exhaustive ballot]] system whereby the candidate receiving the fewest votes in each round is eliminated until a single candidate is chosen by the majority.\n\n=== Rotation policy ===\n[[File:World Map FIFA2.svg|thumb|FIFA's confederations]]\n\nFollowing the selection of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] hosts, FIFA had decided on a policy for determining the hosts of future editions. The six world confederations\u2014roughly corresponding to continents\u2014would rotate in their turn of providing bids, for a specific edition, from within their member national associations. This system was used only for the selection of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] (South Africa) and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] (Brazil) hosts, open only to [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] and [[CONMEBOL]] members, respectively.\n\nIn September 2007, the rotation system came under review, and a new system was proposed which renders ineligible for bidding only the last two World Cup host confederations.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7013110.stm |title= New rotation proposal |work=BBC Sport |date= 25 September 2007 |accessdate=22 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071011155608/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7013110.stm| archivedate= 11 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> This proposal was adopted on 29 October 2007, in [[Zurich]], Switzerland by FIFA's Executive Committee. Under this policy, a 2018 bid could have come from [[CONCACAF]], [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]], [[UEFA]], or [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]], as Africa and South America are ineligible.<ref name=iht>{{cite news |url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/australia-can-host-world-cup/2005/09/17/1126750168444.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title= Australia can host World Cup |first= Matthew |last= Hall |date= 18 September 2005|accessdate=22 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071022203403/http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/australia-can-host-world-cup/2005/09/17/1126750168444.html| archivedate= 22 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> Likewise, no CONMEBOL member could have made a 2022 bid, and candidates from the same confederation as the successful 2018 applicant would be disregarded in the 2022 selection procedure.\n\nThe United States, the last non-European candidate in the 2018 bidding cycle, withdrew its bid for that year; hence the 2018 tournament will have to be held in UEFA. This in turn meant that CONMBEBOL and UEFA were ineligible for 2022.\n\n== Voting procedure ==\nFor both the 2018 and 2022 editions of the World Cup, the [[FIFA Executive Committee]] voted to decide which candidate should host the tournament. The multiple round exhaustive ballot system was used to determine the tournament host. All eligible members of the FIFA Executive Committee had one vote. The candidate country that received the fewest votes in each round was eliminated until a single candidate was chosen by the majority. In the event of a tied vote, FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] would have had the deciding vote. There are twenty-four members on the Committee, but two of those were suspended due to accusations of [[Electoral fraud|selling votes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SPORT/football/12/02/football.world.cup.2018.2022/index.html?hpt=T1|title=Russia, Qatar win race to host World Cups as FIFA spreads its vision|date=2 December 2010|publisher=CNN|accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Schedule ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Notes{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n|-\n|15 January 2009\n|Applications formally invited\n|-\n|2 February 2009\n|Closing date for registering intention to bid\n|-\n|16 March 2009\n|Deadline to submit completed bid registration forms\n|-\n|14 May 2010\n|Deadline for submission of full details of bid\n|-\n|19 July 2010\n|Four-day individual applicant inspections begin\n|-\n|17 September 2010\n|Inspections end<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/newsid=1210979.html |publisher=FIFA.com |title=FIFA receives bidding documents for 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729211034/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/newsid%3D1210979.html |archivedate=29 July 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|2 December 2010\n|FIFA appointed hosts for 2018 and 2022 World Cups\n|}\n\n== 2018 bids ==\nEleven bids were submitted in March 2009 covering thirteen nations, with two joint bids: Belgium-Netherlands and Portugal-Spain. Mexico also submitted a bid, but withdrew theirs on 28 September 2009, while Indonesia had their bid rejected for lack of government support on 19 March 2010.<ref name=reject/> Five of the remaining nine bids, South Korea, Qatar, Japan, Australia and United States were only for the 2022 World Cup, while all the others bid for both the 2018 and 2022 World Cups.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2009-12-03-2489687100_x.htm |title= Bid teams focus on 2018, 2022 WCup hosting prize |first= Graham |last= Dunbar |work=USA Today |date= 3 December 2009 |accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> However, since all of the bids for the 2018 World Cup were from European nations, and FIFA's rules dictate that countries belonging to confederations that hosted either of the two preceding tournaments are not eligible to host,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/administration/releases/newsid=625122.html#rotation+ends+2018 |title=Rotation ends in 2018 |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |work=FIFA.com |accessdate=10 October 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101002817/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/administration/releases/newsid%3D625122.html |archivedate=1 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> all UEFA bids were forced to be for 2018 only. Four bids came from the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC), four from Europe's [[UEFA]], and one from [[CONCACAF]]. It had also been reported on the FIFA website that Egypt was entering a bid, but the president of the [[Egyptian Football Association]] denied that any more than an inquiry in principle had been made.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/7867719.stm|work=BBC News |date= 3 February 2009  |accessdate=3 February 2009  |title= Egypt deny bid for 2022 World Cup | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090206114840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/7867719.stm| archivedate=6 February 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%; border:1px solid black; text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"5\" style=\"background:darkblue; color:white; border:1px solid black\"|[[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]<br>bids<br>\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Belgium}}{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Belgium & Netherlands]]\n|rowspan=\"10\" colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-bottom:0px; border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black\" valign=\"middle\"|<center>[[File:Map of 2018 FIFA World Cup bids.svg|600px|middle]]</center>\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|England}} [[England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|England]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Russia}} '''[[Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Russia]]'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Portugal}}{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid|Portugal & Spain]]\n|-\n!rowspan=5 style=\"background:#5599ff; color:white; border:1px solid black\"|[[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]<br>bids<br>\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Australia]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Japan]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|Qatar}} '''[[Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Qatar]]'''\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px; border-top:0px\"|{{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|South Korea]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; ; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"|{{flagicon|United States}} [[United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|United States]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2 style=\"background:#a244ff; color:white; border-top:2px solid white; border:1px solid black\"|&nbsp;Cancelled&nbsp;<br>bids\n|style=\"border-top:1px solid black; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:0px\"|{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Indonesia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid|Indonesia]]\n|-\n|style=\"border-right:1px solid black; ; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"|{{flagicon|Mexico}} [[#Mexico|Mexico]]\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|darkblue|2018 bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#5599ff|2022 bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#a244ff|Cancelled bid}}</center>\n|style=\"border-right:0px; border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#ff6600|Ineligible in 2018}}</center>\n|style=\"border-left:0px; border-top:0px; border-right:1px solid black; border-bottom:1px solid black\"| <center>{{legend|#d40000|Ineligible in both}}</center>\n|}\n</div>\n\n=== Belgium and the Netherlands ===\n{{Main|Belgium\u2013Netherlands 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\n[[Alain Courtois]], a Belgian Member of Parliament, announced in October 2006 that a formal bid would be made on behalf of the three [[Benelux]] countries: Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg.<ref name=\"Benelux\">{{cite news\n|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=385813&cc=5901\n|title=Benelux trio to apply to host 2018 World Cup|date=16 October 2006 |work=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=18 October 2006}}</ref>\nIn June 2007 the three countries launched their campaign not as a joint bid in the manner of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|Korea-Japan World Cup in 2002]], but emphasising it as a common political organisation.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=441938\n|title= Benelux countries launch 2018 World Cup bid |work= ESPN |date= 27 June 2007 |accessdate=29 October 2007}}</ref> Luxembourg would not host any matches or automatically qualify for the finals in a successful Benelux bid, but would host a FIFA congress.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7095242.stm\n|work=BBC News |location=London\n|title= Benelux countries want World Cup |date= 14 November 2007 |accessdate=14 November 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071116110513/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7095242.stm| archivedate= 16 November 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nBelgium and the Netherlands registered their intention to bid jointly in March 2009.<ref name=twelve>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7863406.stm|title=Twelve nations bid for World Cup|work=BBC News| place=London | date=3 February 2009 }}</ref> A delegation led by the presidents of the [[Royal Belgian Football Association|Belgian]] and [[Royal Dutch Football Association|Dutch]] national football associations met [[FIFA]] president Sepp Blatter on 14 November 2007, officially announcing their interest in submitting a joint bid.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://fifa.com/worldfootball/releases/newsid=637931.html\n |title       = Associations of Belgium and the Netherlands officially announce interest in submitting joint bid\n |date        = 14 November 2007\n |accessdate  = 14 November 2007\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071115095252/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/releases/newsid%3D637931.html\n |archivedate = 15 November 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> On 19 March 2008 the delegation also met with [[UEFA]] President [[Michel Platini]] to convince him that it was a serious offer under one management. Afterwards they claimed to have impressed Platini, who supports the idea of getting the World Cup to Europe.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza.be/voetbal/1.273169 |title= Ons dossier maakte indruk bij Platini |date= 19 March 2008\n|work=sporza.be\n|language= Dutch |accessdate=23 March 2008}}</ref> Former French football international [[Christian Karembeu]] was presented as official counselor for the joint bid on 23 June 2009.\n\nA factor that was against the Benelux bid was the lack of an 80,000 capacity stadium to host the final.<ref name=\"race20090317\">{{cite news\n | title = The race to host World Cup 2018 and 2022\n | first = Marc\n | last = Vesty\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7856716.stm#netherlandsbelgium\n |work=BBC Sport\n | location = London\n | date = 17 March 2009\n }}</ref>\nHowever, the city council of Rotterdam gave permission in March 2009 for development of a [[De Kuip#De Nieuwe Kuip|new stadium]] with a capacity of around 80,000 seats to be completed in time for the possible World Cup in 2018.\nIn November 2009, the venues were presented. In Belgium, matches would have been played in 7 venues: [[Antwerp]], [[Bruges]], Brussels, [[Charleroi]], [[Genk]], [[Ghent]] and [[Li\u00e8ge]]. In the Netherlands, only five cities would host matches: [[Amsterdam]], [[Eindhoven]], [[Enschede]], [[Heerenveen]] and [[Rotterdam]], but both Amsterdam and Rotterdam would provide two stadiums. Eindhoven would function as the 'capital city' of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news\n |work=Sporza.be \n |location=Eindhoven \n |agency=Belga \n |url=http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/wk/091109_speelsteden_WK \n |language=Dutch \n |title=Belgi\u00eb krijgt zeven speelsteden op het WK 2018 \n |date=9 November 2009 \n |accessdate=9 November 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111111437/http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/wk/091109_speelsteden_WK \n |archivedate=11 November 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerfield24.com/world-cup-2018 |title=World Cup 2018|date=September 2010}}</ref> [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] was also jointly hosted by Belgium and the Netherlands.\n\n=== England ===\n{{Main|England 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nOn 31 October 2007, [[The Football Association]] officially announced its bid to host the event.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/article2779563.ece\n|title=FA confirms 2018 World Cup Bid\n|work=The Times |location=London \n|date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2010\n |first=Rosemary\n |last=Bennett}}</ref> On 24 April 2008 England finalised a 63-page bid to host the 2018 World Cup, focusing on the development of football worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/sow/news;_ylt=AjRl4htjIVNdu.daSX4XAgQmw7YF?slug=ap-england-2018worldcup&prov=ap&type=lgns\n|title= England plans its 2018 World Cup bid |work= [[Yahoo!]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=29 April 2008}}</ref> On 27 January 2009, England officially submitted their bid to FIFA.<ref name=jointfail>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7832150.stm\n|title=England submit 2018 World Cup bid\n|date=27 January 2009 |work=BBC Sport|location=London|accessdate=28 January 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090119000948/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7832150.stm| archivedate= 19 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n[[Richard Caborn]] led England's bid to stage the event after stepping down as Sports Minister.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6249864.stm |title= Caborn to spearhead World Cup bid |work=BBC Sport |location=London |date= 28 June 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref> On 24 October 2008 the [[The Football Association|Football Association]] named the Executive Board to prepare the bid, with [[David Triesman, Baron Triesman|David Triesman]] as the bid chairman.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/NewsFromTheFA/Postings/WorldCup2018_execboard.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20081015042409/http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/NewsFromTheFA/Postings/WorldCup2018_execboard.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 October 2008 |title= Board confirmed for 2018 |publisher= [[The Football Association]] |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=24 October 2008}}</ref> Triesman resigned on 16 May 2010 after comments were published where he suggested that Spain would drop their bid if Russia helped bribe referees in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], and was then replaced by [[Geoff Thompson (football)|Geoff Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/05/16/1928333/geoff-thompson-replaces-lord-triesman-as-england-2018-bid |title= Geoff Thompson Replaces Lord Triesman As England 2018 Bid Chief |work= Goal.com |date= 16 May 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2010 |first= Edward |last= Pearce| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100522021404/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2010/05/16/1928333/geoff-thompson-replaces-lord-triesman-as-england-2018-bid| archivedate= 22 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] backed the [[England 2018]] bid. In November 2005, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Gordon Brown]] and [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Sport Minister]] [[Tessa Jowell]] first announced that they were to investigate the possibility of bidding.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2005/press_96_05.cfm| title=Government launches work on 2018 bid| publisher=[[HM Treasury]] (press release) |date=18 November 2005|accessdate=29 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071005103020/http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2005/press_96_05.cfm| archivedate= 5 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nThat month, [[Adrian Bevington]], [[the Football Association]]'s Director of Communications, announced the support of the Government and the Treasury in the bid, but put off definite proposals.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/11/England_WorldCup2018.htm |archive-url= https://archive.is/20080720013206/http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/11/England_WorldCup2018.htm |url-status= dead |archive-date= 20 July 2008 |publisher= Football Association |title= World Cup bid latest |date= 15 November 2005 |accessdate=27 October 2007}}</ref>\nBrown reiterated his support for a bid in March 2006, before England's 2006 World Cup campaign,<ref name=\"fa66\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/Wembley/NewsandFeatures/2006/wembley_commemorate_66|title=Heroes of '66 reunited|publisher= Football Association |accessdate=17 October 2010|date=21 March 2006|first=Mark |last=Whittle}}</ref> and again in May 2006.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www2.goldmansachs.com/insight/research/reports/docs/WCB2006.pdf| title= The World Cup and Economics 2006| publisher= [[Goldman Sachs]] research report| date= 3 May 2006| accessdate= 29 October 2007| format= PDF| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071029140706/http://www2.goldmansachs.com/insight/research/reports/docs/WCB2006.pdf| archivedate= 29 October 2007| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe UK government launched its official report on 12 February 2007, in which it was made clear that its support was for an England-only bid and that all games would be played at [[List of English football stadiums by capacity|English grounds]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/chancellor-s-world-cup-fever-fails-to-grip-the-scots-1-681878\n|last=Kirkup | first= James\n|title= Chancellor's World Cup fever fails to grip the Scots\n|work=The Scotsman \n|place=Edinburgh, UK |date=13 February 2007 |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref> The venues selected on 16 December 2009 to form the bid were: London (three stadiums), [[Manchester]] (two stadiums), [[Birmingham]], Bristol, [[Leeds]], Liverpool, [[Milton Keynes]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Nottingham]], [[Plymouth]], [[Sheffield]] and [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8414235.stm|title=Milton Keynes part of England's 2018 World Cup bid|work=BBC Sport |date=6 December 2009 |accessdate=16 December 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091217032444/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8414235.stm| archivedate= 17 December 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[FIFA]] officials also expressed interest in an English bid. David Will, a vice-president of FIFA, noted England's World Cup proposal as early as May 2004.<ref name=\"will\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/click/rss/0.91/public/-/sport1/hi/football/3740851.stm\n| title=FIFA gives England hope |work=BBC News |place=London\n|date=23 May 2004|accessdate=29 October 2007}}</ref>\n[[Franz Beckenbauer]], leader of Germany's successful bid for the 2006 World Cup and a member of FIFA's Executive Committee, twice publicly backed an English bid to host the World Cup, in January and July 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6307237.stm\n|title= Beckenbauer will back England bid\n|work=BBC Sport |location=London |date= 28 January 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6921154.stm\n|title= England gets Beckenbauer backing |work=BBC Sport |date= 29 July 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\nFIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] said he would welcome a 2018 bid from \"the homeland of football.\"<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4208814.stm\n| title= Blatter Welcomes England Cup Bid |work=BBC Sport | date= 2 September 2005| accessdate=30 October 2007}}</ref>\nBlatter met David Cameron on two occasions to discuss the bid while paying visits to England. The British Prime Minister showed much support for the bid and was hopeful that the \"home of football\" would host the tournament.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/06/digger-david-cameron-sepp-blatter\n|title= Prime minister to back 2018 World Cup bid in talks with Sepp Blatter\n|date= 23 October 2007\n|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=28 October 2007\n|first=Matt\n|last=Scott}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview the leader of Russia's bid, Alexei Sorokin, criticised England's bid citing London's high crime rate, alcohol consumption among young people and English fans \"inciting ethnic hatred.\" England filed a complaint, though the complaint was withdrawn following Russia's apology.\n\n=== Portugal and Spain ===\n{{Main|Portugal\u2013Spain 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nThe President of the [[Portuguese Football Federation]] (FPF), Gilberto Madail, first proposed a joint bid with Spain in November 2007.<ref name=\"telegraph20071127\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=A1YourView&xml=/sport/2007/11/27/sfnwcp127.xml \n |last=Bond \n |first=David \n |work=The Daily Telegraph \n |place=London, UK \n |date=27 November 2007 \n |title=Portugal and Spain to Launch Rival 2018 Bid \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226173847/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=A1YourView&xml=%2Fsport%2F2007%2F11%2F27%2Fsfnwcp127.xml \n |archivedate=26 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=485193&cc=3888\n|title= Iberian threat to England's 2018 World Cup bid\n|work= ESPN |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071201142734/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=485193&cc=3888| archivedate= 1 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> The bid intent was confirmed by [[FIFA]] president, [[Sepp Blatter]], on 18 February 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://www.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1090960.html\n|title=Espa\u00f1a y Portugal se unen para pedir el Mundial de 2018\n|last= Brotons |first=Pablo\n|work= [[Diario Marca|Marca]] |location=Madrid\n|date= 18 February 2008 |accessdate=18 February 2008 |language= Spanish}}</ref>\nHowever, the president of the [[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] (RFEF), Angel Villar, announced in July 2008 that it was Spain's intention to submit an individual World Cup bid, and that positive contacts had already taken place with the government, through the secretary of sports, [[Jaime Lissavetzky]]. No specifications were made then regarding a joint bid with Portugal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Villar/confirma/contactos/Lissavetzky/organizar/Mundial/2018/elpepudep/20080716elpepudep_10/Tes\n|title=Villar confirma contactos con Lissavetzky para organizar el Mundial 2018\n|work= [[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Madrid\n |date= 16 July 2008 |accessdate=16 July 2008 |language= Spanish}}</ref> On 23 November 2008, after his re-election for the RFEF presidency, Villar pledged that one of the fundamental objectives of his term was to bring a World Cup to Spain. While he did not mention whether Spain would present a joint bid with Portugal, he did not rule it out when asked about it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/88/spain/2008/12/23/1026578/spain-portugal-confirm-2018-world-cup-bid|title=Spain-Portugal Confirm 2018 World Cup Bid|date=23 December 2010|work=Goal|accessdate=23 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 December 2008, Angel Villar restated \"We need to present a strong, consistent and winning bid for the 2018 World Cup.\" He further confessed \"Personally, I think it should be with Portugal.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/12/23/sports/SOC-WCup-Spain-Portugal-2018-Bid.php\n|title= Spain eyes joint 2018 World Cup bid with Portugal\n|work= International Herald Tribune\n|location=Paris\n |date= 23 December 2008 |accessdate=23 December 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090204023957/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/12/23/sports/SOC-WCup-Spain-Portugal-2018-Bid.php| archivedate= 4 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Subsequently, in the aftermath of a RFEF meeting board, Spain and Portugal announced their intention to bid together.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1194477.html\n|title= La RFEF concreta su candidatura conjunta al Mundial 2018 |work= [[Diario Marca|Marca]]\n|location=Madrid\n|date= 23 December 2008  |accessdate=23 December 2008  |language= Spanish<!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Spanish sports newspaper ''[[Diario Marca|Marca]]'' advanced some details about the potential bid: Spain would lead a twelve-stadium project with eight of the venues, and the opening and final games would be held in [[Lisbon]] and [[Madrid]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1353757&idCanal=56| location= Lisbon| title= Candidatura ib\u00e9rica ao Mundial 2018 prev\u00ea abertura em Lisboa e final em Madrid| work= [[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]| date= 20 December 2008| accessdate= 23 December 2008| language= Portuguese| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205184203/http://ultimahora.publico.clix.pt/noticia.aspx?id=1353757&idCanal=56| archivedate= 5 February 2009| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Spain has previously hosted the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]], while Portugal organised the [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]].\n\n=== Russia ===\n{{Main|Russia 2018 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nRussia announced its intent to bid in early 2009, and submitted its request to FIFA in time.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7838233.stm |title= Russia enters race to host 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date= 20 January 2009 |accessdate=15 October 2009}}</ref> Russia's President [[Vladimir Putin]] took a keen interest in the bid and ordered Vitaly Mutko, the Minister of Sports, to \"prepare a bid for Russia to hold the 2018 World Cup\". According to a report earlier submitted by Vitaly Mutko, who also served that time as President of the [[Russian Football Union]] (RFU), the country was ready to spend some $10.1 billion on the tournament.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Putin orders sports minister to prepare bid for 2018 World Cup\n | url = http://en.rian.ru/sports/20090505/121448011.html\n | work = RIA Novosti\n | location = [[Moscow]]\n | date =5 May 2009\n }}</ref> The bid committee also included RFU CEO Alexey Sorokin and Alexander Djordjadze as the Director of Bid Planning and Operations.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/bid-committee.aspx |title= Bid committee |work= Russia 2018\u20132022 Bid |date = October 2009|accessdate=15 October 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012020705/http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/bid-committee.aspx| archivedate= 12 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFourteen cities were included in the proposal, which divided them into five different clusters: one in the north, centered on [[Saint Petersburg]], a central cluster, centered on Moscow, a southern cluster, centered on [[Sochi]], and the Volga River cluster. Only one city beyond the Ural Mountains was cited, [[Yekaterinburg]]. The other cities were: [[Kaliningrad]] in the north cluster, [[Rostov-on-Don]] and [[Krasnodar]] in the south cluster and [[Yaroslavl]], [[Nizhny Novgorod]], [[Kazan]], [[Saransk]], [[Samara, Russia|Samara]] and [[Volgograd]] in the Volga River cluster.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/host-cities.aspx |title= Host cities |work= Russia 2018\u20132022 Bid |date = October 2009|accessdate=15 October 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091023181459/http://www.russia2018-2022.com/en/the-bid/host-cities.aspx| archivedate= 23 October 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> At the time of bidding, Russia did not have a stadium with 80,000 capacity, but the bid called for the expansion of [[Luzhniki Stadium]] in Moscow, already a [[UEFA Elite stadium]], from a capacity of slightly over 78,000 to over 89,000. Russia hoped to have five stadiums fit to host World Cup matches ready by 2013 \u2013 two in Moscow and one stadium each in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Kazan]] and [[Sochi]], which at the time was due to host the [[2014 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.rin.ru/eng/news///12466/7// |title= Russia ready to spend $10 bln on World Cup 2018 preparations |date = April 2009|accessdate=30 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n== 2022 bids ==\n\n=== Australia ===\n{{Main|Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nIn September 2007, the [[Football Federation Australia]] confirmed that Australia would bid for the 2018 World Cup finals.<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/socceroos-stars-coming-home-for-two-matches/2006/09/21/1158431837576.html\n|agency=AAP\n|title= Socceroos' stars coming home for two matches |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 September 2007 |accessdate=28 October 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071209231144/http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/socceroos-stars-coming-home-for-two-matches/2006/09/21/1158431837576.html| archivedate= 9 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nPreviously, in late May 2006, the [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] sports minister, [[Justin Madden]], said that he wanted his [[States of Australia|state]] to drive a bid to stage the 2018 World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://keobongda247.com/world-cup-2018.html |work=Keobongda247 Sports VietNam |title= news aggregator world cup 2018\n }}{{dead link|date=June 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref> [[Frank Lowy]], the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]] chairman, stated that they aimed to use [[List of sports venues in Australia|16 stadiums]] for the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23259207-5006068,00.html \n |last=Smithies \n |first=Tom \n |title=Lowy's vision for soccer \n |date=23 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205172915/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0%2C22049%2C23259207-5006068%2C00.html \n |archivedate=5 February 2009 \n |accessdate=13 May 2013 \n |work=The Daily Telegraph \n |place=Sydney \n}}</ref>\nFormer Australian Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] announced the Federal Government's support for the bid,<ref>{{cite news\n|last=Gilmore |first=Heath |author2=Proszenko, Adrian\n|url= http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/pm-makes-the-perfect-pitch-for-world-cup/2008/02/23/1203467452577.html |title= PM makes the perfect pitch for World Cup |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date= 28 February 2008 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref>\nand in December 2008, Federal minister for sport [[Kate Ellis]] announced that the federal government would give the FFA $45.6 million to fund its World Cup bid preparation.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = $45m for 2018 World Cup bid\n |url          = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24778844-12377,00.html\n |agency       = AAP\n |location     = Sydney\n |date         = 10 December 2008\n |access-date  = 12 December 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090206034706/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24778844-12377,00.html\n |archive-date = 6 February 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\nRudd met with Sepp Blatter to discuss the Commonwealth Government's support of the bid in Zurich in July 2009.<ref>[http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=8 Australian Bid Page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720083535/http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=8 |date=20 July 2009 }}.</ref>\n\nAt the 2008 FIFA Congress, held in Sydney, FIFA president Sepp Blatter suggested that Australia concentrate on hosting the 2022 tournament,<ref name=\"2022Bid\">{{cite news\n |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/news/newsid=783630.html#joint+decision+2018+2022+fifa+world+cups \n |title=Joint decision on 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups \n |work=[[FIFA]] \n |date=30 May 2008 \n |accessdate=30 May 2008 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531132531/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/news/newsid%3D783630.html \n |archivedate=31 May 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> but Lowy responded by recommitting Australia to its 2018 bid.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/21/2281753.htm?section=sport\n|agency=AFP\n|title= FFA to press on with 2018 Cup bid: Lowy |date= 21 June 2008 |accessdate=21 June 2008 |work= [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080623012033/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/06/21/2281753.htm?section=sport| archivedate= 23 June 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> However, Australia ultimately withdrew from the bidding for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in favour of the 2022 FIFA World Cup on 10 June 2010, following comments from the chief of the [[Asian Football Confederation]] that the 2018 tournament should be held in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/australia/7818364/World-Cup-2010-Australia-pull-out-of-World-Cup-2018-bidding.html |title= World Cup 2010: Australia pull out of World Cup 2018 bidding |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date= 10 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010525/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/australia/7818364/World-Cup-2010-Australia-pull-out-of-World-Cup-2018-bidding.html| archivedate= 13 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/09/world-cup-2018-2022-europe |title= World Cup 2018 should be in Europe, says Asian Football Confederation |work=The Guardian |location=London |date= 10 June 2010 |accessdate=10 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAustralia's largest stadiums are currently used by other major Australian sports whose domestic seasons overlap with the World Cup. The [[Australian Football League]] and [[National Rugby League]] claimed that loss of access to these major venues for eight weeks would severely disrupt their seasons and impact the viability of their clubs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770679.htm?site=sport&section=football |title=AFL concerns over world cup run deep. |accessdate=21 December 2009 |work=ABC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430034758/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/14/2770679.htm?site=sport&section=football |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/soccers-plan-to-displace-nrl/story-e6frexnr-1225808419104 |title=Soccer's plan to displace NRL |accessdate=21 December 2009 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Sydney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501021425/http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/soccers-plan-to-displace-nrl/story-e6frexnr-1225808419104 |archive-date=1 May 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The AFL in particular had previously advised it would not relinquish [[Docklands Stadium|Etihad Stadium]] in Melbourne for the entire period required.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/cup-bid-needs-to-share-the-vision-20091212-kpim.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Cup bid needs to share the vision | date=13 December 2009}}</ref> On 9 May 2010 the AFL, NRL, and FFA announced a Memorandum of Understanding guaranteeing that the AFL and NRL seasons would continue, should the bid be successful. Compensation for the rival football codes would be awarded as a result of any disruptions caused by hosting the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/rival-codes-finally-shake-hands-on-deal-to-play-through-world-cup-20100509-uluq.html |title= Rival codes finally shake hands on deal to play through World Cup |first= Brad |last= Walter |date= 10 May 2010 |accessdate=19 May 2010 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100512122253/http://www.smh.com.au/sport/football/rival-codes-finally-shake-hands-on-deal-to-play-through-world-cup-20100509-uluq.html| archivedate= 12 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> AFL CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] came out in support of the bid, despite initially not supporting the bid.<ref>http://www.theage.com.au/comment/not-every-afl-point-was-a-goal-20140303-3409o.html</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad-application/world-cup-soccer-2020-decision/story-fn6bn88w-1225961153205 |title= World Cup soccer 2022 debate |first= Andrew |last= Demetriou |date= 26 November 2010 |accessdate=28 November 2010 |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia}}</ref> [[Franz Beckenbauer]] indicated that the issue of factional disputes between the [[Football Federation Australia|FFA]], [[National Rugby League|NRL]] and, [[Australian Football League|AFL]] were not considered by the [[FIFA Executive Committee]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldsun.com.au/ipad-application/argy-bargy-no-threat-to-world-cup-bid/story-fn6bn647-1225961988679 |title= Argy-bargy no threat to World Cup bid |first= David |last= Davutovic |date= 28 November 2010 |accessdate=28 November 2010 |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia}}</ref> Although initially Australia seemed to be a popular contender to host the tournament, the final Australian World Cup bid received only one vote astonishing Franz Beckenbauer<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-12-04/beckenbauer-astonished-by-australia-snub/2362520</ref> and experts alike.\n\n=== Japan ===\n{{Main|Japan 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nJapan bid to become the first Asian country to host the World Cup twice; however, the fact that they were co-hosts so recently in [[World Cup 2002|2002]] was expected to work against them in their bid.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = The race to host World Cup 2018 and 2022\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7856716.stm#japan\n |work=BBC Sport\n | location = London\n | date = 17 March 2009\n }}</ref> Although Japan did not have an 80,000-seat capacity stadium, its plan was based on a proposed 100,000-seat stadium that would have gone on to be a centrepiece of [[2016 Olympics]], for which [[Tokyo bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Tokyo]] was bidding.\n\nJapan also pledged that if it had been granted the rights to host the 2022 World Cup games, it would develop technology enabling it to provide a live international telecast of the event in [[3D television|3D]], which would allow 400 stadiums in 208 countries to provide 360 million people with real-time 3D coverage of the games projected on giant screens, captured in 360 degrees by 200 HD cameras. Furthermore, Japan will broadcast the games in holographic format if the technology to do so is available by that time. Beyond allowing the world's spectators to view the games on flat screens projecting 3D imaging, holographic projection would project the games onto stadium fields, creating a greater illusion of actually being in the presence of the players. Microphones embedded below the playing surface would record all sounds, such as ball kicks, in order to add to the sense of realism.\n\nThe Olympic bid was unsuccessful, coming third in the bidding process that concluded in October 2009. The Vice-President of the [[Japan Football Association]], Junji Ogura, had previously admitted that if Tokyo were to fail in its bid, its chances of hosting either the 2018 or 2022 World Cup would not be very good.<ref>{{cite news\n | title = Japan World Cup bid rests on 2016 Olympic vote\n | first = Alastair\n | last = Himmer\n | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/olympicsNews/idUSSP35460420090123\n | work = Reuters\n | date = 22 January 2009\n | accessdate =5 December 2010\n }}</ref> On 4 May 2010, Japan announced that it was withdrawing its bid for the 2018 tournament to focus on 2022, amidst rising speculation that the 2018 edition will be held in Europe.<ref name=\"Japan 2018 withdrawal\">{{cite news | title = Japan drops bid to host 2018 World Cup to aim for 2022 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8659185.stm |work=BBC Sport | location = London | date = 3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Qatar ===\n{{Main|Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nQatar made a bid for only the 2022 World Cup. Qatar was attempting to become the first Arab country to host the World Cup. Failed bids from other Arab countries include [[Morocco]] (1994, 1998, 2006 and 2010), [[Egypt]] and a Libya-Tunisia joint bid withdrew in the [[2010 World Cup]] bidding process.<ref name=\"race20090317\"/>\nSheikh Mohammed bin Hamad bin Khalifa Al-Thani, son of the former [[Emir of Qatar]], was the chairman of the bid committee.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Qatar 2022 announces Bid Committee leadership \n |url=http://www.dubaichronicle.com/life/sport-life/qatar-2022-announces-bid-committee-leadership-7121 \n |work=Dubai Chronicle \n |date=25 March 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602051207/http://www.dubaichronicle.com/life/sport-life/qatar-2022-announces-bid-committee-leadership-7121 \n |archivedate=2 June 2009 \n}}</ref>\nQatar planned to promote the bid as an Arab unity bid and hoped to draw on support from the entire [[Arab world]] and were positioning this as an opportunity to bridge the gap between the Arab and Western worlds.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Qatar launch \"unity\" bid to stage 2022 World Cup finals\n | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=647154&sec=worldcup2010&&cc=5739\n | work = ESPN\n | date = 17 May 2009\n | accessdate =5 December 2010\n }}</ref> The bid launched an advertising campaign across the nation in November 2009.<ref>{{cite news\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rCt5n5iWTXU\n | title = Qatar 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid TV Commercial\n | date = 15 November 2009\n | work = YouTube\n }}</ref>\n\nSome concerns with Qatar's bid deal with the extreme temperatures.<ref name=cool>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/10093703.stm |title= Qatar pitches cool World Cup bid |first= Neil |last= Heathcote |work= [[BBC World News]] |date= 4 May 2010 |accessdate=7 May 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100507215907/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/10093703.stm| archivedate= 7 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The World Cup is always held in the European off-season in June and July and during this period the average daytime high in most of Qatar is in excess of 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (104&nbsp;\u00b0F), with the average daily low temperatures not dropping below 30&nbsp;\u00b0C (86&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/QAXX0003?from=36hr_bottomnav_business |title=Monthly Averages for Doha, Qatar |work=The Weather Channel |accessdate=26 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229115428/http://www.weather.com/outlook/travel/businesstraveler/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/QAXX0003?from=36hr_bottomnav_business |archive-date=29 December 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Sheikh Mohammed bin Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani, the 2022 Qatar bid chairman, responded saying \"the event has to be organised in June or July. We will have to take the help of technology to counter the harsh weather. We have already set in motion the process. A stadium with controlled temperature is the answer to the problem. We have other plans up our sleeves as well.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Qatar will be great host for WC 2022 \n |first=Raajiv \n |last=Tripathi \n |author2=Nag, Arindam \n |url=http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090325/content.asp?section=exclusive1_1 \n |work=Qatar Tribune \n |location=Doha \n |date=25 March 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329073540/http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090325/content.asp?section=exclusive1_1 \n |archivedate=29 March 2009 \n}}</ref> The first five proposed stadiums are planned to employ cooling technology capable of reducing temperatures within the stadium by up to 20 degrees Celsius. Additionally, the upper tiers of the stadiums will be dis-assembled after the World Cup and donated to countries with less developed sports infrastructure.<ref name=cool/>\n\nPresident of FIFA [[Sepp Blatter]] endorsed the idea of having a World Cup in the Middle East, saying in April 2010, \"The Arabic world deserves a World Cup. They have 22 countries and have not had any opportunity to organise the tournament.\" Blatter also praised Qatar's progress, \"When I was first in Qatar<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineqatar.com/visiting/qatar-world-cup-2022/qatar-world-cup-2022-an-overview|title=Qatar Worldcup 2022 Stadiums|publisher=OnlineQatar|author=Davies Krish|date=9 April 2019}}</ref> there were 400,000 people here and now there are 1.6 million. In terms of infrastructure, when you are able to organise the [[2006 Asian Games|Asian Games (in 2006)]] with more than 30 events for men and women, then that is not in question.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/sport/2010/04/2010424184010305993.html|title=Blatter reaches out to Arabia|work=Al Jazeera|date=25 April 2010|accessdate=1 May 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100429041252/http://english.aljazeera.net/sport/2010/04/2010424184010305993.html| archivedate= 29 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Qatar's bid to host the 2022 World Cup received a huge boost on 28 July 2010 when [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC) President [[Mohammed Bin Hammam]] threw his weight behind his country's campaign. Speaking in Singapore, Bin Hammam said: \"I have one vote and, frankly speaking, I will vote for Qatar but if Qatar is not in the running I will vote for another Asian country.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsfeatures.com/soccernews/story/47199/more-bad-news-for-australia-as-bin-hammam-talks-up-qatars-2022-bid.html |title=Bin Hammam talks up Qatar's 2022 bid |publisher=Sports Features Communications |date=28 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209222311/http://www.sportsfeatures.com/soccernews/story/47199/more-bad-news-for-australia-as-bin-hammam-talks-up-qatars-2022-bid.html |archivedate=9 December 2010 }}</ref> Qatar has already hosted the AFC Asian Cup in 1988, FIFA U-20 World Cup 1995 and the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]].\n\n=== South Korea ===\n{{Main|South Korea 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nSouth Korea bid only for the 2022 World Cup. They were bidding to become the first Asian country to host the World Cup twice; however, the fact that they were co-hosts so recently in 2002 was expected to work against them in their bid. [[Han Seung-joo]], a former [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade (South Korea)|South Korean Minister of Foreign Affairs]], was appointed as the Chairman of the Bidding Committee in August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kfa.or.kr/eng_kfa/news/news/view.asp?g_conid=2009827162321&g_gubun=1 |title=Han Sung-Joo Appointed as the Chairman of the Bidding Committee |work=[[Korea Football Association]] |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=11 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427083109/http://www.kfa.or.kr/eng_kfa/news/news/view.asp?g_conid=2009827162321&g_gubun=1 |archivedate=27 April 2011 }}</ref> He met with FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]] in Z\u00fcrich, Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kr.news.yahoo.com/sports/npb/view?aid=20090926073606806i1 |script-title=ko:(\uc778\ud130\ubdf0) \ud55c\uc2b9\uc8fc \uc704\uc6d0\uc7a5 \"\uad6d\uc81c \ucd95\uad6c\uacc4, 2022 \uc6d4\ub4dc\ucef5 \uc720\uce58 \uc758\uc0ac \ud658\uc601 |date= 26 September 2009 |accessdate=28 November 2009 |work= Yahoo! News Korea |language= Korean}}</ref> In January 2010, President [[Lee Myung-bak]] visited the headquarters of FIFA in [[Zurich]], Switzerland to meet Sepp Blatter in support of the South Korean bid.\n\nAlthough South Korea did not have an 80,000 capacity stadium, it planned to upgrade an existing venue to meet that capacity. There are three grounds which can seat over 60,000 people\u2014[[Seoul Olympic Stadium]], [[Seoul World Cup Stadium]] and [[Daegu Stadium]].  Another 70,000 seat [[Incheon Asiad Main Stadium|stadium]] is scheduled to be built in [[Incheon]] as the main stadium for the [[2014 Asian Games]]. Other venues meet hosting requirements as they were built for the 2002 World Cup.<ref name=\"race20090317\"/> The 12 cities selected to hold the finals were South Korea to win the bid were selected in March 2010 and were [[Busan]], [[Cheonan]], [[Daegu]], [[Daejeon]], [[Goyang]], [[Gwangju]], [[Incheon]] (2 venues), [[Jeonju]], [[Seogwipo]], [[Seoul]] (2venues), [[Suwon]] and [[Ulsan]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.worldfootballinsider.com/Story.aspx?id=33064 |title=Korea 2022 Reveals Host Cities |publisher=World Football Insider |date=4 March 2010 |accessdate=8 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100306150340/http://www.worldfootballinsider.com/Story.aspx?id=33064| archivedate= 6 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{Main|United States 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\n[[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] first said in February 2007 that it would bid for the 2018 World Cup.<ref name=goff>{{cite news\n|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/19/AR2007021900914.html\n|title= U.S. to Seek World Cup\n| work= The Washington Post\n| first=Steven | last=Goff\n| date=20 February 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref> On 28 January 2009, U.S. Soccer then announced that it would submit bids for both the 2018 and 2022 Cups.<ref name=\"USA 2018-2022\">{{cite news\n|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=614052&sec=world&cc=5901\n|title=U.S. to bid for 2018 and 2022 World Cups\n|agency= Associated Press |work=[[ESPNsoccernet]] |location=Chicago |date=29 January 2009 | accessdate=29 January 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090131230810/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=614052&sec=world&cc=5901| archivedate= 31 January 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> David Downs, president of [[Univision]] Sports, was executive director of the bid. Other committee members included president of [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] [[Sunil Gulati]], U.S. Soccer chief executive officer Dan Flynn, [[Major League Soccer]] Commissioner [[Don Garber]], and Phil Murphy, the former national finance chairman for the [[Democratic National Committee]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url= http://voices.washingtonpost.com/soccerinsider/2009/02/usa_in_18_or_22.html\n|title= USA in '18 (or '22) |first= Steve |last= Goff |work= The Washington Post\n|date= 2 February 2009 |accessdate=4 September 2009}}</ref> The vice president of FIFA, [[Austin \"Jack\" Warner|Jack Warner]], who is also the president of CONCACAF, originally said he would try to bring the World Cup back to the CONCACAF region.<ref>{{cite news\n| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/6939170.stm\n| title=Caborn hits back at Warner attack\n|work=BBC Sport | date=10 August 2007 | accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref>\nHowever, Warner also stated that he preferred the USSF change their plans to make a bid for the 2022 FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/8204792/Warner-wants-U.S.-to-bid-for-2022-World-Cup| title= Warner wants U.S. to bid for 2022 World Cup| work= [[Fox Sports (USA)]]| accessdate= 4 June 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080606193657/http://msn.foxsports.com/soccer/story/8204792/Warner-wants-U.S.-to-bid-for-2022-World-Cup| archivedate= 6 June 2008| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, the bid committee identified 70 stadiums in 50 communities as possible venues for the tournament, with 58 confirming their interest.<ref name=\"70 stadiums\">{{cite news\n| title=2018 OR 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid Committee Contacts 70 US Venues\n| date=8 April 2009\n| url =http://soccer.teamusa.org/news/2009/04/08/2018-or-2022-fifa-world-cup-bid-committee-contacts-70-us-venues/11583\n| work = USA Soccer | accessdate =20 January 2018  }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/fifa-world-cup-2018-guide-to-the-12-host-stadiums\n|title=FIFA World Cup 2018: Guide to the 12 host stadiums\n|date=20 January 2018  |accessdate=20 January 2018 |publisher=Sportskeeda}}</ref> The list of stadiums was trimmed two months later to 45 in 37 cities,<ref name=\"45 stadiums\">{{Cite press release\n |title=USA Bid Committee Issues Requests For Proposals to 37 Potential FIFA World Cup Host Cities For 2018 or 2022 \n |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/articles/viewArticle.jsp_14876672.html \n |publisher=United States Soccer Federation \n |date=16 June 2009 \n |accessdate=18 June 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619071040/http://www.ussoccer.com/articles/viewArticle.jsp_14876672.html \n |archivedate=19 June 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> and then in August 2009 to 32 stadiums in 27 cities.<ref name=\"32 stadiums\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Federation-Services/2009/08/27-Cities-Chosen-For-World-Cup-Bid.aspx |title=USA Bid Committee Announces List of 27 Cities Still in Contention For Inclusion in U.S. Bid to Host FIFA World Cup in 2018 or 2022 |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=20 August 2009 |publisher=United States Soccer Federation |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926202259/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Federation-Services/2009/08/27-Cities-Chosen-For-World-Cup-Bid.aspx |archivedate=26 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In January 2010, 18 cities and 21 stadiums were selected for the final bid. The cities were [[Atlanta]], [[Baltimore]], [[Boston]] ([[Foxborough, Massachusetts|Foxboro]]), [[Dallas]], [[Denver]], [[Houston]], [[Indianapolis]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Miami]], [[Nashville]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[San Diego]], [[Seattle]], [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] The cities with multiple qualifying stadiums were [[Los Angeles]], [[Seattle]], [[Dallas]] and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]. With several large [[American football]] stadiums, the 21 venues were to have an average capacity of 77,000; none seated fewer than 65,000. Seven of the stadiums seat at least 80,000.<ref name=\"18 cities chosen\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.gousabid.com/news/entry/bid-committee-announces-official-bid-cities/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123191730/http://www.gousabid.com/news/entry/bid-committee-announces-official-bid-cities |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 January 2010 |title=Bid Committee announces official bid cities |date=12 January 2010 |accessdate=12 January 2010 |publisher=The USA Bid Committee }}</ref> Two proposed stadiums would be used by [[Major League Soccer]] during the summer.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nIn October 2010, the United States withdrew from the 2018 bid process, to focus solely on the 2022 competition.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9097559.stm |title=US withdraw bid to host 2018 World Cup |date=15 October 2010 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n== Cancelled bids ==\nTwo countries had to cancel bids for the 2018 or 2022 FIFA World Cups before individual evaluations began. Mexico cancelled its bid for both cups, while Indonesia was only bidding for the 2022 World Cup.\n\n=== Indonesia ===\n{{Main|Indonesia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid}}\n\nIn January 2009 the [[Football Association of Indonesia]] (PSSI) confirmed their intention to bid for the 2022 FIFA World Cup, with government support.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/16/world-cup/2009/01/30/1084577/exclusive-indonesia-hosting-world-cup-is-not-impossible/\n|title=Exclusive: Indonesia \u2013 Hosting World Cup Is Not Impossible\n|work=Goal.com|date= 30 January 2009|accessdate=5 February 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090212095001/http://www.goal.com/en/news/16/world-cup/2009/01/30/1084577/exclusive-indonesia-hosting-world-cup-is-not-impossible/| archivedate= 12 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.detiksport.com/sepakbola/read/2009/01/29/095205/1076009/76/pemerintah-mendukung-penuh\n|title=Full Support from government for WC bid\n|work=detik.com\n|date= 29 January 2009|accessdate=5 February 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090203073548/http://detiksport.com/sepakbola/read/2009/01/29/095205/1076009/76/pemerintah-mendukung-penuh| archivedate= 3 February 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In February 2009, PSSI launched the \"Green World Cup Indonesia 2022\" campaign.<ref name=\"hotland\">{{cite news\n |last=Hotland \n |first=Tony \n |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/02/10/indonesia-upbeat-host-green039-world-cup.html/ \n |title=Indonesia upbeat to host 'green' World Cup \n |work=The Jakarta Post \n |date=11 February 2009 \n |accessdate=11 February 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424191616/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/02/10/indonesia-upbeat-host-green039-world-cup.html/ \n |archivedate=24 April 2013 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\nThis campaign included a $1 billion plan to upgrade supporting infrastructure beside stadiums to meet FIFA's requirements. The funds to construct stadiums were to come from regional governments.<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://bola.vivanews.com/news/read/28455-anggaran_infrastruktur_rp_10_triliun\n |title        = 10,000 million rupiahs for stadia constructions\n |work         = vivanews.com\n |date         = 9 February 2009\n |accessdate   = 6 September 2009\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090918231601/http://bola.vivanews.com/news/read/28455-anggaran_infrastruktur_rp_10_triliun\n |archive-date = 18 September 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Indonesia had previously made World Cup history when it became the first Asian nation to play in a World Cup, at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938 tournament]] in France under its colonial name of the Dutch East Indies.<ref>{{cite news\n |agency      = Associated Press\n |url         = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/01/28/indonesia-joins-race-host-2018-2022-world-cup.html\n |title       = Indonesia joins race to host 2018, 2022 World Cup\n |work        = The Jakarta Post\n |date        = 28 January 2009\n |accessdate  = 5 September 2009\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090818140133/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/01/28/indonesia-joins-race-host-2018-2022-world-cup.html\n |archivedate = 18 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Indonesia also had tournament hosting experience as the co-host of [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]].\n\nIn the campaign presentation, PSSI president Nurdin Halid said he believed Indonesia stood a chance to win FIFA's approval to host the 2022 World Cup, despite the relatively poor infrastructure, coupled with the low quality of the national squad compared to other candidates. He said Indonesia had proposed a \"Green World Cup 2022\", hoping to capitalise on the current green and global warming movement worldwide: \"Our deforestation rate has contributed much to world pollution. By hosting the World Cup, we wish to build infrastructure and facilities that are environmentally friendly so we can give more to the planet.\"<ref name=\"hotland\"/>\n\nThe bid was launched at a moment when there were strong pressures from Indonesian football fans for Halid to step down from his position as chairman of PSSI. There was no official support from the government of Indonesia until 9 February 2010, the deadline for the country's government to file a letter of support for the bid.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indonesia's bid for 2022 World Cup in question |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/soccer/wires/02/08/2020.ap.soc.wcup.indonesia.bid.1st.ld.writethru.0227/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |date=9 February 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Secretary General of PSSI Nugraha Besoes did not deny that Indonesia could be disqualified from the bidding process because the Indonesian government did not support the bid.<ref>{{cite news\n |language= Indonesian\n | title = Indonesia Dicoret, Selamat Tinggal Piala Dunia\n | url = http://bola.kompas.com/read/xml/2010/03/10/08294818/Indonesia.Dicoret..Selamat.Tinggal.Piala.Dunia\n | work = Kompas.com\n | date = 10 March 2010|accessdate=11 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100325180708/http://bola.kompas.com/read/xml/2010/03/10/08294818/Indonesia.Dicoret..Selamat.Tinggal.Piala.Dunia| archivedate= 25 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On 19 March 2010, FIFA rejected Indonesia's bid to host the 2022 World Cup because the government stated that their concern is for the people of the country and so could not support the bid as FIFA requested.<ref name=reject>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8577452.stm |title= Indonesia's bid to host the 2022 World Cup bid ends |date= 19 March 2010 |accessdate=19 March 2010 |work=BBC Sport| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100320054013/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8577452.stm| archivedate= 20 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> As a consequence, PSSI threw their support behind Australia's bid for the 2022 tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=70 |title=Indonesia backs Australia's 2022 FIFA World Cup Bid |date=12 June 2010 |publisher=[[Australia 2022 FIFA World Cup bid]] |accessdate=2 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614232611/http://www.australia2018-2022.com.au/news-updates_detail.aspx?view=70 |archivedate=14 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\nFormer [[Mexican Football Federation]] President, Alberto de la Torre, announced their intention to bid for the cup in 2005, but was ineligible because of the rotation policy at that time.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n== Selection ==\n\n===Eligible voters===\n{{see also|2015 FIFA corruption case}}\n\n;FIFA President\n* [[Sepp Blatter]] (banned in 2015 for eight years by [[FIFA Ethics Committee]], amid a sweeping corruption investigation led by the U.S. in the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n\n;Senior Vice President\n* {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Julio Grondona]] (died on 30 July 2014; indicted on 6 April 2020 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n;Vice Presidents\n* {{flagicon|Cameroon}} [[Issa Hayatou]]\n* {{flagicon|South Korea|1997}} [[Chung Mong-joon]]\n* {{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]] (indicted for corruption in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Angel Maria Villar]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} [[Michel Platini]] (banned in 2015 for life from all football activities for ethics violations)\n* {{flagicon|England}} [[Geoff Thompson (football)|Geoff Thompson]]\n\n;Members\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}} \n* {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Michel D'Hooghe]]\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Ricardo Teixeira]] (indicted on 3 December 2015 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n* {{flagicon|Qatar}} [[Mohamed Bin Hammam]] (banned in 2011 for life from all football activities for ethics violations)\n* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Senes Erzik]]\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Chuck Blazer]] (plead guilty to corruption charges in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Thailand}} [[Worawi Makudi]] (banned in 2015 for five years for forgery and falsification)\n* {{flagicon|Paraguay|1990}} [[Nicolas Leoz]] (indicted for corruption in [[2015 FIFA corruption case]])\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Junji Ogura]]\n* {{flagicon|Cyprus}} [[Marios Lefkaritis]]\n* {{flagicon|Ivory Coast}} [[Jacques Anouma]]\n* {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Franz Beckenbauer]]\n* {{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[Rafael Salguero]] (indicted on 3 December 2015 by the U.S. Department of Justice)\n* {{flagicon|Egypt}} [[Hany Abo Rida]]\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Vitaly Mutko]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n;Prevented from voting\n*{{flagicon|TAH}} [[Reynald Temarii]]<ref name=qa/>\n*{{flagicon|NGR}} [[Amos Adamu]]<ref name=qa>{{cite web|last1=Fylan|first1=Kevin|title=Q+A - Voting for the 2018 and 2022 World Cup hosts|url=http://uk.mobile.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKTRE6B01OI20101201|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=1 June 2014|date=1 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Voting rounds ===\n[[File:Russia 2018 World Cup.jpeg|right|thumb|Russian officials celebrate after being awarded the 2018 World Cup.]]\n{{further|FIFA World Cup hosts}}\n\nOn 2 December 2010, FIFA president [[Sepp Blatter]] announced the winning bids at FIFA's headquarters in Zurich. Russia was chosen to host the 2018 World Cup, and Qatar was chosen to host the 2022 World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/russia2018/news/newsid=1344698/index.html|title=Russia and Qatar awarded 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups|date=2 December 2010|work=FIFA.com|accessdate=2 December 2010}}</ref> This made Russia the first [[Eastern Europe]]an country to host the World Cup, while Qatar would be the first Middle Eastern country to host the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/02/england-russia-win-2018-world-cup|title=England beaten as Russia win 2018 World Cup bid|date=2 December 2010|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=2 December 2010|first=Owen|last=Gibson}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/dec/02/qatar-win-2022-world-cup-bid|title=Qatar win 2022 World Cup bid|date=2 December 2010|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=2 December 2010|first=Jamie|last=Jackson}}</ref>\nBlatter noted that the committee had decided to \"go to new lands\" and reflected a desire to \"develop football\" by bringing it to more countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/03/sports/soccer/03worldcup.html?_r=1&hp|title=Russia and Qatar Win World Cup Bids|last=Longman|first=Jer\u00e9|work=New York Times|accessdate=2 December 2010|date=2 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn each round a majority of twelve votes was needed. If no bid received 12 votes in a round, the bid with the fewest votes in that round was eliminated, and accordingly each remaining bid should receive no fewer votes in subsequent rounds than in preceding rounds. The actual votes cast were as follows:<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/media/newsid=1344971.html |title=Russia and Qatar to host 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cups, respectively |publisher=FIFA |date=2 December 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203003635/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/2018/media/newsid%3D1344971.html |archivedate=3 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;\"\n|+ '''2018 World Cup host vote results'''\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Country\n! colspan=\"2\" | Vote\n|-\n! 1\n! 2\n|-bgcolor=#90EE90\n| align=left |  '''{{Flagu|Russia}}'''\n|9\n|'''13'''\n|- \n| align=left | {{Flagu|Spain}}/{{Flagu|Portugal}}\n| 7\n| 7\n|-\n| align=left  | {{Flagu|Netherlands}}/{{Flagu|Belgium}}\n| 4\n| 2\n|-\n| align=left  | {{ENG}}\n| 2\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n! align=left |Total Votes\n! 22\n! 22\n|}\n\n{{Col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;\"\n|+ '''2022 World Cup host vote results'''\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Country\n! colspan=\"4\" | Vote\n|-\n! 1\n! 2\n! 3\n! 4\n|- bgcolor=#90EE90\n| align=left | '''{{Flagu|Qatar}}'''\n|11\n|10\n|11\n|'''14'''\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|United States}}\n| 3\n| 5\n| 6\n| 8\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|South Korea}}\n| 4\n| 5\n| 5\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|Japan}}\n| 3\n| 2\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n| align=left | {{Flagu|Australia}}\n| 1\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n| bgcolor=#F08080|\u2013\n|-\n! align=left |Total Votes\n! 22\n! 22\n! 22\n! 22\n|}\n{{Col-end}}As can be observed from multiple bids that received fewer votes in voting round 2 compared to voting round 1 (Netherlands/Belgium, Qatar and Japan), at least 2 voting members in each of the 2018 and 2022 votes changed their votes between voting rounds despite their initial bid not being eliminated in voting round 1 (see '[[2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cup bids#Allegations of vote-buying|Allegations of vote-buying]]', below).\n\n===Allegations of vote-buying===\n{{see also|Garcia Report|2015 FIFA corruption case}}\n\nShortly after the voting in December 2010, [[ESPN]] published allegations linking Qatar's successful bid to Football Dreams, a youth development program that channeled money from the Qatari government to football programs in 15 countries in sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America and Southeast Asia\u2014six of which had representatives on the FIFA executive committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/5933045/how-qatar-became-player-world-soccer |title=Behind Qatar's football success |first=Brent |last=Latham |publisher=ESPN |date=21 December 2010 |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref> In February 2011, Blatter admitted that the Spanish and Qatari bid teams did try to trade votes, \"but it didn't work\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9387891.stm |work=BBC Sport |title=Sepp Blatter hints at 2022 summer World Cup in Qatar |quote=I'll be honest, there was a bundle of votes between Spain and Qatar. But it was a nonsense. It was there but it didn't work, not for one and not for the other side.|date= 7 February 2011 |accessdate=9 February 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110208203040/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9387891.stm| archivedate= 8 February 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, the former England 2018 bid chief [[David Triesman, Baron Triesman|Lord Treisman]] told a [[Select committees of the Parliament of the United Kingdom|House of Commons select committee]] that four FIFA committee members approached him asking for various things in exchange for votes. Among the accused were FIFA Vice President [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], who asked for \u00a32.5 million to be used for projects, and [[Nicol\u00e1s Leoz]], who allegedly asked to be knighted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/917869/lord-triesman-accuses-four-fifa-officials-of-impropriety |work=[[ESPN Soccernet]] |title=Triesman accuses four FIFA members |date=10 May 2011 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> ''The Sunday Times'' further reported that month [[Issa Hayatou]] and [[Jacques Anouma]] were given $1.5 million in exchange for their votes in favor of Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/918397/fifa-demands-evidence-of-corruption-|work=ESPN Soccernet|title=FIFA demands evidence of corruption|date=11 May 2011|accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> On 30 May 2011, [[FIFA President]] [[Sepp Blatter]] rejected the evidence in a press conference, while [[Jack Warner (football executive)|Jack Warner]], who had been suspended that day for a separate ethics violations pending an investigation, leaked an email from FIFA General Secretary [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Valcke]] which suggested that Qatar had \"bought\" the rights to host the 2022 FIFA World Cup. Valcke subsequently issued a statement denying he had suggested it was bribery, saying instead that the country had \"used its financial muscle to lobby for support\". Qatar officials denied any impropriety.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/30/us-soccer-fifa-qatar-idUSTRE74T4J420110530 |title= Qataris brush off allegations of buying World Cup rights |agency=[[Reuters]] |first= Regan E. |last= Doherty |date= 30 May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> [[Theo Zwanziger]], President of the [[German Football Association]], also called on FIFA to re-examine the awarding of the Cup to Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13613314.stm |title= German Federation asks Fifa for inquiry into Qatar 2022 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date= 1 June 2011 |accessdate=1 June 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110601111502/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13613314.stm| archivedate= 1 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, FIFA appointed former U.S. Attorney [[Michael J. Garcia]] to investigate allegations of vote-buying in the selection process. He submitted [[Garcia Report|the report]] in September 2014, which FIFA at the time declined to release in full. Instead, FIFA released a summary that Garcia described as \"materially incomplete,\" leading Garcia to resign in protest. FIFA ultimately published the report in 2017, after German tabloid ''[[Bild]]'' announced they would publish a leaked copy. The report detailed dozens of allegations but didn't provide hard evidence for vote-buying.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/sports/fifa-garcia-report.html |title= In Long-Secret FIFA Report, More Details but No Smoking Gun |newspaper= The New York Times |first= Andrew |last= Keh |date= 27 June 2017 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> In May 2015, as members gathered in [[Z\u00fcrich]] for the [[65th FIFA Congress]], U.S. federal prosecutors disclosed cases of corruption leading to the arrest of seven. More than 40 individuals were indicted, including 2018 and 2022 voters [[Luis Bedoya]], [[Chuck Blazer]], [[Nicol\u00e1s Leoz]], [[Rafael Salguero]], [[Ricardo Teixeira]], and [[Jack Warner]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/03/sports/soccer/fifa-officials-indicted-for-corruption.html |title= The Soccer Officials Indicted on Corruption Charges |newspaper= The New York Times |date= 3 December 2015 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> The [[2015 FIFA corruption case|resulting cases]] led FIFA to suspend many members, including [[Issa Hayatou]], and the end of Sepp Blatter's presidency of the organization.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/03/sports/soccer/sepp-blatter-to-resign-as-fifa-president.html |title= Sepp Blatter Decides to Resign as FIFA President in About-Face |newspaper= The New York Times |first1= Sam |last1= Borden |first2= Michael S. |last2= Schmidt |first3= Matt |last3= Apuzzo |date= 2 June 2015 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[United States Department of Justice]] unsealed further indictments against voters Nicol\u00e1s Leoz, Ricardo Teixeira, [[Julio Grondona]] of Argentina, and Jack Warner. The indictments spelled out how both the Russian and Qatari bids used [[shell corporation]]s and sham consulting contracts to pay voters between $1\u20135&nbsp;million for their support.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.si.com/soccer/2020/04/06/world-cup-bribery-votes-2018-russia-2022-qatar-jack-warner |title= Indictment Reveals Details of Alleged Bribes for 2018, 2022 FIFA World Cup Votes |agency= Associated Press |website= Sports Illustrated |date= 6 April 2020 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> Other voters who had previously pleaded guilty to accepting bribes, including [[Rafael Salguero]] of Guatemala, aided in the indictments, which when included with previous cases, mean that more than half of the voters in the 2018 and 2022 selection have been accused of wrongdoing related to their votes.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/sports/soccer/qatar-and-russia-bribery-world-cup-fifa.html |title= U.S. Prosecutors Say Qatar and Russia Bribed FIFA Officials to Win World Cup Bids |newspaper= The New York Times |first1= Tariq |last1= Panja |first2= Kevin |last2= Draper |date= 6 April 2020 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> Voter [[Franz Beckenbauer]] has also been accused by Swiss prosecutors of embezzlement and money laundering related to voting in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup#Bribery and corruption allegations|2006 FIFA World Cup host selection]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dw.com/en/franz-beckenbauer-probe-to-be-split-from-world-cup-investigation/a-49654583 |title= Franz Beckenbauer probe to be split from World Cup investigation |newspaper= Deutsche Welle |date= 19 July 2019 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref> while [[\u00c1ngel Mar\u00eda Villar]] was arrested in July 2017 for embezzlement, after previously being fined for failure to cooperate with investigations into vote-buying in the 2018 and 2022 host selection.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/27/angel-maria-villar-resigns-uefa-fifa-spain |title= \u00c1ngel Mar\u00eda Villar resigns from Uefa and Fifa positions after arrest in Spain |newspaper= The Guardian |date= 27 July 2017 |accessdate= 7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nIn reaction to the announcement there were celebrations on the streets of Doha.<ref>[[Al Jazeera English]]. 2 December 2010. 18:00 GMT.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9252710.stm|title=A World Cup miracle |date=2 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 December 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101203045716/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/9252710.stm| archivedate= 3 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The [[Qatar Stock Exchange]] responded strongly with increased participation in trading following the announcement.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-12/qatar-shares-head-for-2-year-high-on-growth-prospects-linked-to-world-cup.html | work=Bloomberg | first1=Zahra | last1=Hankir | first2=Ahmed | last2=Namatalla | title=Egypt Shares Gain on View Central Bank May Cut Interest Rates, Led by CIBE | date=12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] told his Qatari counterpart that hosting the tournament \"is a big athletic event which can promote football in the Persian Gulf area and Middle East region.\" He also said Iran was ready to help Qatar in hosting the event, while saying he hoped its neighbours \"could achieve a reasonable share to attend the games.\" al-Thani \"underlined [a] necessity of cooperation between regional countries to use and take advantage of the sport opportunity.\" He also added that Qatar's initiative would motivate its neighbours to \"promote and develop their football.\"<ref>http://cms.mfa.gov.ir/cms/cms/Tehran/en/Ifrem/1898912{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nRoger Burden, who had been acting chairman of England's Football Association, withdrew his application for the permanent post days after the vote, saying he could not trust FIFA members due to their actions.<ref>[[BBC NEWS]]: [[Web News]], 4 December 2010.</ref> England's bid executive Andy Anson said \"I think it has to [change] because otherwise why would Australia, the United States, Holland, Belgium, England ever bother bidding again?\"<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/12/04/3084628.htm?section=justin 'Why bother': Australia warned against future Cup bids] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205023754/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/12/04/3084628.htm?section=justin |date=5 December 2010 }}, Rachael Brown, ABC News, 4 December 2010</ref>\n\nThere was also a backlash from the media in the losing countries; the majority of British newspapers alleged that the World Cup had been \"sold\" to Russia, and the Spanish ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'', Dutch ''[[Algemeen Dagblad]]'', and the Japanese ''[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun|Nikkei]]'' made comments about the financial power of Russia and Qatar's commodity and energy reserves.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9253692.stm |work=BBC News | title=English media angry at Fifa 'fix' | date=3 December 2010}}</ref> American newspapers the ''[[Seattle Times]]'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' alleged collusion and corruption.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*  [https://web.archive.org/web/20100615200629/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/bidders/index.html FIFA 2018/2022 site]\n\n{{Bids for the 2018 and 2022 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{FIFA World Cup bids}}\n{{2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{2022 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Portal bar|Association football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2018 And 2022 Fifa World Cup Bids}}\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup bids| ]]\n[[Category:2022 FIFA World Cup bids| ]]\n[[Category:2010\u201311 in Qatari football]]\n[[Category:2010 in Russian football|World Cup bids]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup bids]]\n[[Category:Football in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Russia at the FIFA World Cup]]\n", "name_user": "Patrickneil", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAllegations of vote-buying:that", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_and_2022_FIFA_World_Cup_bids"}
{"title_page": "Francis Ford Coppola", "text_new": "{{short description|American film director and producer}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Francis Ford Coppola\n| image              = Francis Ford Coppola 2011 CC.jpg\n| caption            = Coppola at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1939|4|7|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.<!--Do not wikilink U.S. as per MOS:OVERLINK. As per Template:Infobox person, birthplace indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| alma_mater         = [[Hofstra University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])\n| occupation         = Film director, screenwriter, film producer, film composer\n| years_active       = 1962\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Woodside, Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, home town indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| parents            = [[Carmine Coppola]]<br />[[Italia Coppola|Italia Pennino]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Eleanor Coppola|Eleanor Jessie Neil]]|1963||end=}}\n| children           = [[Gian-Carlo Coppola]]<br />[[Roman Coppola]]<br />[[Sofia Coppola]]\n| relatives          = [[August Coppola]] (brother)<br />[[Talia Shire]] (sister)<br />[[Jason Schwartzman]] (nephew)<br />[[Nicolas Cage]] (nephew)<br />[[Gia Coppola]] (granddaughter)\n| family             = [[Coppola family tree|Coppola]]\n}}\n\n'''Francis Ford Coppola''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u0252|p|\u0259|l|\u0259}},<ref>{{Cite American Heritage Dictionary|Coppola |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/coppola |title=Coppola |work=[[Collins English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510081852/https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/coppola |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/Coppola,_Francis_Ford \"Coppola, Francis Ford\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510081858/https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/Coppola,_Francis_Ford |date=May 10, 2019 }} (US) and {{Cite Oxford Dictionaries|Coppola, Francis Ford |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> {{IPA-it|\u02c8k\u0254ppola|lang}}; born April 7, 1939)<ref>{{Britannica|136867}}</ref> is an American [[film director]], [[film producer|producer]], [[screenwriter]], [[film composer]], and [[vintner]]. He was a central figure in the [[New Hollywood]] filmmaking movement of the 1960s and 1970s. He is widely considered to be one of the greatest filmmakers of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/news-bfi/lists/francis-ford-coppola-10-essential-films |title=Francis Ford Coppola: 10 essential films |access-date=September 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111221255/https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/news-bfi/lists/francis-ford-coppola-10-essential-films |archive-date=January 11, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter directing ''[[The Rain People]]'' in 1969, Coppola co-wrote ''[[Patton (film)|Patton]]'' (1970), earning the [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]] along with [[Edmund H. North]]. Coppola's reputation as a filmmaker was cemented with the release of ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972). The film revolutionized movie-making in the [[gangster genre]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Barry |first=Langford |title=Film Genre: Hollywood and Beyond |year=2005 |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |page=134}}</ref> and was adored by the public and critics alike. ''The Godfather'' won three [[Academy Awards]]: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]], and [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] (shared with [[Mario Puzo]]).\n\n''[[The Godfather Part II]]'', which followed in 1974, became the first sequel to win the Academy Award for Best Picture. Highly regarded by critics, the film brought Coppola three more Academy Awards: Best Adapted Screenplay, [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], and Best Picture, and made him the second director (after [[Billy Wilder]]) to be so honored three times for the same film. ''[[The Conversation]]'', which Coppola directed, produced and wrote, was released that same year, winning the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[1974 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]. His next film, ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979), which notoriously had a lengthy and strenuous production, was widely acclaimed for its vivid depiction of the [[Vietnam War]]. The film won the Palme d'Or, making Coppola one of only eight filmmakers to have won that award twice.\n\nHis best-known films released since the start of the 1980s are the dramas ''[[The Outsiders (film)|The Outsiders]]'' and ''[[Rumble Fish]]'' (both 1983), the crime dramas ''[[The Cotton Club (film)|The Cotton Club]]'' (1984) and ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'' (1990), and the horror film ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'' (1992). A number of Coppola's relatives and children have become famous actors and filmmakers in their own right: his sister is the actress [[Talia Shire]]; his daughter [[Sofia Coppola]] and granddaughter [[Gia Coppola]] are directors, and the actors [[Jason Schwartzman]] and [[Nicolas Cage]] are his nephews. Coppola resides in [[Napa, California]].\n\n==Early life==\nCoppola was born in [[Detroit]], Michigan, to father [[Carmine Coppola]] (1910\u20131991),<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Carmine Coppola, 80, Conductor And Composer for His Son's Films |first=Wolfgang |last=Saxon |date=April 27, 1991 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/27/obituaries/carmine-coppola-80-conductor-and-composer-for-his-son-s-films.html |access-date=February 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230005701/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/27/obituaries/carmine-coppola-80-conductor-and-composer-for-his-son-s-films.html |archive-date=December 30, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> a [[flautist]] with the [[Detroit Symphony Orchestra]], and mother [[Italia Coppola]] (n\u00e9e Pennino; 1912\u20132004). Coppola is the middle of three children: his older brother was [[August Coppola]], his younger sister is actress [[Talia Shire]]. Born into a family of Italian immigrant ancestry, his paternal grandparents came to the United States from [[Bernalda]], [[Basilicata]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Cowie |first=Peter |title=Coppola: a biography |year=1988 |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=978-0-306-80598-1 |page=2 |nopp=true}}</ref> His maternal grandfather, popular Italian composer Francesco Pennino, emigrated from [[Naples]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web |author=Michael Cabanatuan |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Italia-Coppola-mother-of-filmmaker-2807695.php |title=Italia Coppola \u2013 mother of filmmaker |publisher=SFGate |date=January 23, 2004 |accessdate=May 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325233748/http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Italia-Coppola-mother-of-filmmaker-2807695.php |archive-date=March 25, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Coppola received his middle name in honor of [[Henry Ford]], not only because he was born in the [[Henry Ford Hospital]] but also because of his father's association with the automobile manufacturer. At the time of Coppola's birth, his father was a flautist as well as arranger and assistant orchestra director for ''[[The Ford Sunday Evening Hour]]'', an hour-long concert music radio series sponsored by the [[Ford Motor Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-08-14/features/8802190745_1_carmine-coppola-preston-tucker-francis-ford-coppola |title=The Dream And Its Men Francis Ford Coppola And George Lucas Immortalize A Legendary Car And Its Inventor on Film |work=Sun Sentinel |date=August 14, 1988 |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616141456/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-08-14/features/8802190745_1_carmine-coppola-preston-tucker-francis-ford-coppola |archive-date=June 16, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://partners.nytimes.com/books/first/s/schumacher-coppola.html |title=Francis Ford Coppola |publisher=Partners.nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601060422/http://partners.nytimes.com/books/first/s/schumacher-coppola.html |archive-date=June 1, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Two years after Coppola's birth, his father was named principal flautist for the [[NBC Symphony Orchestra]], and the family moved to New York, settling in [[Woodside, Queens]], where Coppola spent the remainder of his childhood.\n\nHaving contracted [[polio]] as a boy, Coppola was bedridden for large periods of his childhood, allowing him to indulge his imagination with homemade puppet theater productions. Reading ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' at age 15 was instrumental in developing his interest in theater.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 1\">{{Cite web |url=https://achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola |website=Academy of Achievement |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323144840/https://www.achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/ |archive-date=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Eager to be involved in film, he created [[8 mm film|8mm]] features edited from home movies with such titles as ''The Rich Millionaire'' and ''The Lost Wallet.''<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/1251 |title=Francis Ford Coppola |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727010642/http://www.filmbug.com/db/1251 |archive-date=July 27, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a child, Coppola was a mediocre student, but he was so interested in technology and engineering that his friends nicknamed him \"Science\".<ref name=\"The Gods of Filmmaking \" /> Trained initially for a career in music, he became proficient on the tuba and won a music scholarship to the [[New York Military Academy]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola\" /> Overall, Coppola attended 23 other schools<ref name=\"bravo\">{{cite episode |title=Francis Ford Coppola |episodelink=Inside the Actors Studio |series=Inside the Actors Studio |serieslink=Inside the Actors Studio |network=[[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]] |airdate= |season=7 |number=14 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18pZjqLaMMA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524202955/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18pZjqLaMMA |archivedate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> before he eventually graduated from Great Neck High School.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800017123/bio |title=Francis Ford Coppola biography |publisher=Yahoo! Movies |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823043110/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800017123/bio |archivedate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> He entered [[Hofstra University|Hofstra College]] in 1955 with a major in theater arts. There he was awarded a scholarship in playwriting. This furthered his interest in directing theater despite the disapproval of his father, who wanted him to study engineering.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 1\"/> Coppola was profoundly impressed after seeing [[Sergei Eisenstein]]'s ''[[October: Ten Days That Shook the World]]'', especially with the movie's quality of editing. It was at this time Coppola decided he would go into cinema rather than theater.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 1\" /> Coppola says he was tremendously influenced to become a writer early on by his brother, August.<ref name=bravo /> Coppola also gives credit to the work of [[Elia Kazan]] and for its influence on him as a director.<ref name=bravo /> Amongst Coppola's classmates at Hofstra were [[James Caan]], [[Lainie Kazan]] and radio artist [[Joe Frank]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Kristine McKenna |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2008-09-18/stage/off-the-radio |title=Joe Frank: Off the Radio \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Stage \u2013 Los Angeles |newspaper=LA Weekly |date=September 17, 2008 |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132602/http://www.laweekly.com/2008-09-18/stage/off-the-radio/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> He later cast Lainie Kazan in ''[[One from the Heart]]'' and Caan in ''[[The Rain People]]'' and ''[[The Godfather]]''.\n\nWhile pursuing his bachelor's degree, Coppola was elected president of the university's drama group, The Green Wig, and its musical comedy club, the Kaleidoscopians. He then merged the two into The Spectrum Players and under his leadership, they staged a new production each week. Coppola also founded the cinema workshop at Hofstra and contributed prolifically to the campus literary magazine.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola\" /> He won three D. H. Lawrence Awards for theatrical production and direction and received a Beckerman Award for his outstanding contributions to the school's theater arts division.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Biography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/autodoc/page/cop0bio-1 |title=Francis Ford Coppola Biography |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213223954/http://achievement.org/autodoc/page/cop0bio-1 |archivedate=December 13, 2010}}</ref> While a graduate student, one of his teachers was [[Dorothy Arzner]], whose encouragement Coppola later acknowledged as pivotal to his film career.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 1\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1960s===\nAfter earning his theater arts degree from Hofstra in 1960, Coppola enrolled in [[UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television|UCLA Film School]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hofstra.edu/home/news/ur/points-pride.html |title=Points of Pride \u2013 Hofstra University, New York |website=www.hofstra.edu}}</ref> There he directed a short horror film called ''The Two Christophers'', inspired by [[Edgar Allan Poe]]'s \"[[William Wilson (short story)|William Wilson]]\", and ''Ayamonn the Terrible'', a film about a sculptor's nightmares coming to life,<ref name=\"The Gods of Filmmaking \">{{cite web |url=http://www.ambidextrouspics.com/html/francis_ford_coppola.html |title=Francis Ford Coppola biography |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100710050242/http://www.ambidextrouspics.com/html/francis_ford_coppola.html |archivedate=July 10, 2010}}</ref> before directing the experimental [[Softcore pornography|softcore]] comedy ''[[Tonight for Sure]]'' in 1962.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" />\n\nAt UCLA, Coppola met undergraduate film major [[Jim Morrison]]. He later used Morrison's song \"[[The End (The Doors song)|The End]]\" in ''Apocalypse Now''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sparknotes.com/film/apocalypsenow/section3.rhtml |title=SparkNotes: Apocalypse Now: Score and Soundtrack |publisher=www.sparknotes.com |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504054656/http://www.sparknotes.com/film/apocalypsenow/section3.rhtml |archivedate=May 4, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe company that hired him for ''Tonight for Sure'' brought him back to re-cut a German film titled ''Mit Eva fing die S\u00fcnde an'' directed by [[Fritz Umgelter]]. He added some new 3-D color footage and earned a writer's and director's credit for ''[[The Bellboy and the Playgirls]]'', also a box-office failure. Coppola was hired as an assistant by [[Roger Corman]] and his first job for Corman was to dub and re-edit a Russian science fiction film, ''Nebo zovyot'', which he turned into a sex-and-violence monster movie entitled ''[[Battle Beyond the Sun]]'', released in 1962.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /> Impressed by Coppola's perseverance and dedication, Corman hired him as dialogue director on ''[[Tower of London (1962 film)|Tower of London]]'' (1962), sound man for ''[[The Young Racers]]'' (1963) and associate producer of ''[[The Terror (1963 film)|The Terror]]'' (1963).<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Biography\" />\n\nWhile on location in Ireland for ''The Young Racers'' in 1963, Corman, ever alert for an opportunity to produce a decent movie on a shoestring budget, persuaded Coppola to make a low-budget horror movie with funds left over from the movie.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Biography\" /> Coppola wrote a brief draft story idea in one night, incorporating elements from [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock's]] ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'',<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 3\">{{cite web |title=Francis Ford Coppola Biography and Interview |website=www.achievement.org |publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]] |url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/#interview |access-date=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323144840/https://www.achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/#interview |archive-date=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the result impressed Corman enough to give him the go-ahead. On a budget of $40,000 ($20,000 from Corman and $20,000 from another producer who wanted to buy the movie's English rights),<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 3\" /> Coppola directed in a period of nine days ''[[Dementia 13]]'', his first feature from his own screenplay. The film recouped its expenses and later became a [[cult film]] among horror buffs. It was on the sets of ''Dementia 13'' that he met his future wife [[Eleanor Coppola|Eleanor Jessie Neil]].\n\nIn 1965, Coppola won the annual Samuel Goldwyn Award for the best screenplay (''Pilma, Pilma'') written by a UCLA student.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola\" /> This secured him a job as a scriptwriter with [[Seven Arts Productions|Seven Arts]]. In between, he co-wrote the scripts for ''[[This Property Is Condemned]]'' (1966) and ''[[Is Paris Burning? (film)|Is Paris Burning?]]'' (1966). However, with fame still eluding him and partly out of desperation, Coppola bought the rights to the [[David Benedictus]] novel ''You're a Big Boy Now'' and fused it with a story idea of his own, resulting in ''[[You're a Big Boy Now]]'' (1966). This was his UCLA thesis project that also received a theatrical release via [[Warner Bros.]]<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /> This movie earned critical acclaim; [[Geraldine Page]] was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]], as well as a [[Golden Globe Award]], for her performance. It also earned Coppola his Master of Fine Arts Degree from [[UCLA School of Theater, Film and Television]] in 1967.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Biography\" /><ref name=\"UCLATFT\">[http://www.tft.ucla.edu/about/executive-board/francis-ford-coppola/ \"Profile: Francis Ford Coppola\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716061348/http://www.tft.ucla.edu/about/executive-board/francis-ford-coppola/ |date=July 16, 2014 }}, UCLA School of Theater, Film, and television, Executive Board</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of ''You're a Big Boy Now'', Coppola was offered the reins of the movie version of the Broadway musical ''[[Finian's Rainbow (1968 film)|Finian's Rainbow]]'', starring [[Petula Clark]] in her first American film and veteran [[Fred Astaire]]. Producer [[Jack L. Warner]] was nonplussed by Coppola's shaggy-haired, bearded, \"hippie\" appearance and generally left him to his own devices. He took his cast to the [[Napa County, California|Napa Valley]] for much of the outdoor shooting, but these scenes were in sharp contrast to those obviously filmed on a Hollywood soundstage, resulting in a disjointed look to the film. Dealing with outdated material at a time when the popularity of film musicals was already on the downslide, Coppola's result was only semi-successful, although Clark received a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] Best Actress nomination. The film introduced to him [[George Lucas]], who became his lifelong friend as well as production assistant in his next film ''[[The Rain People]]'' in 1969. It was written, directed and initially produced by Coppola himself, though as the movie advanced, he exceeded his budget and the studio had to underwrite the remainder of the movie.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /> The film won the [[Golden Shell]] at the 1969 [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival|San Sebastian Film Festival]].\n\nIn 1969, Coppola took it upon himself to subvert the studio system which he felt had stifled his visions, intending to produce mainstream pictures to finance off-beat projects and give first-time directors their chance to direct. He decided he would name his future studio \"Zoetrope\" after receiving a gift of [[zoetrope]]s from Mogens Scot-Hansen, founder of a studio called Lanterna Film and owner of a famous collection of early motion picture-making equipment. While touring [[Europe]], Coppola was introduced to alternative filmmaking equipment and inspired by the bohemian spirit of Lanterna Film, he decided he would build a deviant studio that would conceive and implement creative, unconventional approaches to filmmaking. Upon his return home, Coppola and George Lucas searched for a mansion in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]] to house the studio. However, in 1969, with equipment flowing in and no mansion found yet, the first home for [[American Zoetrope|Zoetrope Studio]] became a warehouse in [[San Francisco]] on Folsom Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zoetrope.com/zoe_films.cgi?page=history |title=A Brief History of American Zoetrope |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925031247/http://www.zoetrope.com/zoe_films.cgi?page=history |archive-date=September 25, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> The studio went on to become an early adopter of digital filmmaking, including some of the earliest uses of [[HDTV]]. In his book ''The American Cinema'', [[Andrew Sarris]] wrote, \"[Coppola] is probably the first reasonably talented and sensibly adaptable directorial talent to emerge from a university curriculum in film-making... [He] may be heard from more decisively in the future.\"<ref>[[Andrew Sarris|Sarris, Andrew]] (1968). ''The American Cinema'' (Paperback ed.). New York, NY: EP Dutton and Co., Inc. p. 210.</ref>\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:Francis Ford Coppola -1976.jpg|thumb|Coppola in 1976]]\nCoppola was at the forefront of a group of filmmakers known as the \"[[New Hollywood]]\" that emerged in the early 1970s with ideas that challenged conventional film-making. The group included [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Brian De Palma]], [[Terrence Malick]], [[Robert Altman]], [[Woody Allen]], [[William Friedkin]], [[Philip Kaufman]] and [[George Lucas]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.redroom.com/blog/steven-robert-travers/the-kid-stays-in-the-picture |title=The kid stays in the Picture |accessdate=October 21, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510091642/http://www.redroom.com/blog/steven-robert-travers/the-kid-stays-in-the-picture |archivedate=May 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====''Patton'' (1970)====\n{{Main|Patton (film)}}\nCoppola co-wrote the script for ''Patton'' in 1970 along with [[Edmund H. North]]. This earned him his first [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]. However, it was not easy for Coppola to convince [[Franklin J. Schaffner]] that [[Patton (film)#Opening|the opening scene]] would work. Coppola later revealed in an interview:<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/#interview |title=An Interview with Francis Ford Coppola |publisher=achievement.org |access-date=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323144840/https://www.achievement.org/achiever/francis-ford-coppola/#interview |archive-date=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Quotation| I wrote the script of ''Patton''. And the script was very controversial when I wrote it, because they thought it was so stylized. It was supposed to be like, sort of, you know, ''The Longest Day''. And my script of ''Patton'' was\u2014I was sort of interested in the reincarnation. And I had this very bizarre opening where he stands up in front of an American flag and gives this speech. Ultimately, I wasn't fired, but I was fired, meaning that when the script was done, they said, \"Okay, thank you very much,\" and they went and hired another writer and that script was forgotten. And I remember very vividly this long, kind of being raked over the coals for this opening scene.}}\"When the title role was offered to George C. Scott, he remembered having read Coppola's screenplay earlier. He stated flatly that he would accept the part only if they used Coppola's script. 'Scott is the one who resurrected my version,' says Coppola.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Gene |title=Godfather The Intimate Francis Ford Coppola |year=2004 |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |location=Lexington, Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-2304-6 |page=[https://archive.org/details/godfatherintimat00phil/page/32 32] |chapter=1 Point of Departure|chapter-url-access=registration|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/godfatherintimat00phil |url=https://archive.org/details/godfatherintimat00phil/page/32}}</ref>\nThe movie opens with Scott's rendering of Patton's famous military \"Pep Talk\" to members of the Third Army, set against a huge [[Flag of the United States|American flag]]. Coppola and North had to tone down Patton's actual language to avoid an [[Motion picture rating system#Restricted|R rating]]; in the opening monolog, the word \"fornicating\" replaced \"fucking\" when criticizing ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]''. Over the years, this opening monolog has become an iconic scene and has spawned parodies in numerous films, political cartoons and television shows.\n\n====''The Godfather'' (1972)====\n{{Main|The Godfather}}\nThe release of ''The Godfather'' in 1972 was a milestone in cinema. The near 3-hour-long epic, which chronicled the saga of the [[Corleone family]], received overwhelmingly positive reviews from critics and fetched Coppola the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], which he shared with Mario Puzo and two [[Golden Globe Award]]s: for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]. However, Coppola faced several difficulties while filming ''The Godfather''. He was not [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount's]] first choice to direct the movie; Italian director [[Sergio Leone]] was initially offered the job, but declined in order to direct his own gangster opus, ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Christopher Frayling |title=Spaghetti Westerns: Cowboys and Europeans from Karl May to Sergio Leone |url=https://books.google.com/?id=2bo9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA215 |year=1981 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-7100-0503-8 |page=215}}</ref> [[Peter Bogdanovich]] was then approached but he also declined the offer and made ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'' instead; Bogdanovich has often said that he would have cast [[Edward G. Robinson]] in the lead had he accepted the film. According to [[Robert Evans]], head of [[Paramount Pictures]] at the time, Coppola also did not initially want to direct the film because he feared it would glorify the Mafia and violence and thus reflect poorly on his [[Sicilian-American|Sicilian]] and Italian heritage; on the other hand, Evans specifically wanted an Italian-American to direct the film because his research had shown that previous films about the Mafia that were directed by non-Italians had fared dismally at the box office and he wanted to, in his own words, \"smell the spaghetti\". When Coppola hit upon the idea of making it a metaphor for American capitalism, however, he eagerly agreed to take the helm.<ref>''[[The Kid Stays in the Picture]]'' (2002), documentary film about Evans' life</ref>\n\nThere was disagreement between Paramount and Coppola on the issue of casting; Coppola stuck to his plan of casting [[Marlon Brando]] as [[Vito Corleone]], though Paramount wanted either [[Ernest Borgnine]] or [[Danny Thomas]]. At one point, Coppola was told by the then-president of Paramount that \"Marlon Brando will never appear in this motion picture\". After pleading with the executives, Coppola was allowed to cast Brando only if he appeared in the film for much less salary than his previous films, perform a screen-test and put up a bond saying that he would not cause a delay in the production (as he had done on previous film sets).<ref name=\"Look\">''The Godfather'' DVD Collection documentary ''A Look Inside'', [2001]</ref> Coppola chose Brando over [[Ernest Borgnine]] on the basis of Brando's screen test, which also won over the Paramount leadership. Brando later won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for his portrayal, which he refused to accept. Coppola would later recollect:<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Interview page 3\" />{{Quotation| ''The Godfather'' was a very unappreciated movie when we were making it. They were very unhappy with it. They didn't like the cast. They didn't like the way I was shooting it. I was always on the verge of getting fired. So it was an extremely nightmarish experience. I had two little kids, and the third one was born during that. We lived in a little apartment, and I was basically frightened that they didn't like it. They had as much as said that, so when it was all over I wasn't at all confident that it was going to be successful, and that I'd ever get another job.}}\nAfter it was released, the film received widespread praise. It went on to win multiple awards, including the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] for Coppola. The film routinely features at the top in various polls for the greatest movies ever. It has been selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]]. In addition, it was ranked third, behind ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', and ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' on the initial [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies]] list by the [[American Film Institute]]. It was moved up to second when the list was published again, in 2008.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web |work=American Film Institute |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/about/press/2007/100movies07.pdf |title=Citizen Kane Stands the test of Time |access-date=October 21, 2010 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61AtMtzUZ?url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/about/press/2007/100movies07.pdf |archive-date=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> Director [[Stanley Kubrick]] believed that ''The Godfather'' was possibly the greatest movie ever made and had without question the best cast.<ref>[http://www.visual-memory.co.uk/sk/memories/mh.htm Michael Herr for Vanity Fair] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207071514/http://www.visual-memory.co.uk/sk/memories/mh.htm |date=December 7, 2009 }} \"He watched ''The Godfather'' again the night before and was reluctantly suggesting for the tenth time that it was possibly the greatest movie ever made and certainly the best-cast.\"</ref>\n\n====''The Conversation'' (1974)====\n{{Main|The Conversation}}\nCoppola's next film, ''The Conversation'', further cemented his position as one of the most talented [[Auteur theory|auteurs]] of Hollywood.<ref name=\"Greatest Box-Office Bombs, Disasters and Flops of All-Time\" /> The movie was partly influenced by [[Michelangelo Antonioni]]'s ''[[Blowup]]'' (1966)<ref>Murch in Ondaatje, 2002, p. 152</ref> and generated much interest when news leaked that the film utilized the very same surveillance and wire-tapping equipment that members of the [[Nixon administration]] used to spy on political opponents prior to the [[Watergate scandal]]. Coppola insisted that this was purely coincidental. The script for ''The Conversation'' was completed in the mid-1960s (before the [[1968 United States Presidential election|election of Richard Nixon]]); the spying equipment used in the film was developed through research and use of technical advisers and not by newspaper stories about the Watergate break-in. However, the audience interpreted the film to be a reaction to both the Watergate scandal and its fallout. The movie was a critical success and Coppola won his first [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[1974 Cannes Film Festival]].\n\n====''The Great Gatsby'' (1974)====\n{{Main|The Great Gatsby (1974 film)}}\nDuring the filming of ''The Conversation'', Coppola wrote the screenplay for ''The Great Gatsby''. However, in the commentary track to the DVD of ''The Godfather'' Coppola states, \"I don't think that script was [actually] made.\"<ref>Commentary track, ''The Godfather'', ''The Godfather Collection'' 2008 Blu-ray, ASIN: B000NTPDSW,</ref>\n\n====''The Godfather Part II'' (1974)====\n{{Main|The Godfather Part II}}\n\nCoppola shot ''The Godfather Part II'' parallel to ''The Conversation'' and it was the last major American motion picture to be filmed in [[Technicolor]]. George Lucas commented on the film after its five-hour-long preview, telling Coppola: \"You have two films. Take one away, it doesn't work\", referring to the movie's portrayal of two parallel storylines; one of a young [[Vito Corleone]] and the other of his son [[Michael Corleone|Michael]]. In the director's commentary on the DVD edition of the film (released in 2002), Coppola states that this film was the first major motion picture to use \"Part II\" in its title. Paramount was initially opposed to his decision to name the movie ''The Godfather Part II''. According to Coppola, the studio's objection stemmed from the belief that audiences would be reluctant to see a film with such a title, as the audience would supposedly believe that, having already seen ''The Godfather'', there was little reason to see an addition to the original story. However, the success of ''The Godfather Part II'' began the Hollywood tradition of numbered sequels. The movie was released in 1974 and went on to receive tremendous critical acclaim, with many deeming it superior to its predecessor.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/430/430301p1.html |title=Featured Filmmaker: Francis Ford Coppola |date=July 28, 2003 |author=Stax |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511115731/http://movies.ign.com/articles/430/430301p1.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was nominated for 11 Academy Awards and received 6 Oscars, including 3 for Coppola: Best Picture, Best Adapted Screenplay and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].\n\n''The Godfather Part II'' is ranked as the No. 1 greatest movie of all time in TV Guide's \"50 Best Movies of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/tvguide.html |title=50 Greatest Movies (on TV and VIDEO) by TV Guide Magazine |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331175627/http://www.filmsite.org/tvguide.html |archive-date=March 31, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> and is ranked at No. 7 on Entertainment Weekly's list of the \"100 Greatest Movies of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/ew100.html |title=100 Greates Movies of All Time by Entertainment Weekly |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331185517/http://www.filmsite.org/ew100.html |archive-date=March 31, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film is also featured on movie critic [[Leonard Maltin]]'s list of the \"100 Must-See Films of the 20th Century\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/maltin2.html |title=100 Must-See Films of the 20th Century Part 2 by Leonard Maltin |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015115555/http://www.filmsite.org/maltin2.html |archive-date=October 15, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> as well as Roger Ebert's \"Great Movies\" list.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/section?category=greatmovies_fulllist |title=Great Movies |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105031018/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/section?category=greatmovies_fulllist |archive-date=January 5, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was also featured on [[Sight & Sound]]'s list of the ten greatest films of all time in 2002, ranking at No. 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/sightsound.html |title=10 Best Films of All Time Polls by Sight & Sound Magazine |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118083212/http://www.filmsite.org/sightsound.html |archive-date=November 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCoppola was the third director to have two nominations for Best Picture in the same year. Victor Fleming was the first in 1939 with ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' and ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''; Alfred Hitchcock repeated the feat the next year with ''[[Foreign Correspondent (film)|Foreign Correspondent]]'' and ''[[Rebecca (1940 film)|Rebecca]]''. Since Coppola, two other directors have done the same: [[Herbert Ross]] in 1977 with ''[[The Goodbye Girl]]'' and ''[[The Turning Point (1977 film)|The Turning Point]]'', and [[Steven Soderbergh]] in 2000 with ''[[Erin Brockovich (film)|Erin Brockovich]]'' and ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]''. Coppola, however, is the only one to have produced the pictures.\n\n====''Apocalypse Now'' (1979)====\n{{Main|Apocalypse Now}}\nFollowing the success of ''The Godfather'', ''The Conversation'' and ''The Godfather Part II'', Coppola began filming ''Apocalypse Now'', an adaptation of [[Joseph Conrad]]'s ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'' set in [[Cambodia]] during the [[Vietnam War]] (Coppola himself briefly appears as a TV news director). The production of the film was plagued by numerous problems, including [[typhoon]]s, nervous breakdowns, the firing of [[Harvey Keitel]], [[Martin Sheen]]'s heart attack, and extras from the Philippine military and half of the supplied helicopters leaving in the middle of scenes to go fight rebels. It was delayed so often it was nicknamed ''Apocalypse When?''<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola: The RT Interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1920998/news/1920998/francis-ford-coppola-the-rt-interview/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola: The RT Interview. The great director reflects upon his masterpiece Apocalypse Now |first=Tim |last=Ryan |date=October 15, 2010 |publisher=rottentomatoes.com |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020083621/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1920998/news/1920998/francis-ford-coppola-the-rt-interview/ |archive-date=October 20, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> The 1991 [[documentary film]] ''[[Hearts of Darkness: A Filmmaker's Apocalypse]]'', directed by [[Eleanor Coppola]] (Francis's wife), Fax Bahr and [[George Hickenlooper]], chronicles the difficulties the crew went through making ''Apocalypse Now'' and features behind-the-scenes footage filmed by Eleanor. After filming ''Apocalypse Now'', Coppola famously stated:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE0D91530F934A15752C1A967958260 |title=Hearts of Darkness: A Filmmaker's Apocalypse (1991) |date=November 27, 1991 |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=The New York Times |first=Janet |last=Maslin |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515003240/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE0D91530F934A15752C1A967958260 |archive-date=May 15, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> \"We were in the jungle, there were too many of us, we had access to too much money, too much equipment and little by little, we went insane.\"\n\nThe film was overwhelmingly lauded by critics when it finally appeared in 1979 and was selected for the 1979 [[Cannes Film Festival]], winning the [[Palme d'Or]] along with ''[[The Tin Drum (film)|The Tin Drum]]'', directed by [[Volker Schl\u00f6ndorff]]. When the film screened at Cannes, he quipped:<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola: The RT Interview\" /> \"My film is not about Vietnam, it is Vietnam.\" ''Apocalypse Now'''s reputation has grown in time and it is now regarded by many as a masterpiece of the [[New Hollywood]] era and is frequently cited as one of the greatest movies ever made.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/apoc.html |title=Apocalypse Now (Redux) (1979) (2001) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114220114/http://www.filmsite.org/apoc.html |archive-date=November 14, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.film.u-net.com/Movies/Reviews/Apocalypse_Now.html |title=Apocalypse Now (1979) |accessdate=October 18, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129074942/http://www.film.u-net.com/Movies/Reviews/Apocalypse_Now.html |archivedate=November 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://homevideo.about.com/od/dvdreview1/a/apocalypsenowra.htm |title=DVD Pick: Apocalypse Now \u2013 The Complete Dossier |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707075145/http://homevideo.about.com/od/dvdreview1/a/apocalypsenowra.htm |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] considered it to be the finest film on the Vietnam War and included it in his list for the 2002 ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' critics' poll of the greatest movies ever made.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/voter.php?forename=Roger&surname=Ebert |title=How the directors and critics voted |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903062342/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/voter.php?forename=Roger&surname=Ebert |archivedate=September 3, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19991128/REVIEWS08/911280301/1023 |title=Apocalypse Now (1979) by Roger Ebert |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216072521/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19991128%2FREVIEWS08%2F911280301%2F1023 |archive-date=December 16, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Coppola re-released ''Apocalypse Now'' as ''[[Apocalypse Now Redux]]'', restoring several sequences lost from the original 1979 cut of the film, thereby expanding its length to 200&nbsp;minutes.\n\nIn 2019, Coppola re-released ''Apocalypse Now'' as once more as ''Apocalypse Now (Final Cut)'', claiming that version to be his favorite.\n\n===1980s===\n\n====''One from the Heart'' (1982)====\n{{Main|One from the Heart}}\n''Apocalypse Now'' marked the end of the golden phase of Coppola's career.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" /> His musical fantasy ''One from the Heart'', although pioneering the use of video-editing techniques which are standard practice in the film industry today, ended with a disastrous box-office gross of US$636,796 against a US$26&nbsp;million budget,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=onefromtheheart.htm |title=One from the Heart |publisher=Boxofficemojo.com |access-date=October 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011075113/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=onefromtheheart.htm |archive-date=October 11, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> far from enough to recoup the costs incurred in the production of the movie and he was forced to sell his 23-acre Zoetrope Studio in 1983.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Biography\" /> He would spend the rest of the decade working to pay off his debts. (Zoetrope Studios finally filed for [[Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] in 1990, after which its name was changed to [[American Zoetrope]].)<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola (Yahoo!)\" />\n\n====''Hammett'' (1982)====\n{{Main|Hammett (film)}}\nFollowing the disastrous ''One from the Heart'', Coppola co-directed ''Hammett'' along with [[Wim Wenders]] in the same year. Although Coppola was not credited for his effort, according to one source, \"by the time the final version was released in 1982, only 30 percent of Wenders' footage remained and the rest was completely reshot by Coppola, whose mere 'executive producer' credit is just a technicality.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Hammett review |author=Noel Murray |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/42688 |publisher=The Onion A.V. Club |date=November 16, 2005 |accessdate=March 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008184703/http://www.avclub.com/content/node/42688 |archivedate=October 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====''The Outsiders'' (1983)====\n{{Main|The Outsiders (film)}}\nIn 1983, he directed ''The Outsiders'', a film adaptation of the [[The Outsiders (novel)|novel]] of the same name by [[S. E. Hinton]]. Coppola credited his inspiration for making the film to a suggestion from middle school students who had read the novel. ''The Outsiders'' is notable for being the breakout film for a number of young actors who would go on to become major stars. These included major roles for [[Matt Dillon]], [[Ralph Macchio]] and [[C. Thomas Howell]]. Also in the cast were [[Patrick Swayze]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Emilio Estevez]], [[Diane Lane]] and [[Tom Cruise]]. Matt Dillon and several others also starred in Coppola's related film, ''[[Rumble Fish]]'', which was also based on a S. E. Hinton novel and filmed at the same time as ''The Outsiders'' on-location in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]. Carmine Coppola wrote and edited the musical score, including the title song \"Stay Gold\", which was based upon a famous [[Robert Frost]] poem and performed for the movie by [[Stevie Wonder]]. The film was a moderate box-office success, drawing a revenue of $25&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=outsiders.htm |title=The Outsiders |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015022324/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=outsiders.htm |archive-date=October 15, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> against a budget of $10&nbsp;million.\n\n====''Rumble Fish'' (1983)====\n{{Main|Rumble Fish}}\n\n''Rumble Fish'' was based on the [[Rumble Fish (novel)|novel]] of the same name by [[S. E. Hinton]], who also co-wrote the screenplay. Shot in black-and-white as an homage to German expressionist films, ''Rumble Fish'' centers on the relationship between a revered former gang leader ([[Mickey Rourke]]) and his younger brother, Rusty James ([[Matt Dillon]]). The film bombed at the box office, earning a meager $2.5&nbsp;million against a budget of $10&nbsp;million and once again aggravated Coppola's financial troubles.<ref name=\"BoxOffice\">{{cite news |last= |first= |coauthors= |title=''Rumble Fish'' |work=Box Office Mojo |date= |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rumblefish.htm |accessdate=December 30, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625134342/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rumblefish.htm |archive-date=June 25, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''The Cotton Club'' (1984)====\n{{Main|The Cotton Club (film)}}\nIn 1984 Coppola directed the [[Robert Evans]]-produced ''The Cotton Club''. The film was nominated for several awards, including Golden Globes for Best Director and Best Picture (Drama) and the Oscars for Best Film Editing and Best Art-Direction. However, the film failed miserably at the box-office, recouping only $25.9&nbsp;million of the $47.9&nbsp;million privately invested by brothers Fred and Ed Doumani.<ref name=\"Greatest Box-Office Bombs, Disasters and Flops of All-Time\">[http://www.filmsite.org/greatestflops10.html Greatest Box-Office Bombs, Disasters and Flops of All-Time] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122224834/http://www.filmsite.org/greatestflops10.html |date=November 22, 2010 }}. Retrieved October 18, 2010.</ref>\n\n====''Rip Van Winkle'' (1984)====\n{{Main|Rip Van Winkle#Adaptations|l1=Rip Van Winkle}}\nThe same year he directed an episode of ''[[Faerie Tale Theatre]]'' entitled ''Rip Van Winkle'', where [[Harry Dean Stanton]] played the lead role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/faerie_tale_theatre_rip_van_winkle/ |title=Faerie Tale Theatre \u2013 Rip Van Winkle (1984) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204145606/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/faerie_tale_theatre_rip_van_winkle/ |archivedate=December 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====''Captain EO'' (1986)====\n{{Main|Captain EO}}\nIn 1986, Coppola directed ''Captain EO'', a 17-minute space fantasy for [[Disney theme parks]] executive produced by [[George Lucas]], starring singer [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.papermag.com/hollyweird-captain-eo-2608363436.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1 |title=Michael Jackson and the Making of Disney's 'Captain EO' |last=Taylor |first=Trey |date=September 27, 2018 |website=Paper |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113195058/https://www.papermag.com/hollyweird-captain-eo-2608363436.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1 |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====''Peggy Sue Got Married'' (1986)====\n{{Main|Peggy Sue Got Married}}\nIn 1986 Coppola released the comedy ''Peggy Sue Got Married'' starring [[Kathleen Turner]], Coppola's nephew [[Nicolas Cage]], and [[Jim Carrey]]. Much like ''[[The Outsiders (film)|The Outsiders]]'' and ''[[Rumble Fish]]'', ''Peggy Sue Got Married'' centered around teenage youth. The film earned Coppola positive feedback and provided Kathleen Turner her first and only Oscar nomination. It was the first box-office success for Coppola since ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=peggysuegotmarried.htm |title=Peggy Sue Got Married |website=Box Office Mojo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912040318/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=peggysuegotmarried.htm |archivedate=September 12, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the film ranked number 17 on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s list of \"50 Best High School Movies\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/report/0,6115,1532588_1_0_,00.html |title=Entertainment Weekly's 50 Best High School Movies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905083021/http://www.ew.com/ew/report/0%2C6115%2C1532588_1_0_%2C00.html |archivedate=September 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\n====''Gardens of Stone'' (1987)====\n{{Main|Gardens of Stone}}\nThe following year, Coppola re-teamed with [[James Caan (actor)|James Caan]] for ''Gardens of Stone'', but the film was overshadowed by the death of Coppola's eldest son [[Gian-Carlo Coppola]] during the film's production. The movie was not a critical success and performed poorly at the box office, earning only $5.6&nbsp;million against a budget of $13&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=gardensofstone.htm |title=Gardens of Stone |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323064410/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=gardensofstone.htm |archive-date=March 23, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' (1988)====\n{{Main|Tucker: The Man and His Dream}}\nCoppola directed ''Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' the following year. A biopic based on the life of [[Preston Tucker]] and his attempt to produce and market the [[Tucker automobile|Tucker '48]], Coppola had originally conceived the project as a musical with [[Marlon Brando]] after the release of ''[[The Godfather Part II]]''. Ultimately it was [[Jeff Bridges]] who played the role of Preston Tucker. Budgeted at $24&nbsp;million, the film received positive reviews and earned three nominations at the [[62nd Academy Awards]], although its $19.65&nbsp;million box office was a disappointment. Two awards came its way: [[Martin Landau]] won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe for Best Supporting Actor]] and [[Dean Tavoularis]] took [[BAFTA Award for Best Production Design|BAFTA's honors for Best Production Design]].\n\n====''New York Stories'' (1989)====\n{{Main|New York Stories#Life Without Zo\u00eb|l1=New York Stories}}\nIn 1989, Coppola teamed up with fellow [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning directors [[Martin Scorsese]] and [[Woody Allen]] for an [[anthology film]] called ''[[New York Stories]]''. Coppola directed the ''Life Without Zo\u00eb'' segment, starring his sister [[Talia Shire]] and also co-wrote the film with his daughter [[Sofia Coppola]]. ''Life Without Zo\u00eb'' was mostly panned by critics and was generally considered the segment that brought the film's overall quality down.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.currentfilm.com/dvdreviews4/newyorkstoriesdvd.html |title=New York Stories: DVD Information |accessdate=October 18, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123144435/http://currentfilm.com/dvdreviews4/newyorkstoriesdvd.html |archivedate=November 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19890303/REVIEWS/903030306/1023 |title=New York Stories by Roger Ebert |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107225055/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19890303%2FREVIEWS%2F903030306%2F1023 |archive-date=November 7, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> Hal Hinson of [[The Washington Post]] wrote a particularly scathing review, stating that \"It's impossible to know what Francis Coppola's ''Life Without Zo\u00eb'' is. Co-written with his daughter Sofia, the film is a mystifying embarrassment; it's by far the director's worst work yet.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/newyorkstoriespghinson_a0a8de.htm |title=New York Stories (PG) |date=March 3, 1989 |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=The Washington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121124824/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/newyorkstoriespghinson_a0a8de.htm |archive-date=January 21, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\n\n====''The Godfather Part III'' (1990)====\n{{Main|The Godfather Part III}}\n[[File:Francis Ford Coppola Cannes.jpg|thumb|upright|Francis Ford Coppola at the [[1996 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nIn 1990, he released the third and final chapter of ''The Godfather'' series: ''The Godfather Part III''. Coppola felt that the first two films had told the complete Corleone saga. Coppola intended ''Part III'' to be an epilog to the first two films.<ref name=pre>{{cite web |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/the-godfather-part-iii-makes-a-little-more-sense-in-the-streaming-era |title='The Godfather: Part III' makes a little more sense in the streaming era |publisher=sfchronicle.com |date=December 26, 2019 |access-date=December 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227100958/https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/the-godfather-part-iii-makes-a-little-more-sense-in-the-streaming-era |archive-date=December 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his [[audio commentary]] for ''Part II'', he stated that only a dire financial situation caused by the failure of ''[[One from the Heart]]'' (1982) compelled him to take up [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]]'s long-standing offer to make a third installment.<ref name=\"DVDcom\">{{cite news |work=The Godfather Part II DVD |title=DVD commentary featuring Francis Ford Coppola |date=2005}}</ref> Coppola and Puzo preferred the title ''The Death of Michael Corleone'', but Paramount Pictures found that unacceptable.<ref name=pre/> While not as critically acclaimed as the first two films,<ref name=\"The Godfather Part III\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/thegodfatherpartiiirhinson_a0a9c5.htm |title=The Godfather Part III by Hal Hinson |date=December 25, 1990 |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |work=The Washington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208125614/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/thegodfatherpartiiirhinson_a0a9c5.htm |archive-date=February 8, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/15/the_godfather_part_iii_1990_review.shtml |title=The Godfather Part III (1990) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315062016/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/15/the_godfather_part_iii_1990_review.shtml |archive-date=March 15, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> it was still a box office success, earning $136&nbsp;million against a budget of $54&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=godfather3.htm |title=The Godfather Part III |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119162248/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=godfather3.htm |archive-date=November 19, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some reviewers criticized the casting of Coppola's daughter [[Sofia Coppola|Sofia]], who had stepped into the leading role of [[Mary Corleone]] which had been abandoned by [[Winona Ryder]] just as filming began.<ref name=\"The Godfather Part III\">[http://www.reelviews.net/movies/g/godfather3.html The Godfather Part III] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219153651/http://reelviews.net/movies/g/godfather3.html |date=December 19, 2010 }}. Retrieved October 18, 2010.</ref> Despite this, ''The Godfather Part III'' went on to gather 7 [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]. The film failed to win any of these awards, the only film in the trilogy to do so.\n\n====''Bram Stoker's Dracula'' (1992)====\n{{Main|Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)}}\nIn 1992, Coppola directed and produced ''Bram Stoker's Dracula''. Adapted from [[Bram Stoker]]'s [[Dracula|novel]], it was intended to be more faithful to the book than previous film adaptations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://classic-horror.com/reviews/bram_stokers_dracula_1992 |title=Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921232725/http://classic-horror.com/reviews/bram_stokers_dracula_1992 |archive-date=September 21, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Coppola cast [[Gary Oldman]] in the film's title role, with [[Keanu Reeves]], [[Winona Ryder]] and [[Anthony Hopkins]] in supporting roles. The movie became a box-office hit, grossing $82,522,790 domestically, making it the 15th highest-grossing film of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1992&p=.htm |title=1992 Domestic Grosses |publisher=Boxofficemojo.com |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629015451/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1992&p=.htm |archive-date=June 29, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> It fared even better overseas grossing $133,339,902 for a total worldwide gross of $215,862,692 against a budget of $40&nbsp;million,<ref>[http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1992/0BRMS.php Movie Dracula \u2013 Box Office Data, News, Cast Information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419225227/http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1992/0BRMS.php |date=April 19, 2009 }} from The Numbers</ref> making it the 9th highest-grossing film of the year worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=1992&p=.htm |title=Dracula box-office collections |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726204727/http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=1992&p=.htm |archivedate=July 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The film won Academy Awards for [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Costume Design]], [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Makeup]] and [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Sound Editing]].\n\n====''Jack'' (1996)====\n{{Main|Jack (1996 film)}}\nCoppola's next project was ''Jack'', which was released on August 9, 1996. It starred [[Robin Williams]] as Jack Powell, a ten-year-old boy whose cells are growing at four times the normal rate, so at the age of ten he looks like a 40-year-old man. With [[Diane Lane]], [[Brian Kerwin]] and [[Bill Cosby]], ''Jack'' also featured [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Fran Drescher]] and [[Michael McKean]] in supporting roles. Although a moderate box-office success, grossing $58&nbsp;million domestically on an estimated $45&nbsp;million budget,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jack.htm |title=Jack |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120093705/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jack.htm |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> it was panned by critics, many of whom disliked the film's abrupt contrast between actual comedy and tragic melodrama.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blackwelder |first1=Rob |title=SPLICEDwire: \"Jack\" review |url=http://splicedwire.com/96reviews/jack.html |website=SPLICEDwire |publisher=Rob Blackwelder |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210182425/http://splicedwire.com/96reviews/jack.html |archive-date=December 10, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was also unfavourably compared with the 1988 film ''[[Big (film)|Big]]'', in which [[Tom Hanks]] also played a child in a grown man's body.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ebert |first1=Roger |title=Jack movie review & film summary (1996) |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/jack-1996 |website=RogerEbert.com |publisher=Ebert Digital LLC |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031221/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/jack-1996 |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Most critics felt that the screenplay was poorly written, not funny and the dramatic material was unconvincing and unbelievable.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baumgarten |first1=Marjorie |title=Jack - Movie Review |url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/1996-08-09/jack/ |website=The Austin Chronicle |publisher=Austin Chronicle Corp. |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031222/https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/1996-08-09/jack/ |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other critics felt that Coppola was too talented to be making this type of film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gleiberman |first1=Owen |title=Jack |url=https://ew.com/article/1996/08/09/jack/ |website=Entertainment Weekly |publisher=Meredith Corporation |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031220/https://ew.com/article/1996/08/09/jack/ |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Although ridiculed for making the film, Coppola has defended it, saying he is not ashamed of the final cut of the movie. He had been friends with Robin Williams for many years and had always wanted to work with him as an actor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Francis Ford Coppola - Biography |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000338/bio#quotes |website=IMDb |publisher=IMDb.com, Inc. |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410032924/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000338/bio#quotes |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> When Williams was offered the screenplay for ''Jack'', he said he would only agree to do it if Coppola agreed to sign on as director.\n\n====''The Rainmaker'' (1997)====\n{{Main|The Rainmaker (1997 film)}}\nThe last film Coppola directed in the 1990s, ''The Rainmaker'' was based on the 1995 [[The Rainmaker (John Grisham)|novel]] of the same name by [[John Grisham]]. An ensemble courtroom drama, the film was well received by critics, earning an 83% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1080867-rainmaker/ |title=The Rainmaker |access-date=October 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927123727/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1080867-rainmaker/ |archive-date=September 27, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave ''The Rainmaker'' three stars out of four, remarking: \"I have enjoyed several of the movies based on Grisham novels... but I've usually seen the storyteller's craft rather than the novelist's art being reflected. By keeping all of the little people in focus, Coppola shows the variety of a young lawyer's life, where every client is necessary and most of them need a lot more than a lawyer.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19971121/REVIEWS/711210304/1023 ''The Rainmaker'' review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314064335/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F19971121%2FREVIEWS%2F711210304%2F1023 |date=March 14, 2013 }} by [[Roger Ebert]], Chicago Sun-Times, November 21, 1997</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] also gave the film three stars out of four, saying that \"the intelligence and subtlety of ''The Rainmaker'' took me by surprise\" and that the film \"stands above any other filmed Grisham adaptation\".<ref>[http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/r/rainmaker.html ''The Rainmaker'' review] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024053051/http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/r/rainmaker.html |date=October 24, 2017 }} by [[James Berardinelli]], ReelViews.net, 1997</ref> Grisham said of the film, \"To me it's the best adaptation of any of [my books]... I love the movie. It's so well done.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,587688,00.html |title=Grisham v. Grisham: John Grisham issues judgment on all his novels |first=Tina |last=Jordan |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=February 13, 2004 |date=February 6, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626033200/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,587688,00.html |archive-date=June 26, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film grossed about $45&nbsp;million domestically.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=rainmaker.htm |title=The Rainmaker (1997) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607000224/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=rainmaker.htm |archive-date=June 7, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> This would be more than the estimated production budget of $40&nbsp;million, but a disappointment compared with previous films adapted from Grisham novels.\n\n====''Pinocchio'' dispute with Warner Bros.====\nIn the late 1980s, Coppola started considering concepts for a motion picture based upon the 19th century novel ''[[The Adventures of Pinocchio]]'' and in 1991, Coppola and [[Warner Bros.]] began discussing the project as well as two others involving the life of [[J. Edgar Hoover]] and the children's novel ''[[The Secret Garden#Dramatic adaptations|The Secret Garden]]''. These discussions led to negotiations for Coppola to both produce and direct the ''Pinocchio'' project for Warners, as well as ''[[The Secret Garden (1993 film)|The Secret Garden]]'' (which was made in 1993 and produced by [[American Zoetrope]], but directed by [[Agnieszka Holland]]) and ''Hoover'', which never came to fruition. (A film was eventually to be made by [[Clint Eastwood]] in 2011 as ''[[J. Edgar]]'', which was distributed by Warners.)\n\nBut, in mid-1991, Coppola and Warners came to disagreement over the compensation to be paid to Coppola for his directing services on ''Pinocchio''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.schleimerlaw.com/CourtAppealCoppola.htm |title=In the Court of Appeal of the State of California Second Appelate District |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716014033/http://www.schleimerlaw.com/CourtAppealCoppola.htm |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The parties deferred this issue and finally a settlement was reached in 1998, when the jurors in the resultant court case awarded Coppola $20&nbsp;million as compensation for losing the ''Pinocchio'' film project. However, they also awarded him a further $60&nbsp;million in punitive damages on top, stemming from his charges that Warner Bros. sabotaged his intended version. This is the largest civil financial verdict ever against a Hollywood studio.\n\n====''Contact'' dispute with Carl Sagan/Warner Bros.====\n{{Main|Contact (1997 American film)#Lawsuits|l1=Contact}}\nDuring the filming of ''Contact'' on December 28, 1996, Coppola filed a lawsuit against [[Carl Sagan]] and [[Warner Bros.]] Sagan had died a week earlier<ref name=\"Cope\">{{cite news |author=Staff |url=http://www.variety.com/vstory/VR1117436227 |title=Zoetrope sues over 'Contact' |date=December 30, 1996 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=January 26, 2009}}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"Scott\">{{cite news |author=Janet Shprintz |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117780544 |title=Coppola loses 'Contact' |date=February 13, 2000 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=January 28, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025010810/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117780544 |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Coppola claimed that Sagan's novel ''[[Contact (novel)|Contact]]'' was based on a story the pair had developed for a [[television special]] back in 1975, titled ''First Contact''.<ref name=Cope/> Under their development agreement, Coppola and Sagan were to split proceeds from the project with [[American Zoetrope]] and [[Sesame Workshop|Children's Television Workshop Productions]], as well as any novel Sagan would write. The TV program was never produced, but in 1985, [[Simon & Schuster]] published Sagan's ''Contact'' and Warner Bros. moved forward with development of a film adaptation. Coppola sought at least $250,000 in compensatory damages and an injunction against production or distribution of the film.<ref name=Cope/> Even though Sagan was shown to have violated some of the terms of the agreement, the case was dismissed in February 1998 because Coppola had waited too long to file suit.<ref name=\"dismiss\">{{cite news |author=Paul Karon |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117467799 |title=Coppola's 'Contact' claim is dismissed |date=February 17, 1998 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=January 28, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025010840/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117467799 |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''Supernova'' re-edit====\n{{Main|Supernova (2000 film)}}\nIn August 1999, Coppola was brought in by MGM to supervise another re-editing of the film ''[[Supernova (2000 film)|Supernova]]'' costing $1&nbsp;million at his American Zoetrope facility in Northern California. This work included digitally placing [[Angela Bassett]]'s and [[James Spader]]'s faces on the bodies of (a computer-tinted) [[Robin Tunney]] and [[Peter Facinelli]] so that their characters could enjoy a love scene.<ref name=\"horn\">{{cite news |title=A film named after a disaster of stellar proportions? Hmm...: Supernova: Directed by Walter Hill. And Jack Sholder. And Francis Ford Coppola |last=Horn |first=John |newspaper=National Post |date=January 14, 2000 |page=B3}}</ref> But even Coppola's re-edited version had negative test screening and didn't get the PG-13 rating by the MPAA that the studio wanted. Creature designer [[Patrick Tatopoulos]], whose special effects were mostly cut out from the film, said that [[Walter Hill]] wanted the film to be much more grotesque, strange and disturbing while MGM wanted to make it more of a hip, sexy film in space and they didn't want a full-blown makeup effects film. \"I hope that my experience in the film industry has helped improve the picture and rectified some of the problems that losing a director caused,\" said Coppola.<ref name=\"horn\"/> By October 1999, [[MGM]] decided to sell the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tnmc.org/news/supernova.html |title=TNMC Movies: Bad Movie News: Supernova |work=tnmc.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306004240/http://www.tnmc.org/news/supernova.html|archive-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref> The film was eventually released on January 17, 2000, almost two years later than planned.<ref name=\"super\">Lights,camera... new directorHarrison, Genevieve. The Guardian (1959-2003) [London (UK)] June 16, 2000: B8.</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n\n====''Youth Without Youth'' (2007)====\n[[File:Francis Ford Coppola(CannesPhotoCall) crop.jpg|thumb|Francis Ford Coppola at the [[2001 Cannes Film Festival]].]]\n{{Main|Youth Without Youth (film)}}\nAfter a 10-year hiatus, Coppola returned to directing with ''Youth Without Youth'' in 2007, based on the [[Youth Without Youth (novella)|novella]] of the same name by Romanian author [[Mircea Eliade]]. The film was poorly reviewed, currently holding a 30% 'rotten' rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/youth_without_youth/ |title=Youth Without Youth (2007) |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831142242/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/youth_without_youth/ |archive-date=August 31, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was made for about $19&nbsp;million and was given a limited release, only managing $2,624,759 at the box-office.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=youthwithoutyouth.htm |title=Youth Without Youth |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110808205320/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=youthwithoutyouth.htm |archive-date=August 8, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, Coppola announced his plans to produce his own films in order to avoid the marketing input that goes into most films that results in trying to make films appeal to too wide an audience.\n\n====''Tetro'' (2009)====\n{{Main|Tetro}}\nIn 2009, Coppola released ''Tetro''. It was \"set in Argentina, with the reunion of two brothers. The story follows the rivalries born out of creative differences passed down through generations of an artistic Italian immigrant family.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=39343 |title=Tetro |work=ComingSoon.net |publisher=Coming Soon Media, L.P. |accessdate=August 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024131708/http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=39343 |archive-date=October 24, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film received generally positive reviews from critics. On [[Metacritic]], the film has an average metascore of 63% based on 19 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/tetro |title=Tetro (2009): Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=June 23, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615091942/http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/tetro |archive-date=June 15, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 70% of critics gave positive reviews based on 105 reviews with an average score of 6.3/10.<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tetro/ |title=Tetro Movie Reviews, Pictures |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=IGN Entertainment |accessdate=June 23, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609121609/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tetro/ |archive-date=June 9, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> Overall, the Rotten Tomatoes consensus was: \"A complex meditation on family dynamics, ''Tetro'''s arresting visuals and emotional core compensate for its uneven narrative.\"<ref name=\"rt\" /> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 3 stars, praising the film for being \"boldly operatic, involving family drama, secrets, generations at war, melodrama, romance and violence\". Ebert also praised [[Vincent Gallo]]'s performance and claimed that [[Alden Ehrenreich]] is \"the new [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?ID=/20090617/REVIEWS/906179993 |title=Tetro Movie Review \u2013 Roger Ebert |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=June 23, 2009 |date=June 17, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606111859/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?ID=%2F20090617%2FREVIEWS%2F906179993 |archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Todd McCarthy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a B+ judging that \"when Coppola finds creative [[nirvana]], he frequently has trouble delivering the full goods.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940242.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&query=tetro |title=Tetro Review \u2013 Variety |magazine=Variety |date=May 14, 2009 |accessdate=June 23, 2009 |first=Todd |last=McCarthy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619133820/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940242.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&query=tetro |archive-date=June 19, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' gave the film a mixed review, praising Ehrenreich's performance, but claiming Coppola \"has made a movie in which plenty happens, but nothing rings true.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1904079,00.html |title=Coppola's Tetro: An Offer You Can Refuse |accessdate=June 23, 2009 |magazine=TIME Magazine |date=June 11, 2009 |first=Richard |last=Corliss |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615082515/http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1904079,00.html |archive-date=June 15, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> It has made $2,636,774 worldwide,<ref>{{cite web |title=Tetro (2009) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tetro.htm |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 9, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003155745/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=tetro.htm |archive-date=October 3, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> against a budget of $5,000,000.\n\n===2010s===\n\n====''Twixt'' (2011)====\n{{Main|Twixt (film)}}\n''Twixt'', starring [[Val Kilmer]], [[Elle Fanning]], [[Joanne Whalley]] and [[Bruce Dern]] and narrated by [[Tom Waits]], was released to film festivals in late 2011<ref>{{cite web |author=Steven Davies |url=http://www.horror-asylum.com/news/article.asp?item=8659 |title=International One-Sheet For Francis Ford Coppola's New Mystery Thriller 'Twixt'; Horror Movie Entertainment News and Reviews |publisher=Horror-asylum.com |date= |accessdate=November 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405155111/http://www.horror-asylum.com/news/article.asp?item=8659 |archive-date=April 5, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and was released theatrically in early 2012. It received critical acclaim in France,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hypable.com/2012/04/13/francis-ford-coppolas-twixt-opens-in-france-to-critical-acclaim/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola's 'Twixt' opens in France to critical acclaim \u2022 Hypable |publisher=Hypable.com |date=April 13, 2012 |accessdate=November 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524153050/http://www.hypable.com/2012/04/13/francis-ford-coppolas-twixt-opens-in-france-to-critical-acclaim/ |archivedate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> but mostly negative reviews elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web |title=Twixt (2012) |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/twixt/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=April 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408032749/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/twixt/ |archive-date=April 8, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''Distant Vision'' (2015)====\n{{Main|Distant Vision}}\n\n''Distant Vision'' is a semi-autobiographical unfinished live broadcast project wrought in real-time. [[Proof of concept]]s were tested before limited audiences at [[Oklahoma City Community College]] in June 2015 and [[UCLA School of Theater]] in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://pioneer.occc.edu/hollywood-legend-brings-vision-to-occc/ |title=Hollywood legend brings vision to OCCC|access-date=October 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021021253/https://pioneer.occc.edu/hollywood-legend-brings-vision-to-occc/|archive-date=October 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2020s===\n\n====''Megalopolis'' (TBA)====\nIn April 2019, Coppola announced that he plans to direct ''Megalopolis'', which he had been developing for many years prior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/05/09/francis-ford-coppola-says-he-has-abandoned-megalopolis-project/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola Says He Has Abandoned 'Megalopolis' Project |accessdate=October 18, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612021843/http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/05/09/francis-ford-coppola-says-he-has-abandoned-megalopolis-project/|archive-date=June 12, 2012}}</ref> Speaking to ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' he said \"[...] I plan this year to begin my longstanding ambition to make a major work utilizing all I have learned during my long career, beginning at age 16 doing theater, and that will be an epic on a grand scale, which I've titled ''Megalopolis''\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Fleming Jr |url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/francis-ford-coppola-megalopolis-directing-this-year-1202588167/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404011947/https://deadline.com/2019/04/francis-ford-coppola-megalopolis-directing-this-year-1202588167/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola Ready To Make 'Megalopolis' And Is Eyeing Cast |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=August 18, 2019 |archivedate=April 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He had planned to direct this movie, a story about the aftermath and reconstruction of New York City after a mega-disaster, but after the city was hit by the real life disaster of the [[September 11 attacks]], the project was seen as being too sensitive.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bangstyle.com/2012/04/best-films-never-made/ |title=10 Best Films Never Made |publisher=Bangstyle.com |date=April 17, 2012 |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531165626/http://www.bangstyle.com/2012/04/best-films-never-made/ |archivedate=May 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial ventures==\n\n===American Zoetrope===\nIn 1971, Coppola and [[George Lucas]] co-produced the latter's first film, ''[[THX 1138]]''. Shortly after completion of production they brought the finished film to [[Warner Bros.]], along with several other scripts for potential projects at their newly founded company, [[American Zoetrope]]. However, studio executives strongly disliked all the scripts, including ''THX'' and demanded that Coppola repay the $300,000 they had loaned him for the Zoetrope studio, as well as insisting on cutting five minutes from the film. The debt nearly closed Zoetrope and forced Coppola to reluctantly focus on ''[[The Godfather]]''.<ref name=\"Featured Filmmaker: Francis Ford Coppola\">[http://movies.ign.com/articles/430/430301p1.html Featured Filmmaker: Francis Ford Coppola \u2013 IGN] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511115731/http://movies.ign.com/articles/430/430301p1.html |date=May 11, 2011 }}. Retrieved October 18, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Zoetrope Virtual Studio===\n\nHis company [[American Zoetrope]] also administers the Zoetrope Virtual Studio, a complete motion picture production studio for members only. Launched in June 2000, the culmination of more than four years work, it brings together departments for screenwriters, directors, producers and other filmmaker artists, plus new departments for other creative endeavors. Filmmaker members can workshop a wide range of film arts, including music, graphics, design and film and video.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Inglenook Winery===\nCoppola, with his family, expanded his business ventures to include winemaking in California's [[Napa Valley AVA|Napa Valley]], when in 1975 he purchased the former home and adjoining vineyard of [[Gustave Niebaum]] in [[Rutherford, California]] using proceeds from the first movie in the ''[[Godfather Trilogy|Godfather]]'' trilogy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hamlin |first=Suzanne |authorlink= |author2= |title=A Director's Vision for Celebrating Food, Wine and Film |work=[[The New York Times]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher= |location=Rutherford, CA |date=July 10, 1996 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C02E3DB1139F933A25754C0A960958260 |doi= |id= |accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref> His winery produced its first vintage in 1977 with the help of his father, wife and children stomping the grapes barefoot and every year the family has a harvest party to continue the tradition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novusvinum.com/interviews/coppola.html |title=Francis Ford Coppola Winemaker and Sommelier Interviews |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |publisher=Novus Vinum |date=September 17, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511121625/http://www.novusvinum.com/interviews/coppola.html |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter purchasing the property, he produced wine under the Niebaum-Coppola label. When he purchased the former [[Inglenook Winery]] chateau in 1995,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/larryolmsted/2013/06/17/qa-francis-ford-coppola-talks-about-his-passion-for-wine/ |title=Q&A: Francis Ford Coppola Explains His Passion For Wine |magazine=Forbes |date=June 17, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514184821/http://www.forbes.com/sites/larryolmsted/2013/06/17/qa-francis-ford-coppola-talks-about-his-passion-for-wine/ |archive-date=May 14, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> he renamed the winery [[Rubicon Estate Winery]] in 2006. On April 11, 2011, Coppola acquired the Inglenook trademark<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Wine Spectator |accessdate=December 5, 2011 |url=http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/44791 |title=Coppola Reunites Inglenook Name with Its Vineyards |author=James Laube |date=April 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210181541/http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/44791 |archive-date=December 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> paying more, he said, for the trademark than he did for the entire estate<ref>{{cite web |last=Lechmere |first=Adam |url=http://www.decanter.com/news/wine-news/527661/francis-ford-coppola-to-return-inglenook-to-lower-alcohol |title=Francis Ford Coppola to return Inglenook to 'lower alcohol' |publisher=decanter.... |date=June 2, 2011 |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604004237/http://www.decanter.com/news/wine-news/527661/francis-ford-coppola-to-return-inglenook-to-lower-alcohol |archive-date=June 4, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> and announced that the estate would once again be known by its historic original name, Inglenook. Its grapes are now entirely organically grown.\n\n===Uptown Theater===\nGeorge Altamura, a real estate developer announced in 2003 that he had partnered with several people, including Francis Ford Coppola, in a project to restore the [[Uptown Theater (Napa, California)|Uptown Theater]] in downtown Napa, California in order to create a live entertainment venue.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Osborne |first=Heather |title=Altamura tells students he's headed for silver screen |journal=[[Napa Valley Register]] |publisher=Lee Enterprises, Inc. |location=Napa, CA |date=July 17, 2003 |url=http://napavalleyregister.com/news/altamura-tells-students-he-s-headed-for-silver-screen/article_c52489ee-0a00-55ff-a4de-b1972ce9f6a5.html |accessdate=September 2, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401134048/http://napavalleyregister.com/news/altamura-tells-students-he-s-headed-for-silver-screen/article_c52489ee-0a00-55ff-a4de-b1972ce9f6a5.html |archive-date=April 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Francis Ford Coppola Presents===\nCoppola is also the owner of [[Francis Ford Coppola Presents]], a [[lifestyle brand]] under which he markets goods from companies he owns or controls. It includes films and videos, resorts, cafes, a literary magazine, a line of pastas and pasta sauces called Mammarella Foods and a winery.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n====Winery====\nThe Francis Ford Coppola Winery near [[Geyserville, California]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.franciscoppolawinery.com/wine |title=Discover Our Wines &#124; Francis Ford Coppola Winery |publisher=Franciscoppolawinery.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518182304/http://www.franciscoppolawinery.com/wine |archivedate=May 18, 2013}}</ref> located on the former Chateau Souverain Winery,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Davis |first=Kip |authorlink= |title=Coppola's wine chateau also is family-friendly |journal=[[Napa Valley Register]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher=Lee Enterprises, Inc. |location=Napa, CA |date=October 15, 2010 |url=http://napavalleyregister.com/lifestyles/food-and-cooking/wine/article_57207bb0-d7fd-11df-aeef-001cc4c002e0.html |doi= |id= |accessdate=October 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018052041/http://napavalleyregister.com/lifestyles/food-and-cooking/wine/article_57207bb0-d7fd-11df-aeef-001cc4c002e0.html |archive-date=October 18, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> where he has opened a family-friendly facility, is influenced by the idea of the [[Tivoli Gardens]] in [[Copenhagen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.franciscoppolawinery.com/behind-the-scenes/vision |title=Vision |publisher=Franciscoppolawinery.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512045503/http://www.franciscoppolawinery.com/behind-the-scenes/vision |archivedate=May 12, 2013}}</ref> with swimming pools, [[bocce]] courts and a restaurant. The winery displays several of Coppola's [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] along with memorabilia from his movies, including [[Vito Corleone]]'s desk from ''[[The Godfather]]'' and a restored [[1948 Tucker Sedan]] as used in ''[[Tucker: The Man and His Dream]]''.\nIn October 2018, Coppola and family purchased the Vista Hills winery in Dayton, Oregon, and in 2019 renamed it Domaine de Broglie.\n\n====Resorts====\n[[File:Palazzo Coppola.JPG|thumb|''Palazzo Margherita'' in [[Bernalda]], owned by Coppola]]\nIncluded in the [[Francis Ford Coppola Presents]] [[lifestyle brand]] are several hotels and resorts around the world. The Blancaneaux Lodge in [[Belize]], which from the early 1980s was a family retreat until it was opened to the public in 1993 as a 20-room luxury resort<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coppolaresorts.com/blancaneaux |title=Blancaneaux Lodge, Belize Luxury Hotels \u2013 Blancaneaux Lodge at Coppola Resorts |publisher=Coppolaresorts.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517121242/http://www.coppolaresorts.com/blancaneaux |archive-date=May 17, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> and The Turtle Inn, in [[Placencia]], [[Belize]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coppolaresorts.com/turtleinn |title=Turtle Inn, Luxury Resorts in Belize \u2013 Turtle Inn at Coppola Resorts |publisher=Coppolaresorts.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526074414/http://www.coppolaresorts.com/turtleinn/ |archive-date=May 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> (both of which have won several prestigious awards including \"Travel + Leisure's World's Best: Best Resort in Central & South America\"); La Lancha in [[Lago Pet\u00e9n Itz\u00e1]], [[Guatemala]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coppolaresorts.com/lalancha |title=La Lancha, Boutique Hotels Guatemala \u2013 La Lancha at Coppola Resorts |publisher=Coppolaresorts.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517140703/http://www.coppolaresorts.com/lalancha |archive-date=May 17, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Jardin Escondido in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coppolaresorts.com/jardinescondido |title=Jardin Escondido |publisher=Coppolaresorts.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518035248/http://www.coppolaresorts.com/jardinescondido |archive-date=May 18, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Palazzo Margherita (Bernalda)|Palazzo Margherita]] in [[Bernalda]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coppolaresorts.com/palazzomargherita |title=Palazzo Margherita \u2013 Francis Ford Coppola Luxury Hotel in Bernalda Italy |publisher=Coppolaresorts.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526005714/http://www.coppolaresorts.com/palazzomargherita/ |archive-date=May 26, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Cafe and restaurant====\nIn San Francisco, Coppola owns a restaurant named [[American Zoetrope#Cafe Zoetrope|Cafe Zoetrope]], located in the Sentinel Building where American Zoetrope is based.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafecoppola.com/cafezoetrope/ |title=Cafe Zoetrope |publisher=Cafecoppola.com |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525154815/http://www.cafecoppola.com/cafezoetrope/ |archive-date=May 25, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It serves traditional Italian cuisine and wine from his [[Inglenook (Winery)|personal estate vineyard]]. For 14 years from 1994, Coppola co-owned the Rubicon restaurant in San Francisco along with [[Robin Williams]] and [[Robert De Niro]]. Rubicon closed in August 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/Rubicon-Shuttered_4283 |title=Rubicon Shuttered &#124; News &#124; News & Features |publisher=Wine Spectator |date= |accessdate=May 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814223416/http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/Rubicon-Shuttered_4283 |archive-date=August 14, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Literary publications====\nCoppola bought out the [[San Francisco]]-based magazine ''City'' in the 1970s, with the intent of publishing a \"service magazine\" that informed readers about sights and activities in selected cities.<ref name=\"Babitz\">{{cite book |last1=Babitz |first1=Eve |authorlink1=Eve Babitz |title=I Used To Be Charming |date=2019 |publisher=New York Review of Books |location=New York |isbn=9781681373799 |page=34 |chapter=All This and ''The Godfather'' Too}}</ref> The magazine was unsuccessful, and he lost $1.5&nbsp;million on this venture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theoscarsite.com/whoswho5/coppola_f.htm |title=Francis Ford Coppola(1939\u2013):Biography from Baseline's Encyclopedia of Film |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203053323/http://theoscarsite.com/whoswho5/coppola_f.htm |archive-date=December 3, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Coppola founded ''[[Zoetrope: All-Story]]'', a [[literary magazine]] devoted to [[short story|short stories]] and design. The magazine publishes fiction by emerging writers alongside more recognizable names, such as [[Woody Allen]], [[Margaret Atwood]], [[Haruki Murakami]], [[Alice Munro]], [[Don DeLillo]], [[Mary Gaitskill]], and [[Edward Albee]]; as well as essays, including ones from [[Mario Vargas Llosa]], [[David Mamet]], [[Steven Spielberg]], and [[Salman Rushdie]]. Each issue is designed, in its entirety, by a prominent artist, one usually working outside his / her expected field. Previous guest designers include [[Gus Van Sant]], [[Tom Waits]], [[Laurie Anderson]], [[Marjane Satrapi]], [[Guillermo del Toro]], [[David Bowie]], [[David Byrne]], and [[Dennis Hopper]]. Coppola serves as founding editor and publisher of ''All-Story''.\n\n==Other ventures==\nCoppola stated that ''The Godfather Part IV'' was never made as Mario Puzo died before they had a chance to write the film.<ref name=\"gq-magazine.co.uk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/entertainment/articles/2011-03/15/gq-film-godfather-part-four/mario-puzo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308111813/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/entertainment/articles/2011-03/15/gq-film-godfather-part-four/mario-puzo |url-status=dead |title=GQ |archivedate=March 8, 2012 |accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> [[Andy Garc\u00eda]] has since claimed the film's script was nearly produced.<ref name=\"gq-magazine.co.uk\"/>\n\nCoppola was the jury president at the [[1996 Cannes Film Festival]] and he also took part as a special guest at the 46th International [[Thessaloniki Film Festival]] in Greece.\n\nOver the years, Coppola has given contributions to several candidates of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], including [[Mike Thompson (California politician)|Mike Thompson]] and [[Nancy Pelosi]] for the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] and [[Barbara Boxer]] and [[Alan Cranston]] for the [[U.S. Senate]].<ref>[http://www.newsmeat.com/celebrity_political_donations/Francis_Ford_Coppola.php Francis Ford Coppola] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517081459/http://www.newsmeat.com/celebrity_political_donations/Francis_Ford_Coppola.php |date=May 17, 2008 }}. Newsmeat.</ref>\n\nCoppola appeared in a commercial for [[Suntory]] Reserve in 1980 alongside [[Akira Kurosawa]]; the commercial was filmed while Kurosawa was making ''[[Kagemusha]]'', which Coppola produced.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dekanta.com/take-a-look-at-these-japanese-whisky-commercials/ |title=See these Japanese whisky commercials! |first=Henry |last=Baldvin |date=February 16, 2016 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028222729/https://dekanta.com/take-a-look-at-these-japanese-whisky-commercials/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n* In the 2002 poll of the ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' publication, Coppola ranked No. 4 in the Directors' top ten directors of all time<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/directors-directors.html |title=The Directors' Top Ten Directors |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517155218/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/directors-directors.html |archivedate=May 17, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and No. 10 in the Critics' top ten directors of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/critics-directors.html |title=The Critics' Top Ten Directors |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819103438/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/topten/poll/critics-directors.html |archivedate=August 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* He featured at No. 17 in [[MovieMaker Magazine]]'s 25 most influential directors of all-time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filmsite.org/directors.html |title=25 Most Influential Directors of All-Time (ranked) \u2013 MovieMaker Magazine |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205055433/http://www.filmsite.org/directors.html |archive-date=February 5, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* He also ranked No. 9 in toptenreviews' list of top directors of all time<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.toptenreviews.com/directors/list_all_time_director.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322214928/http://movies.toptenreviews.com/directors/list_all_time_director.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 22, 2007 |title=Top Director All Time List |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2010}}</ref> and at No. 21 in [[Entertainment Weekly]]'s top 50 directors of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.listal.com/list/entertainment-weeklys-50-greatest-directors |title=Entertainment Weekly's 50 Greatest Directors |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930152431/http://www.listal.com/list/entertainment-weeklys-50-greatest-directors|archive-date=September 30, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Four of Coppola's films, ''[[The Godfather]]''; ''[[The Godfather Part II]]''; ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' and ''[[Patton (film)|Patton]]'' featured in the [[Writers Guild of America, West]] list of 101 greatest screenplays ever.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wga.org/content/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |title=101 Greatest Screenplays|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130121021/http://wga.org/content/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archivedate=November 30, 2010}}</ref>\n* Three of his films feature in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)|AFI's 100 Years...100 Movies]]: ''The Godfather'' (at #2), ''Apocalypse Now'' (at #28) and ''The Godfather Part II'' (at #32). ''The Godfather'' also ranks at No. 11 in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills]]. The following Coppola films were also nominated for the list: ''[[American Graffiti]]'' (1973) \u2013 Producer; ''[[The Conversation]]'' (1974) \u2013 Director/Producer/Screenwriter; ''[[Patton (film)|Patton]]'' (1970) \u2013 Screenwriter.\n* In 1991, he was honored with the Berlinale Camera at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\" />\n* In 1992, he was awarded a [[Golden Lion#Golden Lion \u2013 Honorary Award|Golden Lion \u2013 Honorary Award]] at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://www.superiorpics.com/francis_ford_coppola/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola |accessdate=October 18, 2010}}</ref>\n* In 1998, the [[Directors Guild of America]] honored him with a Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\" />\n* He was honored with a special 50th anniversary award for his impressive career at the 2002 [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\" />\n* The same year he received a gala tribute from [[Film Society of Lincoln Center]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\" />\n* In 2003, he was awarded a Lifetime Achievement Award at the [[Denver Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Francis Ford Coppola Awards\" />\n* He was given an honorary award at the [[2007 Antalya Golden Orange Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icvbbulletin.org/trnews32.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803023641/http://www.icvbbulletin.org/trnews32.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 3, 2008 |title=44th Antalya Golden Orange Film Festival Kicks off |date= |accessdate=October 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* In 2010, the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] decided to honor him with the [[Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award]] at the 2nd Governor's Awards in November.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altfg.com/blog/movie/francis-ford-coppola-kevin-brownlow-honorary-oscar-2011-thalberg-award/ |title=Oscar 2011: Francis Ford Coppola Gets Thalberg Award, Kevin Brownlow Gets Honorary Oscar |date= |accessdate=October 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110415012810/http://www.altfg.com/blog/movie/francis-ford-coppola-kevin-brownlow-honorary-oscar-2011-thalberg-award/ |archive-date=April 15, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The honor was bestowed on him on November 13, along with honorary Oscars to [[Jean-Luc Godard]], [[Kevin Brownlow]] and [[Eli Wallach]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gUXrrhIktLlv3ZZ0hymjsi5mnVug?docId=CNG.abcbb510a5c046dbf43a74a8c92b43c3.1f1 |title=Honorary Oscars for film legends Coppola, Godard |accessdate=December 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221124540/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gUXrrhIktLlv3ZZ0hymjsi5mnVug?docId=CNG.abcbb510a5c046dbf43a74a8c92b43c3.1f1 |archivedate=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n* On October 16, 2013, he was awarded a [[Praemium Imperiale]] in the theater/film category.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.praemiumimperiale.org/en/component/k2/item/299-zoetrope/299-zoetrope |title=Francis Ford Coppola, 2013 Theatre/ Film, Praemium Imperiale |accessdate=October 25, 2013|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610224550/http://www.praemiumimperiale.org/en/component/k2/item/299-zoetrope/299-zoetrope |archivedate=June 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAs0BJYhZCk |title=2013 Praemium Imperiale Press Conference |accessdate=October 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301072732/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KAs0BJYhZCk |archive-date=March 1, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r22gm5qHnHo |title=Francis Ford Coppola, 2013 Laureate of Theatre/Film |accessdate=October 25, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301081239/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r22gm5qHnHo |archive-date=March 1, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Coppola serves as the \"Honorary Consul H. E. Francis Ford Coppola\" in San Francisco for [[Belize]].<ref>[https://archive.today/20120720112517/http://www.belize.gov.bz/ct.asp?xItem=1703&ctNode=22&mp=26 ''Honorary Consulates of Belize''] from ''[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Belize)]]''</ref>\n* On October 1, 2014, Coppola was inducted into the California Hall of Fame by Governor Edmund G. \"Jerry\" Brown, Jr.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/watch/nbc-news-channel/meet-the-newest-california-hall-of-fame-inductees-336834115568 |title=Meet the Newest California Hall of Fame Inductees |access-date=October 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006090509/http://www.nbcnews.com/watch/nbc-news-channel/meet-the-newest-california-hall-of-fame-inductees-336834115568 |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Coppola is among only six people in Academy Award history to receive Oscars as a producer, director and screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eudesign.com/oscars/osc-curi.htm |title=OSCARS LISTS: RECORDS AND CURIOSITIES |first=Peter Hobbs of |last=EUdesign |website=www.eudesign.com |access-date=December 31, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225210206/http://www.eudesign.com/oscars/osc-curi.htm |archive-date=December 25, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On May 6, 2015, he was awarded the [[Princess of Asturias Award]] for the Arts, in [[Oviedo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fpa.es/en/communication/francis-ford-coppola-princess-of-asturias-award-for-the-arts.html?idCategoria=0&fechaDesde=&especifica=0&texto=&fechaHasta=&tipo=0 |title=Francis Ford Coppola, Princess of Asturias Award for the Arts \u2013 Communication \u2013 The Princess of Asturias Foundation |first=Developed with webControl CMS by Intermark |last=Tecnolog\u00edas |access-date=May 7, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518075235/http://www.fpa.es/en/communication/francis-ford-coppola-princess-of-asturias-award-for-the-arts.html?idCategoria=0&fechaDesde=&especifica=0&texto=&fechaHasta=&tipo=0 |archive-date=May 18, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On December 5, 2015, he was decorated with Gold Medal of the Order of Intellectual Efficience of Morocco, in [[Marrakech]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lobservateur.info/dossiers/francis-ford-coppola-pour-changer-le-monde-le-cinema-doit-etre-libere/ |title=Francis Ford Coppola \u00ab Pour changer le monde, le cin\u00e9ma doit \u00eatre... |date=December 21, 2015 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911044657/http://lobservateur.info/dossiers/francis-ford-coppola-pour-changer-le-monde-le-cinema-doit-etre-libere/ |archive-date=September 11, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* He is an honorary member of [[Phi Beta Kappa]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://depts.washington.edu/uwpbk/famous.htm |title=PBK Famous Members |website=depts.washington.edu |access-date=September 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018010047/http://depts.washington.edu/uwpbk/famous.htm |archive-date=October 18, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> through [[Hofstra University]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{{see|Francis Ford Coppola filmography}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Tonight for Sure]]'' (1962)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Bellboy and the Playgirls}}'' (1962)\n* ''[[Dementia 13]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[You're a Big Boy Now]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Finian's Rainbow (1968 film)|Finian's Rainbow]]'' (1968)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Rain People}}'' (1969)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Godfather}}'' (1972)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Conversation}}'' (1974)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Godfather Part II}}'' (1974)\n* ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[One from the Heart]]'' (1982)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Outsiders|The Outsiders (film)}}'' (1983)\n* ''[[Rumble Fish]]'' (1983)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Cotton Club|The Cotton Club (film)}}'' (1984)\n* ''[[Captain EO]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Peggy Sue Got Married]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Gardens of Stone]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Tucker: The Man and His Dream]]'' (1988)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Godfather Part III}}'' (1990)\n* ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Jack (1996 film)|Jack]]'' (1996)\n* ''{{sortname|The|Rainmaker|The Rainmaker (1997 film)}}'' (1997)\n* ''[[Youth Without Youth (film)|Youth Without Youth]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Tetro]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Twixt (film)|Twixt]]'' (2011)\n}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Francis Ford Coppola}}\n\n<!--Table is for nominations & wins received by films on which Coppola received either the director credit and/or writer credit-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Academy Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| BAFTA Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Golden Globe Awards\n|-\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1966\n| ''[[You're a Big Boy Now]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|3\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Is Paris Burning? (film)|Is Paris Burning?]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Finian's Rainbow (1968 film)|Finian's Rainbow]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|5\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Patton (film)|Patton]]''\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|2\n|-\n|1972\n|''[[The Godfather]]''\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|6\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[American Graffiti]]''\n|align=center|5\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|2\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1974\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|3\n|-\n|''[[The Conversation]]''\n|align=center|3\n|\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|4\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Godfather Part II]]''\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|6\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Apocalypse Now]]''\n|al