{"title_page": "OrbusNeich", "text_new": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = OrbusNeich |\n  logo   = OrbusNeich New Logo.jpg |\n  type   = [[Private company|Private]]|\n  founded = 2005|\n  hq_location      = [[Hong Kong]]|\n  areas_served = [[Florida, USA]] (R&D Headquarters), [[Shenzhen, China]] (Production & Product Development), Hoevelaken, Netherlands (Production Facility & Marketing and Sales)|\n  key_people = Teddy Chien (Founder), David Chien (Chairman of the Board), S. Addonizio (COO)|\n  industry       = [[Medical device|Medical Instruments & Supplies]]|\n  products = [[Stent]], Balloon|\n  num_employees = 500+|\n  homepage       = [http://www.orbusneich.com/ www.orbusneich.com]|\n}}\n\n'''OrbusNeich''' is a global company that designs, develops, manufactures and markets [[medical devices]] for the treatment of vascular diseases.<ref>(January 2010). \"OrbusNeich, a company providing stent technology for the future.\" [[European Heart Journal]].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, OrbusNeich received CE mark for the world's first and only dual therapy stent, the COMBO Dual Therapy Stent. The COMBO Stent features active  [[endothelial progenitor cell]] (EPC) capture technology, which promotes the accelerated natural healing of the vessel wall after the implantation of a stent.<ref>(July/August 2014). \"First Dual-Therapy Stent Nets CE Mark.\" Cardiology Today\u2019s Intervention.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOrbusNeich was founded in 2005, the result of a merger between Orbus Medical Technologies of Fort Lauderdale, Florida, and Hong Kong-headquartered Neich Medical.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOrbus Medical Technologies was founded in 1996. Orbus began as a medical device company and developed the R stent, a [[bare-metal stent]] with a novel dual helix design. With the development of the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Genous]] EPC capture technology in 2001, the company created the world's first pro-healing stent, the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nNeich International was incorporated in Hong Kong in 1979 as the sole distributor for [[Cordis (medical)|Cordis]] in the Asia-Pacific region, including Japan. Neich's operations and sales were absorbed into [[Johnson & Johnson]] with their acquisition of [[Cordis (medical)|Cordis]] in 1996. In 1999, Neich Medical re-entered [[interventional cardiology]] with investments in and agreements with Orbus Medical Technologies. 2001 saw the opening of manufacturing facility in Shenzhen, China.<ref>Levin, Stephen (March 2006). \"OrbusNeich: Tissue Engineering Meets Coronary Stents.\" IN VIVO.</ref>\n\n[[File:OrbusNeich exterior.JPG|thumb|upright|OrbusNeich]]\n\nAt TCT 2011, OrbusNeich's [[Dual therapy stent|Combo Dual Therapy Stent]], a [[coronary stent]] that combines the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Genous]] technology with an antiproliferative, [[sirolimus]] drug elution from a biodegradable polymer, was shown to be as effective as a  [[paclitaxel]]-eluting stent in controlling neointimal [[hyperplasia]].<ref>London, Susan (14 November 2011). \"Bioengineered, Sirolimus-Eluting Stent Found \u2018Safe,\u2019 and \u2018Effective.\u2019\" Cardiology News.</ref> In May 2013, the [[Dual therapy stent|Combo Dual Therapy Stent]] received [[CE marking|CE Mark]] approval in Europe. The product has also received regulatory approval in Hong Kong, Malaysia and other selected countries worldwide.<ref>http://www.medgadget.com/2013/05/orbusneich-combo-drug-eluting-stent-with-endothelial-progenitor-cell-capture.html</ref> Twelve-month results from the randomized REMEDEE trial for the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Combo Stent]] were published in [[Journal of the American College of Cardiology|JACC]] Cardiovascular Interventions.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=23523459 | doi=10.1016/j.jcin.2012.10.018 | volume=6 | title=The REMEDEE trial: a randomized comparison of a combination sirolimus-eluting endothelial progenitor cell capture stent with a paclitaxel-eluting stent | year=2013 | journal=JACC Cardiovasc Interv | pages=334\u201343 | last1 = Haude | first1 = M | last2 = Lee | first2 = SW | last3 = Worthley | first3 = SG | last4 = Silber | first4 = S | last5 = Verheye | first5 = S | last6 = Erbs | first6 = S | last7 = Rosli | first7 = MA | last8 = Botelho | first8 = R | last9 = Meredith | first9 = I | last10 = Sim | first10 = KH | last11 = Stella | first11 = PR | last12 = Tan | first12 = HC | last13 = Whitbourn | first13 = R | last14 = Thambar | first14 = S | last15 = Abizaid | first15 = A | last16 = Koh | first16 = TH | last17 = Den Heijer | first17 = P | last18 = Parise | first18 = H | last19 = Cristea | first19 = E | last20 = Maehara | first20 = A | last21 = Mehran | first21 = R}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.orbusneich.com/ OrbusNeich Web site]\n\n[[Category:Medical technology companies of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = OrbusNeich |\n  logo   = OrbusNeich New Logo.jpg |\n  type   = [[Private company|Private]]|\n  founded = 2005|\n  hq_location      = [[Hong Kong]]|\n  areas_served = [[Florida, USA]] (R&D Headquarters), [[Shenzhen, China]] (Production & Product Development), Hoevelaken, Netherlands (Production Facility & Marketing and Sales)|\n  key_people = Teddy Chien (Founder), David Chien (Chairman of the Board), S. Addonizio (COO)|\n  industry       = [[Medical device|Medical Instruments & Supplies]]|\n  products = [[Stent]], Balloon|\n  num_employees = 500+|\n  homepage       = [http://www.orbusneich.com/ www.orbusneich.com]|\n}}\n\n'''OrbusNeich''' is a global company that designs, develops, manufactures and markets [[medical devices]] for the treatment of vascular diseases.<ref>(January 2010). \"OrbusNeich, a company providing stent technology for the future.\" [[European Heart Journal]].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, OrbusNeich received CE mark for the world\u2019s first and only dual therapy stent, the COMBO Dual Therapy Stent. The COMBO Stent features active  [[endothelial progenitor cell]] (EPC) capture technology, which promotes the accelerated natural healing of the vessel wall after the implantation of a stent.<ref>(July/August 2014). \"First Dual-Therapy Stent Nets CE Mark.\" Cardiology Today\u2019s Intervention.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOrbusNeich was founded in 2005, the result of a merger between Orbus Medical Technologies of Fort Lauderdale, Florida, and Hong Kong-headquartered Neich Medical.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOrbus Medical Technologies was founded in 1996. Orbus began as a medical device company and developed the R stent, a [[bare-metal stent]] with a novel dual helix design. With the development of the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Genous]] EPC capture technology in 2001, the company created the world\u2019s first pro-healing stent, the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nNeich International was incorporated in Hong Kong in 1979 as the sole distributor for [[Cordis (medical)|Cordis]] in the Asia-Pacific region, including Japan. Neich\u2019s operations and sales were absorbed into [[Johnson & Johnson]] with their acquisition of [[Cordis (medical)|Cordis]] in 1996. In 1999, Neich Medical re-entered [[interventional cardiology]] with investments in and agreements with Orbus Medical Technologies. 2001 saw the opening of manufacturing facility in Shenzhen, China.<ref>Levin, Stephen (March 2006). \"OrbusNeich: Tissue Engineering Meets Coronary Stents.\" IN VIVO.</ref>\n\n[[File:OrbusNeich exterior.JPG|thumb|upright|OrbusNeich]]\n\nAt TCT 2011, OrbusNeich\u2019s [[Dual therapy stent|Combo Dual Therapy Stent]], a [[coronary stent]] that combines the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Genous]] technology with an antiproliferative, [[sirolimus]] drug elution from a biodegradable polymer, was shown to be as effective as a  [[paclitaxel]]-eluting stent in controlling neointimal [[hyperplasia]].<ref>London, Susan (14 November 2011). \"Bioengineered, Sirolimus-Eluting Stent Found \u2018Safe,\u2019 and \u2018Effective.\u2019\" Cardiology News.</ref> In May 2013, the [[Dual therapy stent|Combo Dual Therapy Stent]] received [[CE marking|CE Mark]] approval in Europe. The product has also received regulatory approval in Hong Kong, Malaysia and other selected countries worldwide.<ref>http://www.medgadget.com/2013/05/orbusneich-combo-drug-eluting-stent-with-endothelial-progenitor-cell-capture.html</ref> Twelve-month results from the randomized REMEDEE trial for the [[Genous Bio-engineered Stent|Combo Stent]] were published in [[Journal of the American College of Cardiology|JACC]] Cardiovascular Interventions.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=23523459 | doi=10.1016/j.jcin.2012.10.018 | volume=6 | title=The REMEDEE trial: a randomized comparison of a combination sirolimus-eluting endothelial progenitor cell capture stent with a paclitaxel-eluting stent | year=2013 | journal=JACC Cardiovasc Interv | pages=334\u201343 | last1 = Haude | first1 = M | last2 = Lee | first2 = SW | last3 = Worthley | first3 = SG | last4 = Silber | first4 = S | last5 = Verheye | first5 = S | last6 = Erbs | first6 = S | last7 = Rosli | first7 = MA | last8 = Botelho | first8 = R | last9 = Meredith | first9 = I | last10 = Sim | first10 = KH | last11 = Stella | first11 = PR | last12 = Tan | first12 = HC | last13 = Whitbourn | first13 = R | last14 = Thambar | first14 = S | last15 = Abizaid | first15 = A | last16 = Koh | first16 = TH | last17 = Den Heijer | first17 = P | last18 = Parise | first18 = H | last19 = Cristea | first19 = E | last20 = Maehara | first20 = A | last21 = Mehran | first21 = R}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.orbusneich.com/ OrbusNeich Web site]\n\n[[Category:Medical technology companies of China]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OrbusNeich"}
